{ Welcome everyone to this joint venture of ours in the Sicilian Alapin.   This is an introduction to the complete Alapin repertoire for White. The idea of this repertoire is to provide everything one needs to know after }
1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ Why the Alapin?   The Sicilian Defense is often an agony for White because of its insurmountable variations and lines. But there is a simple solution to this big problem, the Alapin!   This hugely underestimated and frequently ignored line possesses fearsome weapons that were grossly unexplored until now.   Why the Alapin again?   Being fully aware that there is already a Chessable course on the Alapin by GM John Sebastian Christiansen, we felt that it was not enough, as Black could follow some well-known already-played game and get a comfortable position.   While we ensured to mention when and why we deviated from GM Sebastian’s suggestion, we aimed to bypass the traditional theory at the earliest and get a new practical position for White, where Black will have numerous ways to go wrong. Even if Black plays precisely, our position will still remain practically attractive.   We will create our own theory and not follow the traditional path unless the existing theory is good enough to get a great position.   Do we have an advantage in all lines?   If any author tries to sell a course by saying he has found an advantage for White in all openings/lines, this would be a blatant lie in modern times when engines are proving equality in various mainlines. That is why it is much easier to write a bulletproof course from the Black side😊. We claim to pose maximum practical problems for Black over the board in any tournament game.   What about the move orders headache and transposition issues?  The major problem with most of the existing Alapin material is the confusion of move orders when Black has many permutations and combinations. It is easy to get drowned and confused by this. The course is nicely structured in a setup format. For instance, in the 2...d5 lines, all ...Bg4 systems are in one file. Likewise, ...Bf5, ...g6, and ...e5 lines are broken setup-wise and not scattered all over, which makes it trivial to learn our setups against each system.   What if our opponents are fully prepared with modern theory in the Alapin?   It will not help them at all since our signature style is to build our new creative direction, challenging the traditional systems and avoiding the mainlines at the earliest possibility. We will not follow modern theory, but modern theory will evolve with our course😊.  How to deal if our opponents follow Anish's Najdorf course or Sam Shankland's suggestion to the Alapin in his Rauzer course?   How attractive it sounds to come up with something new that both of them did not analyze as early as move 5? Our opponents will be on their own irrespective of what course or modern theory they follow.   So with no further delay, let's get started to see what we are bringing into the course😊.  Rustam & Surya   PS: This is Surya here. I would like to personally add and justify why I am writing a course on a line that I never played as White! I lacked clarity as Black in the Alapin against a well-prepared opponent, and my default against such players would be to play Anti Alapin by not playing 1... c5 😋.   Anyhow, Rustam and I go back a long way. We have known each other since 1994, but our professional work started together during Anand's World Championship matches when we were part of Team Anand. Both of us can proudly say that Anand always won his matches @@StartBracket@@Against Kramnik, Topalov, and Gelfand@@EndBracket@@ when we were there on his team😊.   A couple of months back, I got a call from Rustam, and he said he is making a course on the Alapin and would like me on board. Without a second thought, I jumped in as I was fully aware of Rustam's capability to turn any line into a dangerous weapon and find new ideas at the earliest possibility.   Also, I was keen to learn a new opening from the White side and get clarity on how to play from the Black side. Thus the journey began, and we created many new systems for White that were unheard of, and we are confident that soon these will become mainline😊.   So, along with the readers, I would also be employing these new ideas in my tournament games and look forward to making this journey together😊. }
*

