1. e4
{ The introduction files will be a starter to give a glimpse of what awaits in the main course.   We have selected a few lines to show how early we are deviating and creating our own path. }
1... c5
{ One of two moves at Black's disposal that fights White's plan to establish a central superiority with  2.d4!   The Sicilian Defense also presents a lot of headaches for White players because they feel the pressure to learn all the variations within @@StartBracket@@Najdorf, Sveshnikov, early Sveshnikov, Richter-Rauzer, Taimanov, Kan, Dragon, Accelerated Dragon@@EndBracket@@ Feeling dizzy yet? We are just getting started!  Fortunately for us, there is a perfect antidote that takes care of all the lines in one shot. }
2. c3
{ The Alapin! History goes back to the late 19th century when the Russian master Semyon Alapin employed it regularly. Later many World Champions and strong players, including the living legend Magnus, tried it.  Even after the shortest possible explanations, we can see the logic behind this move. White insists on his ambitious plan of building up the powerful pawn center with d4. Another critical point for us to understand is that after  2.c3  , the psychological initiative firmly shifts to White!  When Black prepares 1... c5, 95% of the attention is given to sharp lines after  2.Nf3  , most often followed by mind-boggling complications. The Alapin is thus underestimated and frequently ignored!  We can confidently say this as we have played Sicilian from childhood and compared to  2.Nf3  our notes/options in  2.c3  are significantly limited. In this way, our  2.c3  repertoire ensures that we will have an opening battle on our territory and an overwhelming advantage in opening knowledge.  Now let's see what Black can do to counter White's main threat - d4! }
2... Qa5
{ Many GMs, including a bunch of 2700+ players, also tried this move frequently to surprise White. Black stops White from playing d4-cxd4-cxd4 due to the pin. }
3. g3
{ Out of approximately 1500 games that reached this position, only 50 games continued this way.   As promised, we will take our opponents into a lesser-known area as early as possible. We want to go Bg2-Ne2-O-O and play d4, claiming Black's queen is misplaced on a5. }
3... Nc6 4. Bg2 { Continuing with our plan. } 4... g6 5. Ne2
{ Within the first five moves, we reached a position that has been tried only once at the GM level, and in total, eight games got here.   We are confident those who have not studied this course will be out of their preparation already😊.   In the main course, you can find further explanations. }
