1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6
{ The third most popular move in the position. Black prepares ...Nf6 and is unwilling to get hit with ...e5. }
3. d4 { Our standard response unless Black stops it. } 3... Nf6
{ The main move, Black continues with his plan of playing Nf6 without allowing e5 with impunity. }
4. dxc5 { The first sign of sidestepping the main theory of  4.Bd3 } 4... Nc6
{ This is the big idea for Black and is the most popular move in the position.  By blocking any Qa4 checks, Black now threatens to take on e4 and welcomes White to take  5.cxd6  when after  5...Nxe4  Black gets an excellent fighting position.   The most popular move here is to play  5.f3  when Black plays the unexpected  5...d5  and claims both white knights will be misplaced as they lack their natural developing square of f3 and c3. }
5. Qd3
{ Our signature style of creating our own system, bypassing the mainline, is at your service😊.   From about 15000 games with 2... d6, we are now looking at three GM level games which are almost unheard of, and in total, 14 times this position is reached.   What is the big idea? We protect the e4-pawn without committing f3 to ensure our knight on g1 won't have any trouble getting developed.   Playing  5...d5  makes no sense here as we will take it  6.exd5  , and our knight will come on f3.   Black must reluctantly enter the queenless middlegame with  5...dxc5  , and you will see in the main course how easy it is to play from the White side and how unattractive it is for Black to get such a position out of the opening. }
