1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6
{ There are two main moves in this position  2...Nf6  and  2...d5  .  Purely by the number of games,  2...d5  is more popular, but in modern times we get to see  2...Nf6  played more often.  We found a lot of new exciting ideas for White, changing the evaluation and the direction of play in most lines. Moves like  2...a6  ,  2...b6  ,  2...g6  , and  2...d6  give easy play when even computers can not maintain equality for Black. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3
{ Most flexible. Now Black has a variety of moves, and each of them is covered nicely in the course, again following our style of getting a fresh position as and when necessary.  We don't need to deviate unnecessarily when existing theory gives a comfortable advantage. }
4... d6
{ Let's get a glimpse of what you might expect in the course by seeing this move which is suggested as bulletproof by many experts.   Anish gave this direction in his Najdorf course and Sam in his Rauzer course. We can expect to get this line over the board frequently. }
5. Bb5+
{ The first shock to our opponents who will be following Anish and Sam's course. They do not have this rare move covered. It was seen only once in GM-level classical games; in total, 30 unheard games reached this position. }
5... Bd7
{ 5...Nc6  is also covered, obviously for the sake of completion, but this is Black's most critical response. }
6. Bc4
{ Another blow of surprise. Now we are talking about just six games that reach this position. We are in move six, by the way😊.    The bishop on d7 gets misplaced frequently as the b8 knight belongs to c6, and the bishop goes to b7. We can explain in detail here, but let this introduction just be the trailer to show how quickly we are taking the game and our opponents into new territory. Everything is analyzed methodically and explained nicely in the course.   We do not believe in memorization without understanding the core of the position. Readers can be assured about the explanation throughout the course and not just see a bunch of computer moves😊. }
