1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5
{ The most-played move in the position. Black grabs the center immediately, but it comes at the cost of exposing the queen to the center.   Every sensible move is considered and analyzed thoroughly in the main files; here, we will see some trailers of a few lines that are randomly picked. }
3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4
{ As mentioned earlier, we have created the chapters system-wise, avoiding any move order confusion.   All Bf5 variations @@StartBracket@@with/without Nf6/Nc6/cxd4@@EndBracket@@ are under Bf5 setups. The same applies to the Bg4 setups, g6 setups, e5 setups, etc.   It makes it simpler to study the lines without getting the slightest doubt about the move orders and transpositional issues.   Let us see one line here as a starter to understand what waits for us in the main course😊. }
4... e6 { One of the many different ways Black can play. } 5. Nf3
{ This position is seen more frequently after the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.c3  d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  5.d4  move order. }
5... Nc6 { Quite a popular position, with about 4500 games played here. } 6.
Na3
{ One of the standard ways to develop the knight when Black omits to cxd4-cxd4. }
6... Qd8
{ Black makes prophylaxis against Bc4 and Nb5 ideas. Once again a well-known way for Black to play against this line.   Recently in the 2022 Sharjah Open, Arjun Erigaisi played this line as Black. }
7. Be3
{ From a position where more than 200 games are played, we played a move that was played only once in a tournament game! Arjun was hit by this rare move in Sharjah Open against GM Deep Sengupta. }
7... cxd4 { The obvious way for Black not to allow dxc5 ideas. } 8. Nxd4 Bxa3
{ Arjun opted for the most logical move. After taking  8...Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Qxd4  10.Bxd4  Black cannot take on a3 as the g7-pawn hangs, and the rook on h8 drops. }
9. Nxc6 Qc7
{ It would have been wiser to accept a depressing endgame with  9...Qxd1  10.Rxd1  bxc6  11.bxa3  , but Arjun goes for the most fighting response. }
10. Ne5
{ A great novelty that kills the line and gets White a winning advantage.   Imagine if GM Deep Sengupta was prepared, or if he could find the tactical skirmish here over the board; he would get a winning position against one of the most talented junior players with a 2700+ rating within the first ten moves!   The amount of work/effort people put in the Alapin is far less compared to other mainlines, and even such a strong young player and theoretician like Arjun can get a losing position as early as move ten! }
10... Bxb2
{ Not the best move, but clearly, both players would not think for a second about the obvious evaluation after  10...Qxe5  11.Qa4  followed by Qxa3, giving White an indisputable advantage. }
11. Bb5+ Ke7 12. O-O
{ We sacrifice the rook and the knight on e5.   Let us keep the suspense by not giving further details about this position but just mentioning that Black does not save this game anymore.   What are you waiting for? Welcome to our course! Let's move on to the next chapter now 😊 }
