1. e4 c5 2. c3 Qa5
{ This unique way of stopping White from playing d4 @@StartBracket@@as White cannot take cxd4 due to the pin@@EndBracket@@ is pretty popular. Movsesian and Alekseenko have played this variation several times. Also, we can see players like Rapport, Svidler, Andreikin, Korobov, etc., have tried this system a few times. }
3. g3
{ The first relatively rare move 😊. As you will see throughout the course, we will be finding new/rare ideas very early and creating our own theories. The most popular move is to play  3.Nf3  here.  White's moves are simple Bg2/Ne2/O-O and d4. Black cannot stop this, and he will have to justify the odd queen placement on a5. }
3... Nc6
{ 3...Nf6  allows an extra  4.e5  , which is pretty strong. White can also simply play  4.Bg2  , and after  4...Nc6  , we will get to the position that we shall see from 3... Nc6 move order. }
4. Bg2 { We continue with our normal plan of finishing castle first. } 4... g6
{ Black brings maximum control towards the d4-square. } 5. Ne2
{ O-O and d4 coming soon! } 5... Bg7
{ Black is trying his best to bring as much control as possible to stop d4. }
6. O-O { White is now ready to play d4. } 6... e5 { Trying to stop d4. } 7. d4
{ White strikes in the center anyway! Black's main problem is his king, who remains in the center. }
7... exd4 8. Bf4
{ As usual, development is the key here. The bishop heads for d6. } 8... Nge7
{ Black finally gets to castle but White now gets a lovely spot on d6. } 9. Bd6
O-O 10. Nd2
{ Black's pieces are dominated. He faces a gloomy defense. White's bishop on d6 is not easy to remove, while the threats of Nb3/Nc4 are incredibly annoying. }
