1. e4 c5 2. c3 e5
{ A relatively new approach. Black weakens the d5-square but does get some central control in return, making d2-d4 more difficult. }
3. Nf3
{ Bringing more support to d4 and attacking e5 is the most natural way White can continue. }
3... Nc6 { Otherwise White gets d4 easily. } 4. Bc4
{ A nice developing move, targeting both weaknesses in Black's position, the d5-square and the f7-pawn. }
4... Nf6
{ By far the sharpest response and Black's only hope for equality. Other moves accept being worse. }
5. Ng5 { The most direct approach to hit on f7. } 5... d5
{ Otherwise, Black can as well resign. } 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Qh5
{ White is forcing Black to walk a very narrow path.  The tempting  7.Nxf7  Kxf7  8.Qf3  Ke6  leads to unnecessary complications where Black has his resources. }
7... g6 8. Qf3 Qxg5
{ Surprisingly, the awful  8...Be6  was played several times, and Black is utterly busted after  9.Nxe6  fxe6  10.d3  when there is zero compensation against the double bishop and having a broken pawn structure. }
9. Bxd5
{ White keeps forcing Black to find the only moves to stay in the game. } 9...
Nd8 10. O-O { Simple chess, Black has to deal with the threat of d4! } 10...
Qf5
{ Black, for obvious reasons, wants to trade queens for his king's safety. }
11. Qe3
{ White is not interested in the queen trade when Black is hugely behind in development. }
11... Be6 { Offering further piece trade. } 12. Bf3
{ White keeps more pieces on the board since Black's king remains in the center. }
12... Nc6 13. d3 Rd8
{ A very natural plan to put pressure on d3, but Black still ends with huge problems. }
14. Be4
{ White wants to take on c6 eventually to break Black's pawn structure, but this intermediate move forces Black's queen to go to a worse square. }
14... Qh5 15. Bxc6+
{ Creating very serious pawn weaknesses in the opponent's structure. } 15...
bxc6 16. Nd2
{ With Ne4 coming next and having such a vulnerable pawn structure, Black will sustain some damage here. }
