[Black "2...e6 3.d4 d5 Main Lines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6
{ This move intends to fight for the center by playing d5 next. } 3. d4
{ Given a chance, this move is our automatic reply. } 3... d5
{ The normal continuation. Black strikes in the center without including cxd4 to deprive White of playing Nc3. }
4. exd5
{ The most principled continuation. We want to point out that the chances of getting 3...d5 position is a bit rare compared to other lines if White wants he can directly transpose into the main line of the French Advance with  4.e5   So a player who started with a Sicilian and then switched to the mainline of the French Advance is not something common. If your repertoire against the French is the Advanced variation and you are already happy with it, then you can skip this entire chapter and transpose with  4.e5  .  However, we stick to the Alapin in our recommendations. }
4... exd5
{ 4...Qxd5  will transpose to the Alapin 2... d5 segment, which we will examinehere.  The position after  4...exd5  is essential for us to understand. In most cases, White will take on c5, resulting in a position with an isolated pawn on d5. Our task is to exchange some pieces, block the pawn firmly with a knight on  d4  , and win the endgame.  In most Alapin lines, White plays with the isolated pawn, not against it. The great variety of possible structures arising from the Alapin will improve your feel for many different positions and make you a better player, at least, that's the general idea 😊.  An important trick to know is that after  4...cxd4  5.Bb5  Bd7  White has the cute  6.dxe6  Bxb5  7.exf7  Kxf7  8.Qb3  and the b5-bishop falls when White retains a material advantage. }
5. Bb5+
{ Simple chess. White goes for fastest development, with Nf3 and O-O to follow in short succession.   And as for having maybe to exchange that bishop - we don't really mind some exchanges, as they bring us closer to the d5-pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6
{ All alternatives before this move are covered under the sidelines.   Black finishes his development and does not mind wasting a tempo with Bd6-Bxc5 in case White takes on c5. }
7. dxc5
{ Whenever Black moves the bishop from f8, it makes sense to take on c5 to force Black to waste a tempo. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ This is the most popular setup for Black. He makes sure there are no checks with Re1, and he can castle next. }
9. Nbd2
{ The standard developing square for the knight, heading d4 via b3 and, in the process, gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
9... O-O { 9...Bb6  10.Nb3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. } 10. Nb3
{ At this point, both bishop retreats on b6 and d6 are almost equally popular, and we should be ready for both. }
10... Bb6 { Keeping maximum control on the d4-square. } 11. Re1
{ We have seen this particular theme several times. White intends to play Be3 next.   Any piece trade usually benefits White as long as Black's structure remains weak with the isolated pawn. }
11... Bg4
{ Black continues to fight for the d4-square by pinning the knight on f3. } 12.
Be3
{ The standard follow-up of Re1. Once again, it is safe to stop our preparation here, but let us see a bit more to understand the upcoming middlegame. }
12... Re8 { This was tried a few times but after... } 13. h3 Bh5 14. Rc1
{ A new and strong idea when White clearly states that he is not in a rush and plans to opt for Rc2-Rd2 in the future to put more pressure on the d5-pawn. }
