{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6
{ This move intends to fight for the center by playing d5 next. } 3. d4
{ Given a chance, this move is our automatic reply. } 3... cxd4
{ This dubious move, abandoning the fight for the center at once, is strangely popular. Black just gets a bad version of the French Defense. }
4. cxd4 Nf6
{ Black is postponing d5, but sooner or later, Black will have to play it anyway. Once the knight is kicked from f6, it will usually find itself on awkward squares. }
5. Nc3
{ The disadvantage of including cxd4 is apparent here as White gets to play Nc3, which is the ideal square of the knight right now. }
5... d5 { Striking in the center with the idea of getting the knight to e4. }
6. e5
{ Of course, we are not giving up the center. Instead, we advance further to gain more space and push back the knight on f6. }
6... Ne4
{ This looks more natural, as after  6...Nfd7  7.Qg4  Black will find difficulties developing in the kingside, and White will enjoy more space and better development. }
7. Bd3
{ Time is essential in chess. White quickly finishes his development, and welcomes the prospect of the b2-pawn strengthening the pawn center. }
7... Nxc3
{ After  7...Bb4  8.Nge2  White will castle soon, and the knight on e4 will be back in trouble. }
8. bxc3
{ The seeming weakness of the c3-pawn is deceptive. It's easy for White to defend and makes White's center unassailable. }
8... Qc7 9. Bd2
{ Just defending the pawn.  9.Ne2  was also possible, but the knight, in fact, has different plans. }
9... Nc6 10. Nh3
{ Keeping the square g4 available for the queen and looking at f4 or g5, this knight is very flexible.   Black has a lack of space, worse development, worse center, and on top of everything now; his king will also not find a good place to hide. }
