1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6
{ The third most popular move in the position after  2...d5  and  2...Nf6  . However, this move does little to stop White's expansion in the center with d2-d4. }
3. d4
{ We won't hesitate to grab the center, of course. Now Black has various moves, and most of them don't even pretend to be fighting for equality. }
3... Nf6
{ The main move. Black develops with a tempo. It makes more sense to not include cxd4 when White gets to play Nc3. }
4. dxc5
{ There is nothing wrong with  4.Bd3  , with the idea of Nf3-O-O, which gives White a slightly better position. We liked this idea which is less popular than  4.Bd3  .  This line forces Black into an uncomfortable, queenless middlegame where White plays for only two results. }
4... Nc6
{ The main move.  4...Nxe4  fails to  5.Qa4  when the knight on e4 falls. } 5.
Qd3
{ As typically seen throughout our repertoire, we are not big fans of following the mainline 😊.   White is happy to get the queenless middlegame even at the cost of a tempo. }
5... dxc5
{ Black has very little choice here. Either he can enter the queenless middlegame or try to break the center with d5. }
6. Qxd8+
{ Even at the cost of one tempo @@StartBracket@@Qd3-Qxd8@@EndBracket@@, this queenless middlegame is pleasant for White. }
6... Kxd8
{ Trying to claim that the king will be better placed on c7. However, that is not the main issue Black has here, as we will see. }
7. f3
{ It might look like Black has the lead in development, but in reality, Black's knights are entirely misplaced on their standard squares as White's pawns on f3 and c3 control them nicely.   Meanwhile, White will now build up pressure on the queenside. Let us see how the game could proceed here and why engines are so excited as White here. }
7... Kc7
{ The major problem in Black's position is that he lacks any good square for his minor pieces. }
8. Be3 b6 9. a4
{ Imagine playing this position as Black and think about a good way to develop your pieces. It doesn't look bright for Black, right?😊 }
9... Be6
{ 9...g6  10.Bc4  was annoying for the f7-pawn, and @@StartFEN@@r1b2b1r/p1k1pppp/1pn2n2/2p5/P3P3/2P1BP2/1P4PP/RN2KBNR b KQ a3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...e6  blocks the bishop on c8. }
10. Na3 a6 11. Ne2
{ White will slowly but surely finish his development, while Black struggles to find ideal squares for his minor pieces. }
