[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 g6
{ The fifth most popular move in the position with more than 7000 games already in the database. Black gives away the center but plans to fight against it with the help of the g7-bishop. }
3. d4
{ Our move remains most natural and straightforward. We grab the center at the first chance. }
3... cxd4
{ 3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  g6  which we will examine thoroughly in the main coursehere. }
4. cxd4 d5 { The only reasonable way to counter White's central control. } 5.
e5 { The simplest way to gain more space and a better position. } 5... Bg7
{ Black plans to castle quickly. } 6. Nc3
{ White delays Nf3 to stop Black from playing Bg4. The light-squared bishop lacks any decent square to develop. }
6... Nc6
{ The most popular move. Black goes for the d4-pawn and waits for White to play Nf3 and then opt for Bg4. }
7. Bb5
{ White immediately pins the knight and keeps a strategic threat of taking on c6 timely. }
7... Nh6
{ Playing  7...a6  only helps White to play  8.Bxc6  , which he would like to play anyways at some point. This way, Black also loses the  option of getting any Ba6 ideas in the future. }
8. h3
{ Simple and logical. This small move kills the knight on h6 and the bishop on c8. Not only does it controls the g4-square, but in the future, it is also ready to pounce with g4 if one of the minor pieces lands on f5. }
8... O-O 9. Nf3 f6
{ Black tries to break the center rapidly. Playing slow with  9...Bf5  10.O-O  Be4  doesn't help when White gets a nice tempo with  11.Ng5  and keeps his center solid. }
10. O-O
{ White can ignore the threat on e5 as the knight on h6 will be hanging after the mass trade on e5. }
10... Nf7 { Building more pressure on e5. } 11. exf6 exf6
{ After  11...Bxf6  12.Re1  Black gets a permanent weak pawn structure. Even if he manages to break with e5 still, the pawn on d5 will become weak. White gets an overwhelming advantage. }
12. Re1
{ With Ba4-b3 coming, Black's position looks terrible when he must take care of the pawn on d5, and his bishops lack good squares. }
