[Black "2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 - ...Bf5 Setups"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Bf5
{ We will be seeing all sorts of Bf5 setups in the main course. There are various transpositions and move orders, but we will ensure utmost clarity and no room for confusion.   The primary idea of the Bf5 setup is to play e6 without locking the bishop on c8. There are also additional ideas with Bxb1 to stop Nc3 ideas after cxd4-cxd4 that we will examine later in the main course. }
5. Nf3
{ White's main argument here is against the queen on d5, which can be attacked in the future, and Black's lack of development on the kingside. }
5... Nc6
{ We could reach the same position from the 4... Nc6 move order also. Black ignores the kingside for now and increases pressure on the d4-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ Bringing more support to the d4-pawn and threatening to play c4-d5 next, as Qe4 doesn't come with a check anymore. }
6... Nf6
{ The most popular move in the position. Black develops normally and intends to play e6 next. }
7. Bb5
{ Our signature way of approaching an opening. Surprise your opponent as early as possible. Create your own theory. Ideas remain similar to ensure we spend as little energy as possible against the sidelines.  Finally, most importantly, we will have clarity in all these rare positions while our opponent will have to navigate the intricacies over the board. This is our identical approach for world championship match preparation while helping Anand. We can also proudly say that we never saw Anand lose while we were on his team😊.   7.Na3  is the big mainline. Our idea of  7.Bb5  is to go for the king as early as possible, with c4-Nc3 coming next. }
7... cxd4
{ Black can't afford to allow White to play c4 that easily.  7...e6  8.c4  allows White to develop freely with Nc3 next, and Black's king in the center suffers.   7...a6  8.c4  Qd7  9.Bxc6  gives Black a sad choice of either breaking the structure by recapturing with the b-pawn or taking with the queen and allowing White to grab more space with d5 while Black's king, as usual, remains in the center. In either case, White is significantly better.   Finally, after  7...O-O-O  8.Qa4  the threats of c4/Bxc6 give Black a losing position when his king is unsafe on the queenside. }
8. c4
{ An important detail. First, we harass the queen before taking on d4 with the knight. }
8... Qd6
{ A sensible retreat to keep the d7-square free for the light-squared bishop.  8...Qd7  9.Nxd4  forces Black to give up the bishop pair, and he can't show enough compensation. }
9. Qxd4
{ 9.Nxd4  Bd7  wasn't giving much to White, although definitely playable.   By playing  9.Qxd4  , we exploit Black's queen's position on d6 and give a strategic threat of Qxd6 to break Black's pawn structure. }
9... a6
{ 8...Qc7  allows a fine positional move  9.Qe5  when Black finds it difficult to avoid getting into pressure or bad structure. }
10. Qxd6 { First, we break the pawn structure. } 10... exd6 11. Bxc6+
{ A counterintuitive move. We would love to play  11.Ba4  , but after  11...Rc8  it would be tough to deal with Bd3 and, in some cases, a future Nb4 threat once Black unpins himself.  By taking on c6, we give up the bishop but exploit the lead in development. }
11... bxc6
{ It's not like Black got an amazing structure😊.  Now all the pawns on the queenside can become a potential target. }
12. Nc3
{ White will go O-O-O-Nd4-Rhe1-Na4 etc.   Black finds it uncomfortable to deal with his weak queenside pawns and king in the center with a bad dark-squared bishop. }
