1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  or  5...Nc6  doesn't have any independent value, and it will soon transpose to either 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3 Bg4
{ One of the most popular ways to play Bg4 setups. Black increases pressure on the d4-pawn as fast as possible while keeping the Nc3 option unavailable for White. }
6. dxc5
{ Like in all the 4... Nf6 variations, our response remains the same.   It makes the preparation easier when we have similar responses/plans. Thus it is convenient not to change the plans for every move unless it is really needed.   If Black takes cxd4 and then opts for Bg4, we go for Nc3 ideas. If he plays directly Bg4, we take on c5 with the pawn. This is irrespective of 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 }
6... Qxd1+
{ The best choice for Black. This time taking on c5 is not ideal as after Be3, the queen doesn't have the safe retreat on c7. }
7. Kxd1
{ Our game plan remains crystal clear. We are a pawn up and we tell Black 'Please show us your compensation for the same.' }
7... e5
{ This move is a clear mistake and also the most popular move in the position, and played by many GMs 😊.  Black gives a double threat of e4 and Bxc5 but just like the 4... Nf6 variation here, also, the threat of e4 is nothing but an illusion. }
8. b4
{ We are not worried about any ghosts of e4 or O-O-O ideas. It is essential to protect the pawn on c5. }
8... e4
{ We have seen this idea several times, and by now, our reply must be automatic. }
9. h3 Bxf3+
{ Since Black cannot capture the knight, he tries to take the pawn and balance the material.   9...Bh5  10.g4  doesn't lead anywhere, and White keeps the extra pawn. }
10. gxf3 exf3 11. Nd2
{ White is completely winning as Black loses the pawn on f3, and White will still retain his double bishop advantage and keeps the extra pawn. }
