{ Almost 3000 games have been played, and only about 80 games this rare move was tried.   With our signature attempt, we deviate from the most popular path and take the game to lesser-explored areas. White plans to play Bc4 next. }
6... cxd4
{ The main move. This has to be the logical reaction against Nbd2 to disturb White's main idea of Bc4. }
7. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate developing move before dealing with the pawn on d4. }
7... Qa5
{ This move is rare, and White gets a nice position with obvious moves. } 8.
Nxd4 Nf6
{ Taking on d4 to play against IQP would be harakiri, and after  8...Bxd4  9.cxd4  Nf6  10.O-O  O-O  11.Nf3  Black will miss the g7-bishop badly with the presence of the queens.  In the silicon world, such positions are already lost. White's advantage is obvious due to the lead in development and having a pair of bishops. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 { Developing with a tempo again! } 10... Qc7 11. h3
{ Black's g7-bishop does not have a good diagonal, and its existing diagonal is nicely blocked. The bishop on c8 doesn't have a good square.   It is not easy to develop the queenside pieces  11...Nc6  12.Nxc6  forces Black to break his pawn structure since taking with the queen would lose the pawn on e7. }
