1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... d6
{ Black attacks the e5-pawn at the first chance.   Anish recommends this move in his Najdorf course from the Black side. He also refutes the ideas given in Sebastian's Chessable course from the White side. Our signature strategy is coming into place right now. The current position is super common with many different tries.   A huge surprise is waiting for Black on the next move, which is exceptionally rare. }
5. Bb5+
{ We provoke Bd7 before playing Bc4.  To understand the main reasoning behind it, we need to understand the mainline of  5.Bc4  Nb6  6.Bb3  c4  7.Bc2  . In this position, Black's main move is  7...dxe5  8.Nxe5  Qd5!  attacking d5 and g2.  With the bishop on d7, Black will miss Qd5 move at the end.  More than 1500 games played in this position, and only in two GM level games 5.Bb5 was played. }
5... Bd7 { The most logical move for Black. } 6. Bc4
{ So our claim is compared to the 5.Bc4 line, the bishop on d7 is misplaced. It can be seen in the  6...Nb6  line.  There are only six games that have reached this position so far. Once our course is out, the numbers will increase rapidly😊. }
6... e6
{ You are most likely to face this move more often than  6...Nb6  . Black would like to take advantage of this extra Bd7 move and get Bc6 faster. }
7. d4
{ This is the first position where we give Black various choices that look similar, with or without computers. Funnily enough with the bishop on c8, also we get a position that is part of our repertoire.   Irrespective of the placement of the Bishop @@StartBracket@@c8/d7@@EndBracket@@, we are happy with our position😊. }
7... cxd4
{ Probably the most natural move. Planning to meet cxd4 with Bc6 getting total stability and justifying the extra Bd7. }
8. Bxd5 { Welcome to the triple pawn structure. } 8... exd5 9. O-O
{ Surprise! We are not keen to take back the pawn and focus on rapid development instead. We are sending our greetings to the king on e8. }
9... dxe5 { A risky suggestion of machines. } 10. Nxe5 Nc6
{ The best practical choice. } 11. Nxc6
{ We want to take on d4 with the queen to restrict the bishop on f8. } 11...
bxc6
{ 11...Bxc6  12.Qxd4  gives Black an IQP with two horrible bishops defending pawns. }
12. Qxd4
{ Black still struggles to develop normally.   It would require computer precision to maintain the balance, and even then, White's position remains always easy to play over the board despite the engine evaluation that gives equality. }
