[Black "2...Nf6 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nf3 Alternatives"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... g6
{ The 4th most popular choice after Nc6/e6/d6. } 5. d4
{ Getting control in the center. The threat of c4-d5 practically forces Black to take on d4. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4
{ This is a rare occurrence when we take on d4 with the queen. Only after g6, the queen on d4 becomes stronger due to e6 threats in some cases. }
6... Nc7
{ Black could play  6...Nb6  and after  7.Qh4  we will reach a similar position as here, but the knight on b6 is further away to help Black's king, which will soon come under attack. }
7. Qh4
{ Black's pieces are so funnily placed that it is a good moment to take a picture of the position😊.   Meanwhile, on a serious note, we prepare a future kingside attack by trading the dark-squared bishop at the right time with Bh6. }
7... Nc6
{ Black refrains from playing Bg7 which encourages White to play Bh6.  Playing  7...h6  to stop the Bh6 idea creates a permanent weakness and ensures Black will never be able to castle on the kingside.  White can continue with  8.Bc4  Bg7  9.O-O  when the Black king has no place to go. }
8. Bc4 { We are waiting for Black to play Bg7 before we go Bh6. } 8... d5
{ 8...Ne6  9.O-O  , followed by Re1, ensures Black cannot develop freely, and the king gets stuck in the center. }
9. exd6 Qxd6
{ 9...exd6  10.Qxd8  Kxd8  11.Na3  leaves Black with a weak king and a worse pawn structure with a clear target on d6. }
10. Bf4 { Developing with a tempo and provoking Black to play e5. } 10... e5
{ There is no other sensible move that looks critical. } 11. Bg5
{ White is now coming with Nbd2-e4 to get more control on the f6-square. }
11... Be6 12. Nbd2
{ White knight is coming for the Black queen, and the king on e8 remains stuck, assuring White a clear advantage. }
