[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... Nc6 5.
Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5
{ Whether Black plays d6 or d5, it does not make any difference since we respond with exd6 in both cases. }
7. exd6 e6 8. O-O Bxd6
{ The most natural recapture, but Black has also taken  8...Qxd6  a couple of times, which is covered in the main coursehere. }
9. d4 { Gaining control over the center and opening up the c1-bishop. } 9...
cxd4 { Black wants to play against the IQP and consolidate his position. } 10.
cxd4
{ We give the same argument. The bishop on c8 is bad typically, and with the knight on b6, it gets further worse as it blocks the path of b6-Bb7. }
10... O-O
{ The most obvious and logical move.   Black can play other moves also, but eventually, he will have to castle and we will get a similar position. }
11. Nc3
{ Black's knight on b6 is stopping the c8-bishop from developing. Let us not forget this detail 😊.  At this point, Black can try a few things, but none give him equality. Let us see his various logical plans. It is very interesting to observe that Sebastian's course on the Alapin ended right here, giving White an edge.   We felt it would be essential to understand the upcoming middlegame and plans as this position is highly likely to come, and Black has tried several moves. }
11... Bd7
{ Black doesn't move his knight and first makes a square for the a8-rook. } 12.
Re1 { Our useful developing move. } 12... Rc8 13. Ne5
{ Black clearly could not solve the issue of his light-squared bishop, and White enjoys an easy game. }
