[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "4.Nf3 Nc6 Main line with ...c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... Nc6 5.
Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5 7. exd6 c4
{ We have already covered previous deviations in different chapters. In this chapter, this will be our starting position. }
8. Bc2
{ Can Black claim his pawn on c4 is strong enough to block us from opening the center without making any concessions?   Or is the c4-pawn just a burden for Black that needs more protection? This debate will get more clarity as we move forward. }
8... Qxd6
{ 8...exd6  makes absolutely no sense when White can play O-O and d3, and Black will end up with a pathetic pawn structure.  A sample variation could be  8...exd6  9.O-O  Be7  10.d4  d5  11.a4!  and now Black must either allow White to play a5 and move the knight from b6, thus losing protection from c4, or play a5 and allow Na3-b5 ideas.  In either case, there are too many weaknesses in Black's position. }
9. O-O
{ One of the leading trendy positions of this system.   White keeps his option on the queenside flexible. We can go a4-a5 or break with b3/d3. First, Black must show his intentions with his king.   On which side is it going to hide? }
9... Bg4
{ The most tempting/challenging, and dynamic move. Black pins the knight on f3 and intends to castle long to gain more control on the d3-square.   At first glance, this looks awesome, but let's go deeper before concluding anything. }
10. Re1
{ It is essential to refrain from including h3-Bh5, as suggested by Sebastian in his course. The reasoning will get clear later. }
10... O-O-O
{ Consistent with Black's previous move. Black ensures White cannot push the d-pawn.   10...Qf6  11.Be4  O-O-O  12.a4  gets Black to a position where he cannot simultaneously take care of a5/b3/d4 threats, and the position opens up on the queenside, exposing his king. }
11. Na3
{ Surprisingly rare! We go for the pawn on c4 and not hiding our plans. This is our main suggestion, as the best Black gets here is an endgame where we will be pressing.   However, there is also another second alternative that is risky but poses many practical problems for Black. Feel free to pick your line after studying them thoroughly. Both are very attractive. }
11... Qf6
{ There are no other decent plans available for Black. This is the way Black usually plays in this line. Attacking on f3 and stopping White from playing d3.  After  11...e5  12.h3  Bh5  13.b3  the queenside explodes rapidly, and Black is not on time to generate counterplay on the other side. }
12. Qe2
{ This is a strong and unusual idea for this line. White almost exclusively plays for the b3 break, but here we ruthlessly go for the c4-pawn. }
12... Bxf3
{ The alternatives do not have any independent value as after taking twice on c4, Black will be obliged to take on f3, and we will transpose eventually.   Black cannot get away without making this move sooner or later. }
13. gxf3
{ We are not worried about our king as there are not enough pieces for Black to conduct an attack. Meanwhile, we intend to take on c4 next.   This position is very fresh, and there are too many tempting ideas for Black which backfires completely. It is highly likely that over the board Black will choose the most active moves and get a lost position soon. Especially if we don't blitz out all our moves until here and pretend slightly that we are freestyling on the board 😉.  Let us analyze this position thoroughly to ensure we understand why our king is safe 😉. }
13... e6
{ This is also a human move, Black wants to finish his development faster.   Pushing the pawn two squares is naive as it takes away any future Ne5 ideas and blocks any attacking idea with Bd6xh2. }
14. Nxc4
{ There is no other way. We have to remove this pawn at the first chance. }
14... Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Qxf3
{ This position does not look intimidating by any means. Black has just one queen in the attack, which will be kicked away instantly. }
16. Qe4
{ It was also possible to play  16.Re3  Qh5  17.Qe2  when Black's attack dies, we will play d4 and have a double bishop advantage with a good center. }
16... Qh5 17. d4
{ We are ready to play Bf4 to stop dirty business on that diagonal. Our center is good, and we have a double bishop advantage.  One might get tempted to stop Bf4 with the dubious  17...g5  and will get punched with a stunning retreat  18.Bd1  Qh6  19.Qg2   These two moves are difficult to spot, but once it is on the board, it is no longer possible to deal with the Bf3 and the upcoming massacre on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
