3. g3
{ The first relatively rare move.😊 As you will see throughout the course, We will be finding new/rare ideas very early and creating our own theories. The most popular move is to play  3.Nf3  here.  White's moves are simple Bg2/Ne2/O-O and d4. Black cannot stop this, and he will have to justify the odd queen placement on a5.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bg2  Nc6  will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  .  Also @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bg2  Bg7  5.Ne2  Nc6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  . }
3... b5
{ Black tries to justify the queen's placement on a5, but this further weakens his position. }
4. Bg2 { Just developing pieces } 4... Bb7 5. Ne2
{ White prepares O-O-d4 ideas. } 5... f5
{ This radical move was played once but didn't improve Black's horrible position. Engines scream +2.5 already😊. }
6. d4 { White opens up the center as Black has weakened a bit too much. } 6...
cxd4
{ After  6...Bxe4  7.Bxe4  fxe4  8.dxc5  Black's pieces are awkward, and he will have a tough time finishing development. Engine's evaluation of +2.5 is hard to argue with. }
7. Nxd4 fxe4 8. Qh5+
{ The queen heads for the e5-square once Black plays ...g6. } 8... g6 9. Qe5
{ Black loses heavy material, and White is thus winning. } *

