3... Nc6
{ 3...Nf6  allows an extra  4.e5  , which is pretty strong. White can also simply play  4.Bg2  , and after  4...Nc6  , we will get to the position that we shall see from 3... Nc6 move order. }
4. Bg2 { We continue with our normal plan of finishing castle first. } 4... Nf6
{ Black also continues developing, but the queen on a5 remains misplaced. } 5.
Ne2 { White is now one move away from castling. } 5... h5
{ After other moves, White would follow his plan and continue with O-O and d4.  The move  5...h5  has been played by Movsesian thrice. }
6. h3
{ Simple and strong. White makes sure Black cannot open the h-file anymore. }
6... c4 { Trying to stop White from playing d4. } 7. d4
{ Pushing this pawn seems like the most natural plan to be able to develop freely. }
7... cxd3 { There is no other justification for playing 6... c4. } 8. Qxd3
{ The White queen is not as exposed as the Black queen. If Black attacks the White queen with Ne5, White will move it to c2 and later gain back the tempo by attacking the knight on e5 with f4. }
8... d6 9. f4
{ A possible improvement on Kamsky @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Movsesian @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2008.   White has much more space and an easy game with Be3-O-O coming next. Black will have a hard time finishing his development and finding his king safety. }
