{ This unique way of stopping White from playing d4 @@StartBracket@@as White cannot take cxd4 due to the pin@@EndBracket@@ is pretty popular. Movsesian and Alekseenko have played this variation several times. Also, we can see players like Rapport, Svidler, Andreikin, Korobov, etc., had tried this system a few times. }
3. g3
{ The first relatively rare move.😊 As you will see throughout the course, We will be finding new/rare ideas very early and creating our own theories. The most popular move is to play  3.Nf3  here.  White's moves are simple Bg2/Ne2/O-O and d4. Black cannot stop this, and he will have to justify the odd queen placement on a5.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.Bg2  Nc6  will transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  .  Also @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...g6  4.Bg2  Bg7  5.Ne2  Nc6  transposes to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp1ppppp/8/q1p5/4P3/2P3P1/PP1P1P1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nc6  . }
3... Nc6
{ 3...Nf6  allows an extra  4.e5  , which is pretty strong. White can also simply play  4.Bg2  , and after  4...Nc6  , we will get to the position that we shall see from 3... Nc6 move order. }
4. Bg2 { We continue with our normal plan of finishing castle first. } 4... g6
{ Black brings maximum control towards the d4-square. } 5. Ne2
{ O-O and d4 coming soon! } 5... Bg7
{ Black is trying his best to bring as much control as possible to stop d4. }
6. O-O { White is now ready to play d4. } 6... c4
{ Another way to stop White from playing d4, but this creates a nice target for White. }
7. Na3 { White hits on the target immediately. } 7... b5
{ Black tries to support the falls wall he has created, but it's a matter of time before everything will collapse. After all Black has ignored his king 😊. }
8. b3 Ba6
{ When a bishop is protecting pawns like this early on, it is already a bad sign for Black. }
9. b4 Qb6
{ After  9...Qc7  10.Nxb5  Bxb5  11.a4  Ba6  12.b5  White gets back the piece with a heavy lead in development. }
10. d4 { Grabbing the center. } 10... cxd3 11. Qxd3
{ With Be3-Nd4-f4 etc., coming Black's position collapses completely. } *

