1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nc6
{ This move intends to play d5 next but doesn't stop White from playing d4, which is the main idea of Alapin.   So there are no marks for guessing our next move 😊. }
3. d4
{ White continues with the most obvious plan of taking control of the center. }
3... cxd4
{ 3...d5  4.exd5  Qxd5  is coveredhere in the Alapin 2... d5 section. } 4. cxd4
e6
{ 4...d5  5.exd5  Qxd5  is a better choice, which is also coveredhere in the Alapin 2... d5 section. }
5. d5
{ Otherwise, Black would finally play d7-d5 with some stability. If Black doesn't stop us from playing d5, then we go for it. }
5... exd5
{ Eliminating one pawn from the center but also opening up his king. } 6. exd5
Ne5 7. Nc3
{ White has more space, and this turns out enough for a serious edge.   Without the inclusion of exd5-exd5, it was stronger to opt for f4-e5 ideas, but here this simple developing move promises an excellent game for White. }
7... Bc5
{ 7...Bb4  leads to a position we'll see down the main line from the 6... Bb4 move order, which we will examinehere. }
8. d6 { Cuts the enemy lines, creating immediate threats of Qe2/Qd5, etc. }
8... Nf6 { Black stops Qd5 and intends to meet Qe2 with O-O. } 9. Bf4
{ A very crucial move that gives White an advantage. Without this particular resource, Black would have escaped. Now he won't be able to castle further. }
9... Ng6 10. Qe2+ { The point, of course. We can't let him castle. } 10... Kf8
11. Bg3
{ Black has problems all over the place. White will develop and get a devastating attack soon after.   Only if Black could castle he would solve all his issues in the position, but unfortunately for him, that option is gone. }
