1. e4 c5 2. c3 e5
{ A relatively new approach. Black weakens the d5-square but does get some central control in return, making d2-d4 more difficult. }
3. Nf3
{ Bringing more support to d4 and attacking e5 is the most natural way White can continue. }
3... Nc6 { Otherwise White gets d4 easily. } 4. Bc4
{ A nice developing move, targeting both weaknesses in Black's position, the d5-square and the f7-pawn. }
4... d6 { Allows White to get an easy play with simple moves. } 5. O-O
{ White is ready to play d4 next. } 5... Be7 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bg4
{ This loses, but it's the only thing that needs to be checked as other moves give White a lead in development and a better center. }
8. Qb3
{ Leaves Black unable to defend his pawns.  Note that  8...Bxf3  9.Bxf7  Kf8  loses material as White takes  10.Bxg8  followed by taking on f3. }
