[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 2...a6"]
[Black "2... a6 3. d4 e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 a6
{ This move is better than it looks but fails, perhaps not surprisingly, to equalize. Black stays noncommittal for now and waits for White to charge in the center first. }
3. d4 { Not a surprise when we play Alapin 😊. } 3... e6
{ Getting into a horrible French, really. } 4. Bd3 { Nice, easy development. }
4... d5 5. e5
{ We got into the best possible French Advance for White. Usually, White struggles to get the bishop on d3 as Black puts quick pressure on the d4-pawn, but here Black has wasted a crucial tempo with a6. }
5... Bd7
{ Trying to make sense of it all. After  5...Nc6  6.Nf3  Black's position makes no sense when White manages to finish development smoothly, and Black has zero pressure on the center. }
6. Nd2
{ White keeps the option open for the kingside knight development on e2 or f3. }
6... Bb5 7. Bc2
{ The bishop on b5 will cause Black even more trouble. White will finish his development with a serious edge,  a4-Ne2-O-O is coming next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 2...a6"]
[Black "2... a6 3. d4 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 a6
{ This move is better than it looks but fails, perhaps not surprisingly, to equalize. Black stays noncommittal for now and waits for White to charge in the center first. }
3. d4 { Not a surprise when we play Alapin 😊. } 3... cxd4
{ The point, in connection to the next move. Other moves don't work well with 2... a6. }
4. cxd4 { Now White has his dream center. Black has to strike at once. } 4...
d5
{ The only way to try to fight for adequate counterplay and the actual point of 2... a6. The pawn is very useful for Black in the case of exd5, controlling Bb5 checks. }
5. e5
{ We like this approach much better than the more popular exd5.   After  5.e5  , the black pawn on a6 often turns into a wasted move. }
5... Bf5
{ Black needs to develop, and there's no better way.  5...Nc6  is possible but after  6.Nc3  Bf5  7.Bd3  Black will have to take on d3, and we will eventually transpose to the mainline.  7...Nxd4  fails to  8.Qa4  when White wins a piece. }
6. Bd3
{ Simple chess. White develops and exchanges Black's most active piece. What more can you ask 😊.   We cannot consider the bishop on f5 bad anymore, so it is perfectly fine to trade it. }
6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3
{ White keeps a better center and a lead in the development. } 7... e6 8. Nc3
{ White has more space, and an easy game. } 8... Nc6
{ Both Black's minor pieces have got one attractive square on e7. } 9. Nf3
{ Statistics do not always speak about the reality of the position. So far, only three games have reached this position, and in all Black has won.   It is hard to imagine what can go wrong for White here with more space and an easy game. }
9... Nge7
{ Most natural. Black takes care of the knight first before developing the bishop. }
10. O-O Nf5
{ Black follows the plan. The knight on f5 can become a liability, however. }
11. Ne2
{ This typical move strengthens White's grip in the center and prepares a pawn storm with g4. Black doesn't have the time to consolidate and will have to endure a strong attack. White now waits for Be7 to play g4. }
11... Be7
{ This is a natural developing move, but this is what White is waiting for. }
12. g4
{ That was the main idea against Be7. Now, Blacks bishop will land on h4 instead of the queen. }
12... Nh4 13. Nxh4 { This frees the f-pawn. } 13... Bxh4 14. f4
{ It is important to know that the h4-bishop sometimes risks getting trapped behind enemy lines. }
14... O-O
{ The king is not safe anywhere on the board. It could have run to the queenside, but White's pawns can march on that side too! }
15. f5 { Going for the most principled way to attack. } 15... f6 16. Nf4
{ And White will win material with Nxe6 fork coming next. } *

