1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 Nf6
{ It has been played several times, but Black gets into a horrible French. } 4.
Bd3 { Protecting the pawn and developing at the same time. } 4... Nc6
{ After  4...d5  5.e5  Nfd7  7.Nf3  Black got into the worst version of the French Defense. Compare the same with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  Nf6  4.e5  Nfd7  5.Bd3  c5  6.c3  .  We obviously don't have to play Nd2 here, and Black has zero counterplay against White's strong center and better development. }
5. Ne2
{ We like the knight on e2 more just in case to avoid any Ne4 ideas and also keep the f4 ideas available in the future. }
5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nb4
{ Black tries to justify his play by taking the bishop on d3. } 7. Nbc3
{ Ignoring the threat and developing normally. } 7... Nxd3+ 8. Qxd3
{ Black did get double bishop, but he can't be proud of the bishop on c8. White keeps a significant lead in the development and enjoys a strong center. }
