[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2...e6 3.d4 d5 Sidelines"]
[Black "3.d4 d5 4.exd5 exd5 5.Bb5+ Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5
{ The normal continuation. Black strikes in the center without including cxd4 to deprive White of playing Nc3.   3...cxd4  is covered in the next chapter, and moves like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  will essentially transpose to Black's 2nd move sidelines @@StartBracket@@b6/a6@@EndBracket@@, which are also covered separately. }
4. exd5
{ The most principled continuation. We want to point out that the chances of getting 3...d5 position is a bit rare compared to other lines if White wants he can directly transpose into mainline of the French Advance with  4.e5  .  So a player who started with a Sicilian and then switched to the mainline of the French Advance is not something common. If your repertoire against the French is the Advanced Variation and you are already happy with it, then you can skip this entire chapter and transpose with  4.e5  . However, we stick to the Alapin in our recommendations. }
4... exd5
{ 4...Qxd5  will transpose to the Alapin 2... d5 segment, which we will examinehere.  The position after  4...exd5  is essential for us to understand. In most cases, White will take on c5, resulting in a position with an isolated pawn on d5. Our task is to exchange some pieces, block the pawn firmly with a knight on  d4  , and win the endgame.  In most Alapin lines, White plays with the isolated pawn, not against it. The great variety of possible structures arising from the Alapin will improve your feel for many different positions and make you a better player, at least, that's the general idea 😊.  An important trick to know is after  4...cxd4  5.Bb5  Bd7  White has the cute  6.dxe6  Bxb5  7.exf7  Kxf7  8.Qb3  and the b5-bishop falls when White retains a material advantage. }
5. Bb5+
{ Simple chess. White goes for the fastest development, with Nf3 and O-O to follow in short succession.   And as for having maybe to exchange that bishop - we don't really mind some exchanges, as they bring us closer to the d5-pawn. }
5... Bd7
{ Somewhat less popular, but a possible move. Exchanging this bishop makes d5 potentially more vulnerable, but White still has to work plenty to prove it. Players who get isolated pawns would like to avoid piece exchanges in general. }
6. Bxd7+ { Otherwise, we lose time to defend that bishop on b5. } 6... Qxd7
{ Black loses a bit of time, but insists on a more active placement of the knight on c6. }
7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O
{ The open e-file with all sorts of tricks is a source of worry for Black now. }
8... cxd4
{ Black doesn't want to lose a tempo with Be7/Bd6-Bxc5 so he clarifies the center before developing his bishop. }
9. Re1+ Be7 10. Bg5
{ This prevents Nf6, and makes it tricky for Black to untangle. } 10... O-O-O
{ I played once in a tournament game, but the king will never be safe on c8. After  10...f6  11.Bf4  the problem of the g8-knight doesn't solve. }
11. Bf4
{ A logical and straightforward improvement. Black's king becomes unsafe, and the attack on the queenside becomes evident as the files will start to open soon. }
*

