{ Somewhat less popular, but a possible move. Exchanging this bishop makes d5 potentially more vulnerable, but White still has to work plenty to prove it. Players who get isolated pawns would like to avoid piece exchanges in general. }
6. Bxd7+ { Otherwise, we lose time to defend that bishop on b5. } 6... Qxd7
{ Black loses a bit of time, but insists on a more active placement of the knight on c6. }
7. Nf3 Nc6 8. O-O
{ The open e-file with all sorts of tricks is a source of worry for Black now. }
8... Bd6
{ Most frequently, this move intends to finish the development in a most natural way.  8...Be7  9.dxc5  Bxc5  leads to the same position we will be seeing from the @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/pp1q1ppp/2n5/2pp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bd6  move order. }
9. dxc5
{ Now we take on c5 and force Black to lose a tempo @@StartBracket@@Bd6-Bxc5@@EndBracket@@. }
9... Bxc5 10. Re1+
{ Developing with a tempo and giving Black a choice on how to block the check. }
10... Nge7
{ The most natural way to block the check.  After  10...Be7  11.Bg5  it would be difficult for Black to develop the kingside knight and castle short without compromising the pawn structure. }
11. Be3 { We want to trade pieces to highlight the weakness on d5 further. }
11... Bd6
{ Having an isolated pawn, Black naturally wants to keep more pieces to play for activity. }
12. Nbd2
{ White has better development and a better pawn structure which gives him a better position. }
