5... Nc6 { The most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ White wants to castle and take on c5 at the right moment. } 6... cxd4
{ One of the better moves if Black is trying to avoid the main line that starts with  6...Bd6  , which we will examine in thenext chapter.   6...Nf6  is pretty common, but after  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  , we are back to the line which is also covered in the next chapterhere. }
7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. O-O
{ It looks very dangerous for Black already, and from a practical point of view, it is also possible to stop our opening preparation right here 😊.   For the sake of completeness, we will continue, but for instance, in our games already, this is a good enough place to stop by concluding Black has isolated pawn and stays behind the development. However, let us continue to see a bit to improve our general understanding of how to play against isolated pawns.   The course is aimed to make you a better player and not just an opening expert 😊. }
8... Bd6
{ An attempt to get the perfect setup with ...Bd6, ...Nge7 doesn't quite work. }
9. c4
{ White immediately undermines Black's position in the center. Given that the bishop on d6 is vulnerable, Black has no way to avoid serious structural problems.   It is good to know that such a counter-intuitive motif of playing c4 and letting Black get rid of the isolated pawn also exists. }
9... Nge7
{ After  9...dxc4  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Bxc6  bxc6  12.Qg4  the double attack on g7 and c4 with the king in the center puts Black in grave danger. }
10. cxd5 Nxd5 { 10...Nxd4  11.Bxd7  Qxd7  12.Qxd4  gives White a free pawn. }
11. Re1+ Be7
{ After  11...Nde7  12.Nxc6  Bxc6  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Nd2  Black gets a permanent weakness on the queenside due to his pawn structure, and White enjoys a better position where he plays only for two results. }
12. Nxc6 { Ruining Black's pawn structure. } 12... Bxc6
{ 12...bxc6  doesn't create any threat as the d5-knight falls if Black ever takes on b5. White plays the strong  13.Bg5  and trades another piece while playing  13...f6  14.Bh4  causes further weakness in Black's position. }
13. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ Now that the pawns are chronically weak, White will have good chances in most middlegames or endgames. }
14. Bg5 O-O 15. Bxe7
{ We are exchanging more pieces and playing simple chess. } 15... Nxe7 16. Nd2
{ Maybe Black can hold this, but surely it is not an attractive task to spend a whole game defending. We are sure no one will object to playing this position from the White side 😊. }
