{ It looks very dangerous for Black already, and from a practical point of view, it is also possible to stop our opening preparation right here 😊.   For the sake of completeness, we will continue, but for instance, in our games already, this is a good enough place to stop by concluding Black has isolated pawn and stays behind the development. However, let us continue to see a bit to improve our general understanding of how to play against isolated pawns.   The course is aimed to make you a better player and not just an opening expert 😊. }
8... Nf6 { The better one of the two possible setups. } 9. Re1+
{ White uses the open e-file to make it difficult for Black to finish the development properly. }
9... Be7 10. Qe2
{ Now Black can't castle as the e7-bishop will be hanging after White takes on c6. The following line is the only way for Black to stay solid. }
10... Nxd4 { This move starts a forced sequence. } 11. cxd4
{ Still stopping Black from castling. } 11... Bxb5 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qe2
{ Back to business. Now, after some exchanges, the problem is the same - how to castle without losing some material? }
13... Rc8
{ The best way to do it. The rook on the 6th rank is a great defensive piece in most positions.  It is good to know that Black cannot solve this issue tactically with  13...O-O  14.Qxe7  Rae8  as White has  15.Qb4  protecting the rook on e1, and he remains one piece up.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1qbppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1R1K1 b kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  with a similar idea to bring the rook to e6 via Ra6 is possible but after  14.Bd2  , often the pawn on a5 will be hanging as compared to the mainline @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1qbppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1R1K1 b kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rc8  14.Bd2  . }
14. Bd2
{ An almost entirely new idea that proves quite poisonous. White combines many different ideas and poses quite a few unusual problems to solve. To start with we threaten Bb4. }
14... Ne4
{ Trying to close the e-file might look very tempting but White has a simple resource against it. }
15. Nc3 { Getting rid of the knight immediately. } 15... f5
{ 15...Nxd2  16.Nxd5!  wins on the spot as Black loses material. } 16. Qh5+
{ Never giving time to castle. } 16... g6 17. Qh6
{ Black finds his task far from easy here. The king will have to stay in the middle of the board for a while. }
17... Nxd2 { 17...Kf7  18.Bf4  didn't look fun either with a terrible king. }
18. Qxd2
{ White is better, especially since  18...O-O  still fails due to  19.Nxd5  . }
