[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 2...e6 3.d4 d5 Sidelines"]
[Black "5.Bb5+ Nc6 6.Nf3 cxd4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5
{ The normal continuation. Black strikes in the center without including cxd4 to deprive White of playing Nc3.   3...cxd4  is covered in the next chapter, and moves like  3...b6  ,  3...a6  will essentially transpose to Black's 2nd move sidelines @@StartBracket@@b6/a6@@EndBracket@@, which are also covered separately. }
4. exd5
{ The most principled continuation. We want to point out that the chances of getting 3...d5 position is a bit rare compared to other lines if White wants he can directly transpose into mainline of the French Advance with  4.e5  .  So a player who started with a Sicilian and then switched to the mainline of the French Advance is not something common. If your repertoire against the French is the Advanced Variation and you are already happy with it, then you can skip this entire chapter and transpose with  4.e5  . However, we stick to the Alapin in our recommendations. }
4... exd5
{ 4...Qxd5  will transpose to the Alapin 2... d5 segment, which we will examinehere.  The position after  4...exd5  is essential for us to understand. In most cases, White will take on c5, resulting in a position with an isolated pawn on d5. Our task is to exchange some pieces, block the pawn firmly with a knight on  d4  , and win the endgame.  In most Alapin lines, White plays with the isolated pawn, not against it. The great variety of possible structures arising from the Alapin will improve your feel for many different positions and make you a better player, at least, that's the general idea 😊.  An important trick to know is after  4...cxd4  5.Bb5  Bd7  White has the cute  6.dxe6  Bxb5  7.exf7  Kxf7  8.Qb3  and the b5-bishop falls when White retains a material advantage. }
5. Bb5+
{ Simple chess. White goes for the fastest development, with Nf3 and O-O to follow in short succession.   And as for having maybe to exchange that bishop - we don't really mind some exchanges, as they bring us closer to the d5-pawn. }
5... Nc6 { The most popular move. } 6. Nf3
{ White wants to castle and take on c5 at the right moment. } 6... cxd4
{ One of the better moves if Black is trying to avoid the main line that starts with  6...Bd6  , which we will examine in thenext chapter.   6...Nf6  is pretty common, but after  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  , we are back to the line which is also covered in the next chapterhere. }
7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. O-O
{ It looks very dangerous for Black already, and from a practical point of view, it is also possible to stop our opening preparation right here 😊.   For the sake of completeness, we will continue, but for instance, in our games already, this is a good enough place to stop by concluding Black has isolated pawn and stays behind the development. However, let us continue to see a bit to improve our general understanding of how to play against isolated pawns.   The course is aimed to make you a better player and not just an opening expert 😊. }
8... Nf6 { The better one of the two possible setups. } 9. Re1+
{ White uses the open e-file to make it difficult for Black to finish the development properly. }
9... Be7 10. Qe2
{ Now Black can't castle as the e7-bishop will be hanging after White takes on c6. The following line is the only way for Black to stay solid. }
10... Nxd4 { This move starts a forced sequence. } 11. cxd4
{ Still stopping Black from castling. } 11... Bxb5 12. Qxb5+ Qd7 13. Qe2
{ Back to business. Now, after some exchanges, the problem is the same - how to castle without losing some material? }
13... Rc8
{ The best way to do it. The rook on the 6th rank is a great defensive piece in most positions.  It is good to know that Black cannot solve this issue tactically with  13...O-O  14.Qxe7  Rae8  as White has  15.Qb4  protecting the rook on e1, and he remains one piece up.  @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1qbppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1R1K1 b kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...a5  with a similar idea to bring the rook to e6 via Ra6 is possible but after  14.Bd2  , often the pawn on a5 will be hanging as compared to the mainline @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp1qbppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/8/PP2QPPP/RNB1R1K1 b kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rc8  14.Bd2  . }
14. Bd2
{ An almost entirely new idea that proves quite poisonous. White combines many different ideas and poses quite a few unusual problems to solve. To start with we threaten Bb4. }
14... Rc6 { Following the plan that started with Rc8. } 15. Qe5
{ Creating an annoying threat with Qb8 that forces Black into passive defense. }
15... Qd8 16. Nc3
{ White finishes the development, connecting the rooks in the meantime. Black still can't castle without some concessions. }
16... Re6
{ Finally, Black is ready to castle, but he has lost many tempos in the process. }
17. Qg3 { The queen is well placed here. } 17... Rxe1+
{ Trying to keep the pawns healthy leads to a very passive position. } 18. Rxe1
O-O 19. Bg5
{ A massive difference in activity means that Black will remain under pressure for a long time. It would be challenging to take care of the weak d5-pawn, the bishop on e7, and the knight on f6. }
*

