[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6
{ All alternatives before this move are covered under the sidelines.   Black finishes his development and does not mind wasting a tempo with Bd6-Bxc5 in case White takes on c5. }
7. dxc5
{ Whenever Black moves the bishop from f8, it makes sense to take on c5 to force Black to waste a tempo. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Nf6
{ This line has become popular in recent times, the World Champion played it twice already in 2022.  The same position could also occur from a different move order with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n5/1Bpp4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  7.O-O  Be7  8.dxc5  Bxc5  .  The knight is more active on f6, but Black also takes serious risks due to the upcoming pin with Bg5 and the open e-file. }
9. Bg5 { Pinning the knight, but also directly threatening the pawn on d5. }
9... Be6
{ The point of Black's setup; going for a maximum activity to compensate for his weak d-pawn. }
10. Nbd2
{ We are finishing the development most naturally and aiming for Nb3-Nd4 in the future. }
10... O-O 11. Nb3 Bb6
{ Black stays true to his concept and refuses to play for safety. The plan is to go h6-g5, Ne4, and fight. The plan of h6-g5-Ne4 is pretty common in this kind of isolated pawn structure. }
12. Bxc6
{ A new and powerful positional concept. White exchanges some pieces, limiting Black's dynamic possibilities. We let him eliminate the weak d5-pawn but bring a new weakness on c6. }
12... bxc6 13. Nbd4
{ Not just c6, but the strategic threat on e6 is also pretty annoying for Black. }
13... c5
{ Stabilizing the center to compensate for the new weakness on e6 that is about to come. }
14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. c4
{ A fine strategic move, making the bishop on b6 look quite useless. Black has no prospects here, also because his pawn chain in the middle of the board is static and vulnerable.  After  15...d4  16.Re1  , the weakness on e6 and the horrible bishop on b6 would be painful for Black.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/p5pp/1b2pn2/2pp2B1/2P5/5N2/PP3PPP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Qd7  with the idea of Ne4 is well met by  16.Re1  when Black cannot play Ne4 anymore due to the pin on the queen.  White remains better here with a risk-free position. }
