1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6
{ All alternatives before this move are covered under the sidelines.   Black finishes his development and does not mind wasting a tempo with Bd6-Bxc5 in case White takes on c5. }
7. dxc5
{ Whenever Black moves the bishop from f8, it makes sense to take on c5 to force Black to waste a tempo. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ This is the most popular setup for Black. He makes sure there are no checks with Re1, and he can castle next. }
9. Nbd2
{ The standard developing square for the knight, heading d4 via b3 and, in the process, gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
9... O-O { 9...Bb6  10.Nb3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. } 10. Nb3
{ At this point, both bishop retreats on b6 and d6 are almost equally popular, and we should be ready for both. }
10... Bd6
{ Here Black abandons the fight for the d4-square but focuses on the kingside. }
11. Be3
{ A solid developing move. White retains the possibility of challenging the bishop on d6 with Be3-c5. }
11... Bg4
{ Stopping Bc5 ideas for a while. After  12.Bc5  Bxc5  13.Nxc5  Qb6  14.Bxc6  Nxc6  White will have difficulties dealing with the pin on d1, which would allow Black to create threats of Ne5/d4 etc. }
12. h3 { Always nice to make sure we'll never blunder this pawn 😊. } 12... Bh5
13. Be2
{ We are getting away from the pin and planning Nfd4 at the right moment. }
13... Re8 14. Re1
{ Both sides are completing the development, and the problems of the d5-pawn are likely to stay for a long time. }
14... Qd7
{ After  14...Qc7  White gets a tempo of  15.Nbd4  by threatening Nb5, and Black will have to play  15...a6  when White can trade the other bishop with  16.Nh4  , and yet once again, Black will be left with the weak IQP. }
15. Qd2
{ Good, solid play with Bf4-ideas in mind in the future, and also bringing the rook to d1 soon. }
15... Rad8 16. Bf4 { Exchanging the bishop finally. } 16... Bxf4 17. Qxf4
{ Slowly but surely, White will establish a knight on d4 and get a slight but durable advantage. }
