[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6 3. d4 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6
{ All alternatives before this move are covered under the sidelines.   Black finishes his development and does not mind wasting a tempo with Bd6-Bxc5 in case White takes on c5. }
7. dxc5
{ Whenever Black moves the bishop from f8, it makes sense to take on c5 to force Black to waste a tempo. }
7... Bxc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ This is the most popular setup for Black. He makes sure there are no checks with Re1, and he can castle next. }
9. Nbd2
{ The standard developing square for the knight, heading d4 via b3 and, in the process, gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
9... O-O { 9...Bb6  10.Nb3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. } 10. Nb3
{ At this point, both bishop retreats on b6 and d6 are almost equally popular, and we should be ready for both. }
10... Bb6 { Keeping maximum control on the d4-square. } 11. Re1
{ We have seen this particular theme several times. White intends to play Be3 next.   Any piece trade usually benefits White as long as Black's structure remains weak with the isolated pawn. }
11... Nf5
{ The knight on f5 makes it more challenging for White to access important squares e3 and d4, and Black silently gives a deadly threat of Bxf2-Kxf2-Qb6 when White cannot keep the support with Nd4 as Black will take twice on d4, and the bishop on b5 will fall at the end. }
12. a4
{ A great move, which takes care of Black's threat of Bxf2, as mentioned before, and White also keeps the idea of playing a5 in many variations.   It is good enough to stop our opening analyses here by saying White is better, but why lose the opportunity to learn a little strategy and positional concept to improve general chess understanding? Let's keep going 😊. }
12... a6
{ Black seeks clarity and chases the bishop away from b5. After  12...a5  White can still play  13.Bd3  and keep ideas like Bxf5-Be3 or Bc2-Qd3 in hand, or proceed with  13.Bf4  and ask Black how he will deal with the weak d5-pawn. }
13. Bd3
{ The bishop is very well placed here, exerting pressure on the f5-knight and further. We'll see this bishop retreat very often, so get used to it 😊. }
13... h6
{ Black needed to cover g5 in almost all lines to avoid Bg5/Ng5 ideas. } 14. a5
{ Since this pawn can't be captured, as we will see, this advance gives White space on the queenside and activates a dormant rook. }
14... Ba7
{ After  14...Nxa5  15.Nxa5  Bxa5  16.Re5  the engine evaluation of +5 seems agreeable once we see that it is impossible to deal with the weaknesses on a5, d5, and f5. Black loses material. }
15. Bxf5
{ The point. White gets some useful exchanges, and the weakness on d5 becomes more prominent. }
15... Bxf5 16. Be3
{ Exchanging pieces favors White and specially changing this one 😊. } 16...
Bxe3
{ 16...Bb8  17.Bb6  would make no sense for Black so he is obliged to take on e3 instead. }
17. Rxe3 Bg4 { To avoid Nfd4. } 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Qxf3
{ Time to congratulate Black for going to suffer for a long time. The advantage might not be much, but it is going to last for a very long time, and White is once again playing for two results only. }
