{ This is the most popular setup for Black. He makes sure there are no checks with Re1, and he can castle next. }
9. Nbd2
{ The standard developing square for the knight, heading d4 via b3 and, in the process, gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop. }
9... O-O { 9...Bb6  10.Nb3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. } 10. Nb3
{ At this point, both bishop retreats on b6 and d6 are almost equally popular, and we should be ready for both. }
10... Bb6 { Keeping maximum control on the d4-square. } 11. Re1
{ We have seen this particular theme several times. White intends to play Be3 next.   Any piece trade usually benefits White as long as Black's structure remains weak with the isolated pawn. }
11... Bg4
{ Black continues to fight for the d4-square by pinning the knight on f3.   11...Qd6  12.Be3  doesn't stop White's idea when Black cannot play  12...Bc7  due to  13.Bc5  and he loses material due to the pin on f8.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp2nppp/1bn5/1B1p4/8/1NP2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 7 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a6  only helps White to bring the bishop to a better square by playing  12.Bd3  . }
12. Be3
{ The standard follow-up of Re1. Once again, it is safe to stop our preparation here, but let us see a bit more to understand the upcoming middlegame. }
12... Bxe3
{ A sad necessity.   12...Bc7  13.h3  Bh5  13.Bc5  doesn't look bright with the pin on f8. }
13. Rxe3 Nf5 14. Re1
{ Now Black needs to act very fast to avoid getting pushed back starting with h3. }
14... Nh4
{ The most natural.  After  14...Nd6  15.Be2  Nc4  White consolidates his position with  16.Qc2  , followed by Nbd4, and Black remains with his usual weak IQP. }
15. Be2 { We are getting away from the pin and welcoming piece trade. } 15...
Re8 { Black tries his best to build up some initiative with Rxe2 threat. } 16.
Nfd4
{ A novelty. The knight on h4 can be misplaced at times; no need to exchange it. }
16... Bxe2 17. Rxe2 Qd7 { Preparing a square to retreat } 18. h3
{ Taking time to ensure the king's safety. Black's activity and threats have come to an end and once again it is time to congratulate him on his permanent weakness on d5 😊. }
