{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 e6
{ This move intends to fight for the center by playing d5 next. } 3. d4
{ Given a chance, this move is our automatic reply. } 3... cxd4
{ This dubious move, abandoning the fight for the center at once, is strangely popular. Black just gets a bad version of the French Defense. }
4. cxd4 Nf6
{ Black is postponing ...d5, but sooner or later, Black will have to play it anyway. Once the knight is kicked from f6, it will usually find itself on awkward squares. }
5. Nc3
{ The disadvantage of including cxd4 is apparent here as White gets to play Nc3, which is the ideal square of the knight right now. }
5... Bb4
{ Black keeps building pressure on White's e4 pawn, but White is ready to take care of that. }
6. Bd3
{ Defending the pawn on e4 and preparing a harmonious development with a solid center. }
6... Nc6 7. Ne2
{ This move is aimed against Black's idea of playing  7...d5  8.e5  Ne4  when White will go  9.O-O  , and the c3-knight remains protected with the knight on e2, and Black's knight on e4 gets into trouble. }
7... O-O 8. O-O
{ White has an excellent pawn center and easy play. Any d5-ideas by Black will always be met with e5. }
