1. e4 c5 2. c3 d6
{ The third most popular move in the position after  2...d5  and  2...Nf6  .   However, this move does little to stop White's expansion in the center with d2-d4. The weird move  2...Qc7  has no independent value, as, after  3.d4  d6  , we will get to a position covered under @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  3.d4  Qc7  . }
3. d4
{ We won't hesitate to grab the center, of course. Now Black has various moves, and most of them don't even pretend to be fighting for equality. }
3... cxd4
{ Just abandoning any fight for the center and freeing c3 for the white knight. White is clearly better from now on. We were surprised to see more than a thousand games played in this direction! }
4. cxd4 { The mission 'dream center' accomplished 😊. } 4... Nf6
{ Other moves don't change anything. White develops and has a significant edge. Black could play  5...d5  , but why on earth did he play 2... d6? 😊. }
5. Nc3
{ One of the main drawbacks of 3... cxd4 comes to light. It is a pleasure to defend e4 with a nice developing move. }
5... a6
{ To control b5, and maybe prepare b7-b5 one day. Other moves are equally grim.  5...g6  6.Nf3  Bg7  7.Bb5  is coveredhere under the 2... g6 move order. }
6. f4
{ Why not? With all the time White has, it makes sense to develop as aggressively as possible. }
6... e6
{ Establishing a pawn in the center. White was already threatening to cause damage with e4-e5. }
7. Nf3
{ White finishes development and starts generating serious threats with e4-e5. Black has no compensation against White's massive control in the center. }
