{ White ignores the Bg4 plan as f6 has been committed. The precise reason for this will be cleared after the next two moves. }
8... Bg4 9. h3 { Forcing Black to take on f3. } 9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3
{ The pawn on d5 comes under attack and Black is obliged to play e6. } 10... e6
{ Now we see the disadvantage of having played f6. Black would very much like to have his pawn back on f7.   The f6-break would be great after Black has castled, but how is he going to castle now? His knight on g8 cannot move, and we are not going to take on f6 😊. }
11. O-O { White ignores the pawn and plays for the attack. } 11... fxe5
{ Otherwise, the knight on g8 would never come out. Playing f5 would stabilise White's center forever. }
12. dxe5 Ne7
{ Playing  12...Bxe5  13.Re1  is as good as resigning when Black's king sits on fire. }
13. Bg5
{ A very crucial move. Black was one move away from being okay with Nf5. Now he is not on time. }
13... Qc7 14. Rac1
{ White tactically stops Nf5, as after  14...Nf5  15.Nxd5  exd5  16.Qxd5  Black's position collapses like a house of cards. His king in the center gets no place to hide.   On the other hand,  14...a6  15.Bxe7  , followed by Bxc6, doesn't look bright either when Black's king remains in the center. }
