e5 { The simplest way to gain more space and a better position. } 5... Bg7
{ Black plans to castle quickly.   5...Nh6  6.Nc3  Bg7  transposes to the lines that we will examine now. }
6. Nc3
{ White delays Nf3 to stop Black from playing Bg4. The light-squared bishop lacks any decent square to develop. }
6... Nc6
{ The most popular move. Black goes for the d4-pawn and waits for White to play Nf3 and then opt for Bg4. }
7. Bb5
{ White immediately pins the knight and keeps a strategic threat of taking on c6 timely. }
7... Nh6
{ Playing  7...a6  only helps White to play  8.Bxc6  , which he would like to play anyways at some point. This way, Black also loses the  option of getting any Ba6 ideas in the future. }
8. h3
{ Simple and logical. This small move kills the knight on h6 and the bishop on c8. Not only does it controls the g4-square, but for the future, it is also ready to pounce with g4 if one of the minor pieces lands on f5. }
8... O-O 9. Nf3 f6
{ Black tries to break the center rapidly. Playing slow with  9...Bf5  10.O-O  Be4  doesn't help when White gets a nice tempo with  11.Ng5  and keeps his center solid. }
10. O-O
{ White can ignore the threat on e5 as the knight on h6 will be hanging after the mass trade on e5. }
10... Nf7 { Building more pressure on e5. } 11. exf6 exf6
{ After  11...Bxf6  12.Re1  Black gets a permanent weak pawn structure. Even if he manages to break with e5 still, the pawn on d5 will become weak. White gets an overwhelming advantage. }
12. Re1
{ With Ba4-Bb3 coming, Black's position looks terrible when he must take care of the pawn on d5, and his bishops lack good squares. }
