1. e4 c5 2. c3 b6
{ Black gives up the center without fighting. Naturally, White takes over with normal logical moves. }
3. d4
{ Our standard response. If Black doesn't stop us from taking control of the center, we will go for it. }
3... e6 { Black takes care of d5 before playing Bb7. } 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. Bd3
{ White keeps developing logically and keeps the better center. } 5... Nf6 6.
Qe2
{ It is astonishing that more than 1600 games have already reached this position.   In the computer world, this is already +1.35 for White, and our chess understanding also says White should be clearly better at this point. }
6... d5
{ It makes sense to challenge the center, although White is well-equipped to take care of it. }
7. e5
{ White gets into a French setup when Black's pieces are horribly placed, giving White a tremendous position. }
7... Nfd7
{ Unfortunately, this has to be played.   7...Ne4  might look tempting, but Black's only active piece will be immediately exchanged after White goes  8.Nbd2  and Black will be left with a lousy center, lack of space, and underdeveloped. }
8. Be3
{ Almost automatically, White castles in this position which we did not like much. It gives the additional option of creating counterplay with future g5-ideas.   It is better to take care of the queenside development first, and to seal Black's hope of progressing on the kingside by playing h4.😊 }
8... Nc6
{ If Black tries to exchange the light-squared bishop with  8...Qc8  with the idea of Ba6 next, then an excellent strategic idea is to opt for  9.a4  Ba6  10.Bb5  to make sure if Black trades the bishop on b5, we take with the a4-pawn, and both Black's knights would remain stuck for a long time. }
9. h4
{ A fantastic strategic concept. We already have a strong center, and it is time to expand on the other wing. White intends to play h5-Rh3-Kf1 and asks Black how he will make any progress. }
9... cxd4
{ We could not find any other sensible resource for Black. Black goes for the d3-bishop with the idea of getting Nb4 after White takes on d4 with the pawn. }
10. cxd4 Nb4 { Now or never. White would play a3 otherwise. } 11. Bb5 a6 12.
Ba4 { We won't give the bishop for the d7-knight, obviously. } 12... Bc6
{ Black forces us to trade the bishop since White cannot retreat with the bishop due to Bb5-ideas. }
13. Bxc6 Nxc6 14. h5
{ Going forward on the kingside with the idea to play h6 next. } 14... h6
{ Otherwise White would have played h6. } 15. Rh3
{ White is clearly better here. Why? Ask both kings where they are going to hide, and you will have a big smile on your face 😊. }
