1. e4 c5 2. c3 b6
{ Black gives up the center without fighting. Naturally, White takes over with normal logical moves. }
3. d4
{ Our standard response. If Black doesn't stop us from taking control of the center, we will go for it. }
3... Bb7
{ Black attacks the e4-pawn without taking cxd4 in order to prevent White from playing Nc3. }
4. d5
{ Blocking the bishop and taking more space in the center. It is important to understand why we are not sticking to a similar setup as we did against 3... e6.  After @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/p2ppppp/1p6/2p5/3PP3/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb7  4.Bd3  Nf6  5.Qe2  Black will not transpose with  5...e6  , but play  5...cxd4  6.cxd4  Nc6  when dealing with the double threat of Nxd4 and Nb4 would be difficult.  Another way to have a clear concept is if Black allows us to play d5 by not playing e6, we go for d5, and if he stops us from doing that by starting with e6, then we opt for Bd3-Qe2 setups. }
4... Nf6 { 4...e6  5.c4  is similar to 4... Nf6 and 5... e6. } 5. Qc2
{ White will play c4-Nc3-/Nf3-Be2-O-O and slowly consolidate his position. Black doesn't have enough counter in this Benoni structure.   We refrain from putting the bishop on d3 to avoid d7-Nbd7-Ne5 ideas in the future. Hence we want the bishop to be placed on e2. }
5... e6
{ The only way to justify the bishop's role on b7 is to attack d5 asap. } 6. c4
{ Of course that is the main reason we decided to play d5, knowing that we can cement the d5-pawn with c4 😊. }
6... exd5
{ Trying to play like a Benko gambit with  6...b5  would be a disaster after  7.e5  Ng8  8.Nc3  when White dominates the center, and Black's pieces are heavily underdeveloped. }
7. exd5
{ Avoiding the trap set by Black. The obvious  7.cxd5  Qe7!  would put White in a difficult position when saving his central pawns will be an issue. By taking exd5, White is killing the bishop on b7. }
7... Bd6
{ 7...b5  8.Nc3  bxc4  9.Bxc4  doesn't change the future of the b7-bishop, and White remains better. }
8. Nf3 O-O 9. Nc3 { Not worried about any check on the e-file due to Be2. }
9... Na6 10. Be2
{ Black does not have any counterplay. White will slowly improve his position. He has a better center and more space. This position occurred in a correspondence game, and White won easily. }
