[Black "2... d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Bb5+ Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Nf6
{ Black would like to take the pawn on d5 with the knight next. That is a nice thought, but White won't make his life easy.   Many strong players have tried this particular sideline, especially Indian youngsters who played it in their online games. The line got special attention when Magnus played this against Nils Grandelius in Chessable Masters 2022. We shall maintain our strategy and bypass long lines and create our own system 😊 }
4. Bb5+
{ White is not just developing with checks but forcing Black to block it on d7. White also points out that if he ever plays c4, the light-squared bishop won't be passive.  If we go strictly by several games played,  4.d4  is the main move, but the text move is much stronger. }
4... Bd7
{ This forces the trade that White initiated, but White doesn't mind that, as it makes it easier to play c4 in the future. }
5. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ After  5...Nbxd7  6.c4  Black just remains a pawn down for nothing. White also managed to trade the light-squared bishop, which makes his position significantly better with material advantage. }
6. c4
{ We see the obvious advantage of not having the bishop on f1. White will castle faster, and he doesn't have to bother about a lousy bishop on f1 with his central pawn structure being on the white squares. }
6... e6
{ The only way to create some threats on White's strong center. Targeting the tail with  6...b5  only helps White to consolidate his center and development by going  7.d3  . }
7. dxe6
{ The most straightforward route to get an advantage.   Black has the option of either breaking his pawn structure with fxe6 and remaining a pawn down or taking with the queen and exchanging queens after we go Qe2 and remain a pawn down.   In either case, he will remain a pawn down😊. }
