{ Going for the c5-bishop to gain more tempos and space on the queenside. }
12... O-O
{ The most human move and the most likely move we will see in OTB games.  The engine's top choice is to go for  12...b6  to ensure he can play  13.b4  Bd6  @@StartBracket@@no more c5-business@@EndBracket@@, but any mortal would get nervous about a future Qd2-Rd1 when the bishop must return. The top line of the computer goes  14.Qd2  Bb7  15.Rd1  Ke7  @@StartBracket@@the point you should call arbiter and search for hidden device@@EndBracket@@.  First of all, no one is playing like this. Secondly, engines still give some slight advantage for White after  16.h3  Rhd8  17.Qe1  and practically it more than slight edge😊. }
13. b4 Be7 14. Qd4
{ A brilliant move. Taking full advantage of the misplaced knight on d7, which cannot approach the queen with Nc6. Meanwhile, White threatens Bf4. }
14... e5 { That was the only way to get to the queen. } 15. Qe3
{ White aims for the simple Bb2-Rac1-Rfd1-Nd5, and Black can do very little about it while defending the pawn on e5 and also dealing with his bishop on c8. White remains clearly better.   This position occurred in the game Dvoirys, S @@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@ -Doroshkievich, V @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ Rostov on Don, 1993. }
