[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 2...d5 3.exd5 Nf6"]
[Black "2... d5 3.exd5 Nf6 4.Bb5+ Nbd7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Nf6
{ Black would like to take the pawn on d5 with the knight next. That is a nice thought, but White won't make his life easy.   Many strong players have tried this particular sideline, especially Indian youngsters who played it in their online games. The line got special attention when Magnus played this against Nils Grandelius in Chessable Masters 2022. We shall maintain our strategy and bypass long lines and create our own system 😊 }
4. Bb5+
{ White is not just developing with checks but forcing Black to block it on d7. White also points out that if he ever plays c4, the light-squared bishop won't be passive.  If we go strictly by several games played,  4.d4  is the main move, but the text move is much stronger. }
4... Nbd7
{ Black doesn't help White to trade the bishop on b5 so that after White goes c4, the bishop on b5 can be harassed. }
5. d4
{ We are bypassing the main theory, which is to protect the pawn with  5.c4  .  The concept behind our move  5.d4  is to capitalize on development while Black will be busy taking the pawn on d5, and we will also gain further tempos by attacking the knight on d5 at the right moment. }
5... a6
{ The strongest response and it has been played by some of the brightest Indian kids. Black goes for the bishop on b5 before addressing the pawn on d5. White usually takes on c5.  Attacking the bishop with  5...Qb6  takes away the b6-square for the d7-knight. White can calmly play  6.Bc4  and Black will be missing any Nb6 ideas.  The only thing that remains is to see if Black takes  6...cxd4  , but White has an ice-cool response with  7.Nf3  when Black remains underdeveloped and engines are already giving clear advantage for White. }
6. Be2
{ This position has occurred only four times so far, but we are confident once this course gets out, we will see this position more frequently😊.   White is changing the course of play now. He is not interested in defending the pawn but claims that Black's pieces are awkwardly placed. The knight on d5 will give extra tempo with c4, and the knight on d7 belongs to c6. }
6... Nxd5
{ That was Black's main point of starting with ...a6. Now the X-ray attack from d1 on the d5-knight is not effective anymore due to the X-ray defense from the queen on d8. }
7. Nf3
{ As mentioned earlier, White is only interested in rapid development, and plays against Black's oddly placed knights. }
7... e6
{ Otherwise, White might get c4-d5 both. Playing  7...b5  weakens Black's queenside once White goes  8.a4  . }
8. c4 N5f6 9. O-O
{ This will be technically a novelty over Shevchenko - Erigaisi from the Junior Speed Blitz final 2021.  In the game mentioned above, White started with  9.Nc3  . The advantage of starting with  9.O-O  gets clear against the  9...cxd4  variation, which we will see later.  For now, let's just say we want to castle asap😊. }
9... Qc7
{ Following the way Arjun played against 9.Nc3.  The idea is that Black doesn't want to play  9...Be7  due to  10.dxc5  when taking with the bishop on c5 would result in loss of tempo and trading the queen after  10...Nxc5  11.Qxd8  doesn't look bright with the dead bishop on c8.  Black will lose further tempos with the knight on c5 when White opts for Be3-c5 etc. }
10. Nc3
{ We wait for Black to move his bishop from f8 before taking dxc5. Meanwhile,  10...b6  runs into  11.d5  when Black's king gets stuck in the center.  Despite playing a novelty earlier, we get a game again with a transposition. This particular game came from the French defense😊.  We don't have to get intimidated or fearful as the current position is just better for us. However, for academic purposes and curiosity, let us give the opening moves to understand how the transposition occurred. @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.Nd2  dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  5.c4  Ngf6  6.Nc3  c5  7.Nf3  a6  8.Be2  Qc7  9.O-O  and we have the current position😊. }
10... cxd4 11. Qxd4
{ We have seen a similar theme in the 9...cxd4 lines. The queen heads for the lovely h4-square. }
11... Bc5 12. Qh4
{ We can stop here by saying White has a clear edge, and almost any engine moves give White an advantage. However, we want to show one particularly interesting idea that can be good for improving the general understanding of chess. }
12... O-O 13. Rd1
{ White continues to develop normally, while Black has to solve issues with his bishop on c8. }
13... b6 14. Qf4
{ Surprise! White offers to trade queens😊. Black's lack of development will become more prominent after this trade when the pressure on the d-file increases.  For instance, after  14...Qxf4  15.Bxf4  the threats of Na4 are incredibly annoying.  15...Bb7  16.Na4  Be7  17.Ne5  is a sample line when Black's pawn on b6 is about to fall, and engines give a winning advantage already. }
14... e5 15. Qg3
{ The white queen is now nicely placed on g3, aiming at e5 and threatening Bh6 ideas. The bishop on c5 for Black will attack soon after White goes a3-b4. The e5-pawn becomes a burden for Black, and he needs to keep defending that.   Once White gets a3-b4, the rook will soon come to c1 once the bishop moves, and the queen on c7 will start to feel uncomfortable. No wonder engines think White has a significant advantage here. }
