1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Bf5
{ We will be seeing all sorts of Bf5 setups in this chapter. There are various transpositions and move orders, but we will ensure utmost clarity and no room for confusion.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bf5  will eventually transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5  with or without the inclusion of cxd4.  The primary idea of the Bf5 setup is to play e6 without locking the bishop on c8. There are also additional ideas with Bxb1 to stop Nc3 ideas after cxd4-cxd4 that we will see later. }
5. Nf3
{ White's main argument here is against the queen on d5, which can be attacked in the future, and Black's lack of development on the kingside. }
5... Bxb1
{ One of the worst possible continuations, but we should be prepared for such ideas. In some positions, it is playable, but Black is pushing it too far without developing other pieces. }
6. Rxb1 Qxa2
{ Black tries to justify his previous move by going for the pawn. After  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  we will transpose to similar positions that we covered after the 5... cxd4 move order. }
7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne5
{ Among many other ways to win the game, we find this the most aesthetically pleasing and strongest. }
8... Qxb1 9. O-O
{ There is no rush at all. Black's king is not running anywhere. } 9... Qe4 10.
Re1 Qd5 11. Qa4
{ The evaluation of +8 is not superficial. Black cannot deal with many threats like Nxc6, Bc4-Bxf7/d5, etc.  The best move according to machines is  11...Rc8  12.Bc4  Qxe5  giving up the queen 😊. }
