6. Bb5+
{ Keeping similar ideas like in most of the lines in Bf5 setups. This way, preparation, and understanding of the line become simpler. Also, we should not spend too much energy and kill memory space on such sidelines.   Keeping it similar, getting away from the mainline, and surprising our opponents while having complete clarity in mind. What better can we ask for😊. }
6... Nbd7
{ After  6...Nc6  , we suggest the simple memory space-saving move  7.Be3  that transposes to 5...Nc6 lines. Curious players can also study  7.c4  , a novelty that might be stronger but requires memorization of more concrete lines.  We feel practically it is easier to keep  7.Be3  in mind as in the case of 5...Nc6, we will be forced into Be3 anyways.   6...Bd7  loses the entire point of the Bf5 setups, and White can simply play  7.Be2  , where his bishop is nicely developed and intends to castle next, while Black's concept of Bf5 failed miserably with his bishop returning to d7. }
