5. Nf3
{ White's main argument here is against the queen on d5, which can be attacked in the future, and Black's lack of development on the kingside. }
5... Nc6
{ We could reach the same position from the 4... Nc6 move order also. Black ignores the kingside for now and increases pressure on the d4-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ Bringing more support to the d4-pawn and threatening to play c4-d5 next, as Qe4 doesn't come with a check anymore. }
6... cxd4
{ One of the most logical ways to continue.  Some games continued most radically with  6...O-O-O  , but computers rightly give +2 after  7.Nbd2  when soon Bc4 will come with a tempo and Black's king on c8 is exposed, White will take dxc5 and start expanding on the queenside. }
7. Nxd4
{ We don't mind the trade on d4, which will expose Black's king on e8 from the a4-e8 diagonal. }
7... Nf6
{ 7...O-O-O  is almost suicidal and after  8.Nd2  Black finds it very difficult to stop the multiple threats of Bc4/Nf5/Nc6 etc. He needs to take care of the f5-bishop, c6-knight, and the pawn on a7, which falls after  8...Nxd4  9.Bxd4  e5  10.Bxa7   The same is applicable for  7...Rd8  8.Nd2  when the only difference is Black's king instead of suffering on the queenside will now be dealing with issues in the center😊. }
8. Nxf5 { Pair of bishops. That's all we gotta say 😊. } 8... Qxf5 9. Bd3
{ This is nice and easy.  9.Qa4  or  9.Qb3  is stronger according to machines, but we feel practically this is easier to understand and play.  Once again, we keep our preparation easy to understand, saving memory space and getting positions that will be practically annoying for our opponents. There is no need to remember a bunch of computer moves in every sideline 😊. }
9... Qd5 10. O-O
{ Black has to make sure to do something rapid; soon, White will unpin himself, and the Black king in the center will get into trouble. }
10... O-O-O 11. Be2
{ Threatening to move the queen to a4 given a chance when Black's king would soon be dead with Bf3 coming. }
11... Qxd1 { Now we get closer to an endgame with double bishop advantage. }
12. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 13. Bxd1
{ White is strategically better for having pair of bishops and a queenside pawn majority, which is ideal for endgames.   The only thing that remains is analyzing whether Black can create something immediately dynamic. }
13... Nd5 14. Bc1
{ Our advantage is strategic. All we need is to consolidate our position and restrict Black's immediate threats. Keeping the d2-square free for the knight on b1. }
14... e6 15. g3
{ Just take a moment to appreciate how we restrict Black's knights before preparing Nd2.   We don't give a damn about the weaknesses on the light squares as Black is missing the light-squared bishop, and we still have ours 😊. }
15... Be7 16. Nd2
{ The knight comes out while keeping its counterparts restricted. We have two plans at our disposal, and both are equally good.   We can bring the king to e2 via f1. Once again, we can see how our pawns on g3 and c3 secure the king on e2. Then play a4-Nc4-Bc2 and take more space on the queenside.   The other plan is to play Be2 remove the knight from d2, get the c1-bishop out, and put the rook on d1. We don't mind trading rooks with the pawns on both wings and having a pair of bishops give us a long-term edge, while Black cannot create any immediate threats.   Our advantage is slight but durable, and for Black, it is frustrating to play for two results on the negative side. }
