1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Bf5
{ We will be seeing all sorts of Bf5 setups in this chapter. There are various transpositions and move orders, but we will ensure utmost clarity and no room for confusion.  @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Bf5  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bf5  will eventually transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bf5  with or without the inclusion of cxd4.  The primary idea of the Bf5 setup is to play e6 without locking the bishop on c8. There are also additional ideas with Bxb1 to stop Nc3 ideas after cxd4-cxd4 that we will see later. }
5. Nf3
{ White's main argument here is against the queen on d5, which can be attacked in the future, and Black's lack of development on the kingside. }
5... Nc6
{ We could reach the same position from the 4... Nc6 move order also. Black ignores the kingside for now and increases pressure on the d4-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ Bringing more support to the d4-pawn and threatening to play c4-d5 next, as Qe4 doesn't come with a check anymore. }
6... e6
{ Black opens up the f8-bishop and also takes care of White's c4-d5 ideas. } 7.
Na3
{ We cannot play in the same manner as 6... Nf6 line where we go  7.Bb5  as after  7...cxd4  8.c4  Black will have  8...Bb4+  this time.   On the other hand,  7.Na3  is useful here as the complications with  7...cxd4  favor us, which we will be seeing now. }
7... cxd4 8. Nb5
{ An intermediate thematic move, giving a colossal fork threat on c7. } 8...
O-O-O
{ Black's typical response against Nb5. Securing the king on the queenside and stopping Nc7 ideas. }
9. Nbxd4
{ Black usually plays 9... Ng4 to attack the bishop on e3 in the 6...Nf6 line, but this vital move is not available in the 6... e6 variation. }
9... Bc5
{ After  9...Nf6  both  10.Qa4  targetting c6 or  10.Qb3  to trade queens and get a pleasant queenless middlegame position, it favors White when Black doesn't have time to attack the e3-bishop any time soon. }
10. Nxc6 Qxc6 11. Nd4
{ Black's king comes under attack once he trades on d4, as we will be taking with the c-pawn. Playing b4 next is another idea White has to chase the bishop from c5.   Engines are giving an advantage to White which is mainly because our king is much safer than its counterpart. }
