8... Qe4 { Pinning the bishop and aiming to go Qg4 in case White plays Nbd2. }
9. Nbd2
{ It is also possible to take  9.Qxd4  but it doesn't give the strategic threat of Qxd6 compared to the 8...Qxd6 line. }
9... Qg4
{ The position gets very wild and dynamic now. Black threatens to take on e3 and g2. }
10. Bxc6+
{ The move order is very crucial here.   10.Qa4  with the same idea would be losing for White since after  10...dxe3  11.Bxc6  Black is not obliged to take back on c6, and he can play  11...Nd7  , which would be a disaster for White. }
10... bxc6 11. Qa4 { Black has no time to take on e3 anymore. } 11... Bd7
{ Only move to stay alive. After  11...Rd8  12.Nxd4  Rxd4  White has an excellent intermediate  13.f3  when Black eventually cannot keep the protection of the d4-rook and loses heavy material. }
12. Nxd4
{ White is one move away from castling while  12...c5  is met by  13.Nb5  . }
12... Qxg2 13. O-O-O
{ Only move, but also the most obvious one. White's king remains secured on the queenside, and Black is still yet to solve issues with his king and kingside development. }
13... c5 14. Nb5 { Threatening Nc7 now. } 14... Qb7
{ An amazing retreat. Black stops the threat of Nc7, brings his queen back to defense, and threatens a6.   It seems like White's attack has come to an end. What to do now? }
15. Qa6
{ We meet a good move with a brilliant move😊. White stops a6 in a genius way. The queen on b7 is under attack, and taking on a6 allows Nc7 fork. }
15... Rb8
{ 15...Qxa6  16.Nc7  Kd8  17.Nxa6  not only keeps Black's king in the center but also loses the c5-pawn. }
16. a4
{ The pawn on a4 protects the knight on b5, which covers the queen on a6 with the help of the Nc7 fork. One of the weird and pretty chains we can witness here 😊.   Meanwhile, Black's king remains in the center, and his queenside pawns are too weak; on top of everything, he is also behind in development. }
