1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4
{ One of the worst possible ways to opt for Bg4 setups; allowing White to play Nc3 and attack the queen on d5. }
7. Nc3
{ Given a chance, White will always put the knight on c3. That is the main disadvantage of taking on d4 that early. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black tries to shatter White's pawn structure while claiming  8.Nxd5  Bxd1  9.Nc7  would eventually result in the knight's trap on a8.   7...Qd8  8.Qb3  would instantly highlight the weakness on b7 and the disadvantage of a premature Bg4. }
8. gxf3
{ Structural weakness will come later, but the lead in development and the weak king on e8 will speak faster. }
8... Qa5
{ 8...Qe6+  9.Be2  doesn't change when the threats of d5/Bb5/Qa4 kill Black, who has no time to finish his development.   Black's advantage after  8...Qa5  is strategic. Give Black one more move to consolidate with e6, and he will be better, but it is still one move away... }
9. Qb3
{ Black's seeds of strategic advantage will never grow, while White's dynamic advantage is paying immediately.   The threats on b7 and the exposed king on e8 @@StartBracket@@note how much difference it makes to lose the light square bishop@@EndBracket@@ are unbearable, and Black is close to losing at this point. }
