[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ One of the popular ways to play Bg4 without allowing White to get Nc3 and make sure the queen on d5 feels safe.   However, as we will see now, there is a different issue with playing Bg4 without including cxd4. }
6. dxc5
{ The mainline by the number of moves is  6.Be2  , but we are confident things will soon change once this course gets out 😊. White takes on c5 and gives Black an immediate choice.  1. Trade the queen on d1 and remain a pawn down for a while.  2. Take on c5 and allow White to play Be3 with a tempo. }
6... Qxc5 7. Be3
{ White will not miss the chance to develop his piece with a tempo, and Black must move his queen for the third time within the first seven moves. }
7... Qc7
{ The queen finally finds a secure place where it cannot be disturbed easily.   7...Qh5  8.Nbd2  would leave Black's queenside exposed, and once White plays Qb3, the pawn on b7 will miss the queen on h5 and the bishop on g4. }
8. h3
{ Asking Black to decide which diagonal he would like to stay in. The bishop on g4 was ideal for controlling different diagonals. }
8... Bh5
{ 8...Bf5  9.Nd4  gives additional tempo, and any other square doesn't look attractive for the bishop. }
9. Na3
{ The queen on c7 turns out to be not immune from attack. White prepares nasty Nd5 ideas now. }
9... a6 { There was no other way to stop this threat. } 10. Nc4
{ Exploiting the weakness Black created in the last move. White heads for the b6-square. }
10... Nbd7
{ Controlling the b6-square.   10...Nc6  11.Bb6  Qf4  12.Qd2  leaves Black in an unpleasant position when his queenside remains locked with or without queens, and slowly but surely, White will one day start expanding there with b4-a4-a5/b5 and gain more space. }
11. g4
{ A superb and very important move. Our advantage is dynamic. Which means time is the key. If we give Black a few moves, he will consolidate his position.   With each move, White is creating new threats and not giving Black any time. }
11... Bg6 12. g5
{ Giving Black no time to develop his kingside. All he needed was to play e6 once, but since move six, there was no time as White kept giving new threats with his energetic moves. }
12... Nh5
{ 12...Ne4  13.Nh4  will pick up the bishop on g6, and the knight on e4 will become a target.  For instance, after  13...e6  14.Qf3  engines are already giving more than +1 for White since soon White will take on g6 and opt for O-O-O while Black shall remain underdeveloped, lacks a pair of bishops, and on top of everything, it would be tough to find a safe place for his king. }
13. Qd4
{ The centralized queen cannot be attacked, hence it is the best place for her. }
13... e6
{ Finally, after seven moves, Black got a chance to play e6. He now wants to go Be7 and O-O-O. }
14. Rd1
{ Threatening to play Nd6 at the right moment and get a pair of bishops.   14...Bc5  would be a blunder due to  15.Qxd7  Qxd7  16.Rxd7  Bxe3  17.Rxb7  and White will be up in material.   The above variation is the reason why we chose  14.Rd1  over  14.O-O-O  as Bxe3 doesn't come with a check. }
