[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nf6 5.Nf3 Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ One of the popular ways to play Bg4 without allowing White to get Nc3 and make sure the queen on d5 feels safe.   However, as we will see now, there is a different issue with playing Bg4 without including cxd4. }
6. dxc5
{ The mainline by the number of moves is  6.Be2  , but we are confident things will soon change once this course gets out 😊. White takes on c5 and gives Black an immediate choice.  1. Trade the queen on d1 and remain a pawn down for a while.  2. Take on c5 and allow White to play Be3 with a tempo. }
6... Qxd1+
{ Black trades queen and hopes for compensation against White's king on d1. }
7. Kxd1
{ This time our advantage is purely materialistic and a bit strategic as we have a majority in the queenside.   All remains to ensure there is no immediate attack against our king in the center. This is not a real issue without the queens, as we will see now. }
7... e5
{ The double threats of e4 and Bxc5 are nothing but an illusion. There is only one threat, Bxc5, which we will take care of now.   7...Nc6  will be coveredhere after the 4...Nc6 move order. }
8. b4
{ White completely ignores the other threat of e4 and cements his pawn on c5. }
8... e4
{ No other ways to justify the previous move. Black goes for the knight on f3. }
9. h3
{ It resembles the Botvinnik system in Semi-Slav, where Black does this kind of trick with a similar structure in the queenside.   The biggest advantage for White compared to that system is queens are off, which makes White's king on a1 not just safe but stronger as it will go to queenside faster😊. }
9... Bh5
{ After  9...exf3  10.hxg4  Nxg4  11.Kc2  Nxf2  12.Bb5  Black king will die in the center, and white will also regain the f3-pawn after forcing a check with his rook, irrespective of Black's next move. }
10. g4 { The only but obvious follow-up. We go for the bishop. } 10... Nxg4 11.
hxg4 Bxg4
{ One of the main positions with 350+ games. Several GMs opted for this position as Black.   We will now see a groundbreaking move that has not been tried at an IM/GM level yet, and that gives White a winning position😊. }
12. Rg1
{ White basically wins the game with this shocking move. Surprisingly it has not been tried at a high level yet.   White completely ignores the material part and forces Black to take on f3. Black's main problem will be his king on e8, and there will be no one to protect her majesty. It is shocking how quickly the attack develops against Black's king. }
12... Bxf3+
{ Sooner or later, Black will have to take it, so wasting further tempos on it makes no sense. }
13. Kc2
{ Why do strong machines give close to +2 here? Look at the king on e8 and try to find some defender for him.   The bishop in f3 looks strong but does nothing to protect the king. White intends to play Bb5/Bf4/Nd2 and start attacking in the center. }
13... h5 { Hoping to queen the pawn is nothing but daydreaming. } 14. Bf4
{ Completely ignoring Black's wild dream and focusing on development. } 14...
h4
{ 14...Bg4  15.Bg2  f5  16.Nd2  would soon blast the center with f3, and the king on e8 will be on fire. }
15. Nd2
{ The bishop on f3 will be gone, and it will be a good time for Black to shake hands. The king on e8 is not going to survive for long. }
