{ White develops fast and keeps Black's development under control. The bishop on f8 cannot move as he must protect the pawn on g7. }
15... Nc6 16. Be3
{ Black gets wholly paralyzed. White plans to expand on the queenside, while Black's pawns on the kingside cannot make any progress.   Engines evaluation keeps growing, claiming White is winning here despite being a pawn down. }
16... O-O-O
{ After  16...h6  17.b5  Nd8  18.Bh3  Black's pawns again come to a standstill and soon falls after  18...g6  19.Ne5   Playing  16...a6  17.a4  doesn't improve anything for Black. }
17. b5 Nb8 18. a4
{ It is a matter of time before Black will have to give material to save his king.   Let's stop here with an evaluation of close to +3. We will just throw our pawns at Black's king now 😊. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4
{ As usual, the inclusion of cxd4 before playing Bg4 favors White. This helps White to get Nc3 with a tempo. }
7. Nc3 Bxf3
{ Any other move gives +4 for White😊. We meet every single queen retreat with d5.  For example,  7...Qa5  8.d5  Ne5  9.Qb3  threatens on e5 and b7 and after  9...Nxf3  10.gxf3  threats of Qxb7/fxg4/Bb5 are impossible to meet.   7...Qd8  8.d5  Ne5  9.Nxe5  Bxd1  10.Bb5  is a common theme in many different openings, and it is good to know about such motifs. }
8. gxf3
{ 8.Nxd5  is also possible, which gives White some advantage, but we felt the text move is much stronger and easier to play. }
8... Qxd4
{ Black is obliged to take here. Without the light-squared bishop, it would be too dangerous to allow White to play d5 and open up the a4-e8 diagonal. }
9. Qxd4 Nxd4
{ How to deal with Nxf3 and Nc2 forks now? A brilliant move is waiting for Black... }
10. Nb5
{ A fantastic counter fork trick. The entire line is based on this idea. Without this resource, we could not have entered this variation. }
10... e5
{ Keeping the knight on d4 and hoping to trap the knight on a8 while playing against White's king in the center. This was tried by Topalov in the 2010 Olympiad. }
11. Nc7+ Kd7 12. Nxa8
{ We have a whole rook extra. It is not Black's duty to prove his compensation. Our argument is our extra rook.   Let's not speak much about the comp evaluation close to +2.5 😋. }
12... Bb4+ 13. Kd1
{ A rook is a rook. Suffer a bit if you have to. We gotta adjust against a few empty checks when we get free rook 😊. }
13... Ne7
{ Black develops rapidly and threatens to take on a8 and damage the material imbalance. }
14. f4
{ Let's not forget we also have a double bishop advantage apart from being a rook up😊. Let us open up the position for fun 😊. }
14... Rxa8 15. fxe5
{ Now we are just an exchange up with a pair of bishop advantage. This will suffice to win the game 😊. }
15... Rd8 { Creating some illusionary threats on the d-file. } 16. a3
{ In the game Stevic - Topalov from the Olympiad 2010 White opted for  16.Bh3  which also gives a clear advantage, but the text move is much stronger. }
16... Ke8 17. Ra2
{ The knight can jump wherever it wants, and this doesn't bother White's king, who will improve his position by going Kc2. }
17... Nb3+ 18. Kc2 Nxc1 19. Bb5+
{ White remains one exchange up, and all Black's attack has been stopped. White is winning without any complications. }
*

