[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 Bg4
{ As usual, the inclusion of cxd4 before playing Bg4 favors White. This helps White to get Nc3 with a tempo. }
7. Nc3 Bxf3
{ Any other move gives +4 for White😊. We meet every single queen retreat with d5.  For example,  7...Qa5  8.d5  Ne5  9.Qb3  threatens on e5 and b7 and after  9...Nxf3  10.gxf3  threats of Qxb7/fxg4/Bb5 are impossible to meet.   7...Qd8  8.d5  Ne5  9.Nxe5  Bxd1  10.Bb5  is a common theme in many different openings, and it is good to know about such motifs. }
8. gxf3
{ 8.Nxd5  is also possible, which gives White some advantage, but we felt the text move is much stronger and easier to play. }
8... Qxd4
{ Black is obliged to take here. Without the light-squared bishop, it would be too dangerous to allow White to play d5 and open up the a4-e8 diagonal. }
9. Qxd4 Nxd4
{ How to deal with Nxf3 and Nc2 forks now? A brilliant move is waiting for Black... }
10. Nb5
{ A fantastic counter fork trick. The entire line is based on this idea. Without this resource, we could not have entered this variation. }
10... Nc2+
{ The best bet Black has got.   10...Nxf3  11.Ke2  runs into a double threat of Kxf3 and Nc7.   10...Ne6  11.Bc4  Rc8  12.Bd5  gives White an excellent position as  12...Rc5  13.Bxb7  Rxb5  runs into another fork with  14.Bc6  😊.   Finally,  10...O-O-O  11.Nxd4  Rxd4  12.Be3  Rd6  loses the pawn with  13.Bxa7  as there is no way to trap the bishop with  13...b6  since White has  14.Ba6   Thus in all these variations White gets almost an winning position. }
11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ 11...Rc8  12.Nxa7  Rc5  13.b4  is a nice deflection trick with the idea  13...Nxb4  14.Rb1  with pressure on the b-file, Black struggles to cope with finishing development on the kingside and dealing with the pressure on the queenside. }
12. Nc7+ Kd7 13. Nxa8
{ 13...e5  14.Be3  would pick up some pawns on the queenside, and White gets a winning position as it would be now impossible to trap the knight on a8. }
13... g6 { Black keeps the option of Bg7-Bh6 open. } 14. Be3
{ We keep an eye on the a7-pawn. } 14... Bh6
{ After  14...Kc6  15.f4  Black would need both e6 and Nf6 together to meet Bg2-ideas, which won't be possible in this case. }
15. Bb5+ Kd6 16. Bxa7
{ White knight will soon come out to c4 via b6, making the king on d6 more exposed, and Black knight's future on a1 is still doomed.   White also enjoys a double-bishop advantage. Black is struggling big time in this position. }
