12. Nc7+ Kd7 13. Nxa8
{ 13...e5  14.Be3  would pick up some pawns on the queenside, and White gets a winning position as it would be now impossible to trap the knight on a8. }
13... Nf6
{ Although not the most popular move, this is Black's best option here. } 14.
Bb5+ Kc8 15. Bf4
{ Stopping any Kb8 ideas. The bishop on f4 becomes strong, and Black cannot get rid of this bishop quickly.   In the exact position with the pawn on g6 instead of the Knight on f6, Black would have Bh6 ideas to trade the bishop, but that is not possible here. }
15... Nd5 16. Bg3 g5
{ The only way to stay alive in the game. Black plans to block the diagonal and then opt for Kb8-Ka8. }
17. Ke2
{ Attacking the knight on a1 and getting a fast Rc1 to attack the king. } 17...
Nf4+ { Black just makes it on time to make sure he has Kb8 after Rc1. } 18.
Bxf4 gxf4 19. Rxa1
{ The position remains tricky.  A direct  19...Kb8  20.Rd1  would put Black in danger since he cannot take the knight due to back rank mate, and there are positional threats of Rd7 as well. }
19... Bh6
{ Another precise move to stay in the game. Black wants to meet Rd1 with Rd8 ideas. }
20. Bc4
{ With proper defense, Black is likely to hold but will suffer long-term.   First of all, Black must make it until here, and even now, the pawn on f7 will fall, and White rook will get entry while Black gets busy recapturing the knight on a8. }
