[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Be3 cxd4
{ 6...Bg4  7.dxc5  Qxd1  8.Kxd1  is covered from 5... Bg4 move order, which we will examinehere. }
7. cxd4 Bg4
{ Black has taken cxd4 before playing Bg4, so our next move is easy to understand. }
8. Nc3 Qa5
{ 8...Bxf3  9.Nxd5  Bxd1  10.Nxf6  followed by Rxd1 leaves Black with double pawns on the f-file while White gets double bishop advantage. }
9. h3
{ Exploiting the disadvantage of playing a quick Bg4 and opening up the position without taking care of the kingside. }
9... Bh5
{ Black maintains the pin to justify Bg4 setups.   9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  does not just give pair of bishops for free, but also ideas like Bb5-O-O-d5 come rapidly for White while the Black king remains in the center. }
10. g4
{ The bishop is coming from g2, looking at the long diagonal, which the c8 bishop is far away from. }
10... Bg6 11. Bg2 e6 12. O-O
{ With ideas like Qb3-Ne5 etc., coming Black struggles to cope with taking care of the queenside and finishing castling on the kingside.   There are also other threats like Nh4-Nxg6 and Nd2-Nc4 at White's arsenal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ One of the most popular ways to play Bg4 setups. Black increases pressure on the d4-pawn as fast as possible while keeping the Nc3 option unavailable for White. }
6. dxc5
{ Like in all the 4... Nf6 variations, our response remains the same.   It makes the preparation easier when we have similar responses/plans. Thus it is convenient not to change the plans for every move unless it is really needed.   If Black takes ...cxd4 and then opts for ...Bg4, we go for Nc3 ideas. If he plays directly ...Bg4, we take on c5 with the pawn. This is irrespective of 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6. }
6... Qxc5 { The queen will now find it hard to find a safe square. } 7. Be3
{ Compared to the 4...Nf6 lines, Black is missing Qc7 ideas. } 7... Qa5
{ It's hard to find a better square. After  7...Qh5  8.Nbd2  soon Qb3 will happen when the queen on h5 remains far away from the action area. }
8. h3
{ A good move to ask Black to decide the diagonal for his light-squared bishop. }
8... Rd8
{ An intermediate counter move attacking the queen on d1 before moving the bishop.  After  8...Bh5  9.Na3  is annoying with the idea of Nc4 attacking the queen on a5. The game can continue with  9...e6  10.Nc4  Qc7  11.g4  Bg6  12.Nd4  with engines giving +2 for White. Ask Black's kingside pieces how they feel, and they will agree with this evaluation.  It would be impossible to stop the threats on the queenside like Nb5-Bg2/Nc6/Qa4 while Black's kingside pieces are in hibernation. }
9. Nbd2 Bxf3
{ Black decides to give up the bishop pair to buy some time for finishing development on the kingside. }
10. Qxf3
{ Now apart from being ahead in development, we also have pair of bishops to enjoy😊. }
10... Nf6 11. Nb3 Qc7 12. Bb5
{ The pin on the c6-knight is deadly, with threats like Nd4/Bxa7 on the air.  Playing  12...a6  doesn't help Black since White will take on c6 and break the structure and soon will collect those pawns while Black tries to complete his development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Bg4 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bg4
{ One of the most popular ways to play Bg4 setups. Black increases pressure on the d4-pawn as fast as possible while keeping the Nc3 option unavailable for White. }
6. dxc5
{ Like in all the 4... Nf6 variations, our response remains the same.   It makes the preparation easier when we have similar responses/plans. Thus it is convenient not to change the plans for every move unless it is really needed.   If Black takes ...cxd4 and then opts for ...Bg4, we go for Nc3 ideas. If he plays directly ...Bg4, we take on c5 with the pawn. This is irrespective of 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6. }
6... Qxd1+
{ The best choice for Black. This time taking on c5 is not ideal as after Be3, the queen doesn't have the safe retreat on c7. }
7. Kxd1
{ Our game plan remains crystal clear. We are a pawn up and we tell Black 'Please show us your compensation for the same.' }
7... Nf6
{ Black remains noncommittal and waits for White to show his hand first. He plans to meet Be3 with Nd5 and b4 with a5. }
8. Be3
{ We don't mind getting hit with Nd5. For now, we develop and bring more support to the extra pawn on c5.   8.b4  a5  9.Bb5  is not ideal as Black will have  9...axb4  10.cxb4  Nd5  and it would be impossible to keep the extra pawn. }
8... e5
{ This is more direct than  8...e6  when White can continue to develop normally with  9.Bc4  and Black do not have enough compensation for the pawn. }
9. h3
{ The simplest solution. We hit the bishop, and one way or another, the knight on f3 will get out of the pin. }
9... Bxf3+
{ 9...Bh5  10.g4  Bg6  11.Nh4  forces Black to lose a few more tempos to save the bishop.  11...Be4  12.f3  Bd5  13.Nd2  gives White almost a winning advantage when Black has no compensation for the extra pawn that White possesses. }
10. gxf3
{ We have a bad structure, but we have a pair of bishops with an extra pawn. That's a great deal 😊. }
10... Nd5
{ Otherwise, Black cannot get this pawn ever. He aims to eliminate the bishop on e3. }
11. Bc4
{ A lovely move. White transforms his material advantage into a positional one by giving up the pawn at the right moment. }
11... Nxe3+ 12. fxe3 { First, the structure got better😊. } 12... Bxc5 13. Ke2
{ It is incredible how strong engines consider these positions as overwhelming for White. Black has no targets, and White will have free play on the queenside. Let's see how the game can proceed. }
13... Ke7 14. a4 { Planning to progress on the queenside. } 14... a5 15. Nd2
{ Try to find a good square for Black's minor pieces. Difficult right? They look good, but in reality, they are more like a showpiece.   White intends to play slowly with Bb5-Ne4/Nc4. On the kingside, h4-h5-Rhg1 ideas come into mind. The pawns on f7 and g7 would come under pressure. We won't go as far as the engines by saying it is +1, but White is significantly better here. }
*

