8... Nd5 { Eliminating the bishop on e3 to weaken the pawn on c5. } 9. Bc4
{ We are welcoming Black to take on e3. } 9... Nxe3+
{ Breaking White's pawn structure. } 10. fxe3
{ Our main strength is the pawn on c5, and we not parting with that 😊. The bishop on e3 is gone, but b4 is enough to keep the pawn on c5 alive. }
10... e6
{ 10...e5  11.h3  Bxf3  12.gxf3  we examinedhere from the 8... e5 move order.   10...a5  11.Bb5  e6  12.b4  is covered from the 10... e6 move order. }
11. b4 a5
{ Black goes for the tail on b4 to put more pressure on the c5-pawn. } 12. Bb5
{ Tactically solving the attack on b4. White will take Bxc6 as soon as Black takes axb4, and he keeps the healthy extra pawn alive. }
12... axb4 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 14. cxb4
{ White remains one pawn up with a solid majority on the queenside. The threats of g6-Bg7 are not scary, as White always has a3-Ra2 ideas at his disposal.   Engines are giving White an advantage, which is hard to argue with as we don't see enough compensation for the extra pawn. }
