{ One of the most popular ways to play Bg4 setups. Black increases pressure on the d4-pawn as fast as possible while keeping the Nc3 option unavailable for White. }
6. dxc5
{ Like in all the 4... Nf6 variations, our response remains the same.   It makes the preparation easier when we have similar responses/plans. Thus it is convenient not to change the plans for every move unless it is really needed.   If Black takes ...cxd4 and then opts for ...Bg4, we go for Nc3 ideas. If he plays directly ...Bg4, we take on c5 with the pawn. This is irrespective of 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6. }
6... Qxd1+
{ The best choice for Black. This time taking on c5 is not ideal as after Be3, the queen doesn't have the safe retreat on c7. }
7. Kxd1
{ Our game plan remains crystal clear. We are a pawn up and we tell Black 'Please show us your compensation for the same.' }
7... Nf6
{ Black remains noncommittal and waits for White to show his hand first. He plans to meet Be3 with Nd5 and b4 with a5. }
8. Be3
{ We don't mind getting hit with Nd5. For now, we develop and bring more support to the extra pawn on c5.   8.b4  a5  9.Bb5  is not ideal as Black will have  9...axb4  10.cxb4  Nd5  and it would be impossible to keep the extra pawn. }
8... Nd5 { Eliminating the bishop on e3 to weaken the pawn on c5. } 9. Bc4
{ We are welcoming Black to take on e3. } 9... O-O-O
{ This helps White to unpin himself from the g4-bishop, but Black gets other options by delaying ...Nxe3. }
10. Kc1
{ The king remains safe on c1, and Black is yet to show his compensation for the extra pawn. }
10... g6
{ At very high depth and after a lot of analyses, we concluded that this move is the best option for Black. It is a challenging move to make over the board. Black doesn't go for the c5-pawn but prepares Bg7 to aim for the c3 pawn if White plays b4. }
11. Nbd2
{ We won't play b4 when Black has already shown his intention to develop the bishop on g7. We are finishing development and planning to play h3 next.  It would be nice to keep the knight on b1 for a while to have the b4 option open, but unfortunately,  11.Rd1  does not work due to a forced sequence of  11...Bxf3  12.gxf3  Nxe3  13.Rxd8  Kxd8!  14.fxe3  e6!  and everything fizzles out after  15.b4  Nxb4  16.cxb4  Bg7  17.Nc3  Bxc3  18.Rb1  when Black escapes with a draw. }
11... e6
{ To make such a brilliant move would take intense preparation, and we don't believe such move orders @@StartBracket@@g6-e6@@EndBracket@@ are humanly possible to figure out over the board.   First, Black refrains from playing e6 since White had b4 ideas. So he waited with a non-committal g6 that stops b4, and only once White developed the knight on b1 @@StartBracket@@which we had to do anyways@@EndBracket@@, now Black goes for the c5-pawn @@StartBracket@@instead of the more natural Bg7@@EndBracket@@ when we are unable to play b4.   This is too deep and intricate to navigate during a game without solid preparation. Black should omit Nxe3-fxe3 as that will felicitate White to play b4 when the c3 pawn is no longer hanging. Engines speak for themselves 😊. }
12. Bxd5
{ As we cannot play b4, we should retain our dark-squared bishop to keep the c5-pawn alive for now. }
12... Rxd5 13. Ng5
{ Gaining a tempo by attacking the pawn on f7 and preparing to chase the bishop out from g4 with h3. }
13... Ne5 14. h3
{ Going for the bishop.  14.f3  Bxc5  is a lovely trick that Black should foresee from a distance. The point is after  15.Bxc5  Nd3  16.Kc2  Nxc5  , the knight on g5, hangs, and Black escapes with equality. }
14... Be2 15. b4
{ Now we save the pawn and ask Black to show his compensation. } 15... Be7
{ Targetting the knight on g5. } 16. Ngf3
{ It is a good time to eliminate the knight on e5. } 16... Nxf3
{ After  16...Nd3  17.Kc2  , the bishop on e2, would be in trouble due to the unexpected Ng1 threat😊. }
17. Nxf3 Rhd8
{ Black keeps the double bishop and gets the d-file in control. White should show some plans to untangle the position. }
18. Rb1
{ We plan to play Re1 and move the bishop out.   There is no way Black is getting the pawn in near future. Black does have some compensation, and it would be impossible to win against engines that give a very tiny edge to White. However, Black must make this far with a series of amazing moves and then, with precise play, make a draw.   All the best for finding these over the board and then confidently holding this😊. }
