{ In a symmetrical position, White has two extra tempos  @@StartBracket@@Nf3-Nd4@@EndBracket@@, and this is our only advantage, which means we must play energetically and put as much pressure as possible. }
9... Bc5
{ Black logically develops with a tempo.  9...a6  is prophylaxis against Ndb5 ideas, but it gives another crucial tempo to White after  10.Bg5  Be7  11.O-O-O  O-O  12.Bc4   White is just one move away from finishing development with another tempo @@StartBracket@@Rhe1@@EndBracket@@, while Black's queenside pieces haven't started yet. White seizes the initiative. }
10. Ndb5
{ We are threatening Nc7 and forcing Black to compromise with his natural development.   10...Bb6  allows  11.Nd6  and the Black king get into trouble, while @@StartFEN@@rnb1k2r/pp3ppp/5n2/1Nb5/8/2N5/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Na6  11.Be2  keeps the knight on a6 misplaced, and White takes the lead in development. }
