[Black "4.d4 cxd4 5.cxd4 e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 e5
{ Black has included cxd4-cxd4 and then opted for e5.   This means the king on d1 will be exposed, Black's knight on c6 will not be restricted with our pawn on c3, and Black's bishop on f8 won't be restricted with his pawn on c5.   In simple words... do not take on e5 and allow him to take Qxd1 now😊. }
6. Nf3
{ Thanks to the inclusion of cxd4-cxd4, White now will have Nc3 ideas to attack the queen on d5. }
6... exd4
{ Black clears the center and hopes for equality.   6...Nc6  transposes to the main line.   6...Bb4  7.Bd2  Bxd2  8.Nbxd2  helps White to develop more pieces, and Bc4 comes with another tempo when computers already claim White to be close to winning.   6...Bg4  7.Be2  e4  8.Nc3  Bb4  runs into a lovely trap when White plays  10.Nd2!  Bxe2  11.Qxe2  and Black lose his central pawn exposing his king completely while staying behind the development that gives White, once again, almost a winning advantage. }
7. Qxd4
{ A simple solution that looks close to equal but is an illusion. Every tempo will count here, and the position is not as simple as it seems. }
7... Qxd4
{ The most natural move. Black trades queens and hopes to get an equal position.  Avoiding the queen trade with  7...Qe6  gives white the lead in development after  8.Be3  Nc6  9.Bb5  Bd7  10.Qd3  when it is much easier to play from the White side due to the obvious developmental advantage and the ability to occupy the open files with the rooks faster. }
8. Nxd4
{ White has two extra tempos in a symmetrical position @@StartBracket@@Nf3-Nd4@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Bb4+
{ 8...Nf6  9.Nc3  and @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/8/8/3N4/8/PP3PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...a6  9.Nc3  Nf6  will transpose into the variation we've examined previouslyhere. }
9. Bd2
{ It was also possible to play  9.Nc3  , and engines claim some edge, but we like  9.Bd2  more as it will give White three extra tempos. }
9... Bxd2+ 10. Nxd2
{ Now we have three extra tempos @@StartBracket@@Nf3-Nd4-Nd2@@EndBracket@@ in a symmetrical structure😊. }
10... Nf6 11. Nb5
{ There are different ways to play at this point, and it is purely a matter of taste how one should continue.  Moves like  11.f3  restricting the knight on f6, or going for  11.O-O-O  also makes perfect sense and gives White a pleasant position. }
11... Na6 12. Bc4 O-O 13. O-O
{ Although the position looks close to equality, Black still has to solve the problem of developing the bishop on c8.   Nd6 will come soon, and although the machine will defend such a position, it is always annoying to get tortured like this in a tournament game when White plays only for two results. }
