[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 Nc6 6. Nf3 e5
{ This line is quite popular when Black includes both cxd4 and Nc6 before playing e5.   Our response remains logical and easy to understand. Black has taken cxd4, which means our king will be exposed on d1, so we should not take dxe5. }
7. Nc3 Bb4
{ Absolutely the only move. Otherwise, White would take the pawn on e5 with dxe5 or d5-Nxe5. Black pins the knight with Bb4, but White unpins it effortlessly next. }
8. Bd2
{ Renewing the threat to take on d5 and forcing Black to give up the pair of bishops. }
8... Bxc3
{ Once again obligatory. Without this move, Black would lose a pawn either with dxe5 or d5-Nxe5. }
9. Bxc3 e4
{ Black would like to keep the position closed as White has a double bishop advantage.   9...Bg4  10.dxe5  loses a pawn.   9...exd4  10.Nxd4  not only opens up the position, which is beneficial for White due to the pair of bishops but also dealing with immediate threats like Nb5/Qe2 will be a pain for Black. }
10. Ne5 { Threatening Bc4 and forcing Black's next move. } 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5
{ Our advantage is obvious: The pair of bishops😊. } 11... Ne7
{ Another obligatory move. Black needs to finish his development on the kingside and secure his king. }
12. Be2
{ We like this simple solution. Engines give many different moves for White with a slight advantage that includes  12.a3  ,  12.Qe2  ,  12.Qb3  etc.  Each move has different purposes, but we want to keep it as simple as possible and ensure we get a pleasant position that is easier to play from the White side. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Qxd1  13.Rxd1  O-O  would lose material after  14.Bb4  due to back rank issues. }
13. Qa4
{ About 360 games reached this position, and in more than 350 games, White opted for the most common move,  13.O-O  . This idea of suddenly changing plans of not trading queens is extremely rare and has never been seen at a higher level.  There is nothing wrong with  13.O-O  and it also gives White a slight advantage, but we stick to our strategy of early surprise and take your opponent out of their preparation and comfort zone asap😊.  The idea of our move is simple: we want a quick Rd1 to attack the queen on d5. }
13... Bd7 { The most obvious move, and already White's advantage increases. }
14. Qb4
{ Attacking the knight and keeping an eye on the b7-pawn. Black is now unable to play Nc6 as the pawn on b7 hangs. }
14... Nf5 15. Rd1 Qc6 16. O-O
{ White retains his double bishop advantage. Black has a few loose points, like the bishop on d7 and the pawns on b7 and e4 that need protection.   White's advantage looks obvious. }
