[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...e6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 cxd4 6.cxd4 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  or  5...Nc6  doesn't have any independent value, and it will soon transpose to either 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 7. Nc3
{ Whether Black plays Nf6 or Nc6 or both, it doesn't change the nature of the position. White gets a quick lead in the development. }
7... Qa5
{ Black can move the queen wherever he wants, and it doesn't change our kingside development. }
8. Bd3
{ There is no exception for this. The light-squared bishop belongs to d3. }
8... Nf6 9. O-O Be7
{ Any other bishop move would allow White to play Bg5 with a threat of Bxf6. }
10. a3
{ Before playing Bf4, let us stop Black from playing Nb4-Nd5 and gain a tempo against our bishop. }
10... O-O 11. Bf4
{ Our dark-squared bishop development changes, depending on where Black places his queen.   Against Qd8, we go Bg5 as there is no need to protect d4 @@StartBracket@@no Rd8@@EndBracket@@.   For Qd6, we put our bishop on e3 to protect the pawn on d4 and make the queen on d6 look useless, as its only idea is to play Rd8 and put pressure on d4.   Finally, for Qa5, we don't want the bishop on g5 as the queen keeps an eye on that square from a5. We don't need it on e3, as, unlike Qd6, there is no pressure on d4. Hence we put it on f4, the best available diagonal for the bishop.   In this position, the bishop on f4 is ideal, but we would like to point out that in a different move order @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pq4/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nf6  5.Nf3  Nc6  we play  6.Be3  which is examinedhere in the ...Bg4 setup chapter.@@EndBracket@@, Black could force us to get the same position with a bishop on e3 which also gives White an advantage.   In other words, if you want to be lazy, you can also play  11.Be3  , which will transpose to Nf6-Nc6 systems covered in a different chapter. }
11... Nd5
{ Trying to trade pieces is a common idea for Black in such setups.   11...Rd8  is a blunder, and Black loses after  12.b4  Qh5  13.b5  when taking on d4 is not an option due to Bxh7 tricks, and Na5 is not an option due to Bc7 winning material.  Black will have to go back to b8, and White goes Re1 with ideas like Re5 when engines give +3, and that is not surprising when we look at Black's development and piece coordination. }
12. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ After  12...exd5  we get a unique position when Black's both bishops are bad while White's both bishops are good 😊.  White can further increase his advantage with  13.b4  Qb6  14.b5  removing the knight from the center and getting a dominating position. }
13. Re1 Rd8 14. Be4
{ It is hard to imagine how Black will finish his development on the queenside. The activity of White's pieces speaks for itself. }
