[White "15) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...e6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nc6 5.Nf3 cxd4 6.cxd4 e6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  or  5...Nc6  doesn't have any independent value, and it will soon transpose to either 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3 cxd4 6. cxd4 e6 7. Nc3
{ Whether Black plays Nf6 or Nc6 or both, it doesn't change the nature of the position. White gets a quick lead in the development. }
7... Qd6
{ Black keeps the queen in a more active square and hopes to put pressure on the d4-pawn faster with a future Rd8. In return, he also blocks the f8-bishop, and the queen on d6 is prone to attack. }
8. Bd3 { As always, we put the bishop on d3 to its best diagonal. } 8... Nf6 9.
O-O Be7
{ We have seen similar setups in multiple move orders. Both sides try to finish castling quickly. }
10. a3 { Getting away from any Nb4 ideas. } 10... O-O 11. Be3
{ With the queen on d6, our dark square bishop is ideally placed on e3.   True, it is merely protecting the pawn on d4 and not doing much otherwise, but it kills the sole purpose of Black's idea behind keeping the queen on d6 @@StartBracket@@to put pressure with Rd8@@EndBracket@@.   Now the queen is useless on d6, and we will exploit that. }
11... b6
{ Black can also start with Rd8, but it doesn't bother us as the d4-pawn is well-protected. Sooner or later, Black will have to play b6, and we will transpose into the 11... b6 line one way or the other. }
12. Qe2 { We keep focusing on development. } 12... Bb7 13. Rad1
{ Black knight on c6 doesn't have easy access to the d5-square. White wants to play Rfe1 next and wait for Black's plan.   Engines already prefer White, but for our general understanding and chess improvement, let us go further to grasp the position.   Black will keep one rook on d8 to put pressure on the d4-pawn. He can choose d8-c8 or d8-e8 for his rooks. }
13... Rad8 14. Rfe1
{ White finished his development. Black needs his c6 knight on d5, but that is not going to happen. }
14... Rfe8
{ Black needs to consolidate his position to exploit the strategic advantage of playing against the IQP, but his pieces are not ideally placed for it @@StartBracket@@Qd6/Nc6@@EndBracket@@. }
15. Bb1 { Exploiting the odd placement of the queen on d6. } 15... Qb8 16. Qd3
{ Black cannot exploit our queen placement on d3 as  16...e5  is met by  17.d5  . Meanwhile, White targets h7. }
16... g6
{ Taking care of the h7 target, Black is one move away from getting an excellent position by playing Bf8. }
17. Ba2
{ A super important move/plan in such setups. We stop the Bf8-Bg7 idea tactically... }
17... Bf8
{ We will gladly give our e3 bishop after  17...Ng4  18.h3  Nxe3  19.Qxe3  when black will have to deal with Ne4-Qh6 ideas and also constantly watch out for d5-breaks. }
18. Bg5 Bg7 19. d5
{ Look at White's active pieces and appreciate it 😊.  The pin on the f6 knight becomes deadly. Engines are screaming with a winning advantage after  19...exd5  20.Nxd5 }
