1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  or  5...Nc6  doesn't have any independent value, and it will soon transpose to either 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Be3 cxd4 7. cxd4 e6
{ This is undoubtedly the best way to opt for the cxd4-e6 setup when White is committed to Be3. }
8. Nc3 { Our standard way of playing once Black takes cxd4. } 8... Bb4
{ This is a natural move to avoid any loss of tempo. } 9. Bd3
{ White intends to unpin the knight by castling next. } 9... e5
{ This is a direct way to solve problems. Black tries to liquidate the center. }
10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5
{ Now Black must give of bishop pair since  11...Qxe5  loses to  12.Qa4  and the bishop on b4 falls. }
11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qxe5 13. Qa4+
{ It was also possible to play  13.O-O  , which gives a pleasant position, but we like this direction which poses maximum practical problems for Black. }
