[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nc6
{ 4...cxd4  5.cxd4  Nf6  or  5...Nc6  doesn't have any independent value, and it will soon transpose to either 4...Nc6 or 4...Nf6 lines. }
5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Be3 cxd4 7. cxd4 e6
{ This is undoubtedly the best way to opt for the cxd4-e6 setup when White is committed to Be3. }
8. Nc3 { Our standard way of playing once Black takes cxd4. } 8... Qd8
{ Black keeps the queen in a place where it cannot be attacked, but it also admits to wasting two tempos by playing Qd5-Qd8.  The main move here is  8...Qd6  , which soon transposes after  9.a3  Be7  10.Bd3  O-O  11.O-O  which we've examined here. }
9. Bb5
{ As Black chose to make us play Be3 before going for the cxd4-e6 setup, we take advantage of the same. The c1-square is available for the rook, so we build pressure against the c6-knight. This idea is unheard of and has never been played by any 2400+ players yet.   Apart from being strong, it should also have a great surprise and practical value.  9.Bd3  gets us to the line where we wanted to have our bishop on g5, not e3.  Although it is slightly better according to the engines, even with the bishop on e3, we felt this rare  9.Bb5  is precise and poses more practical problems to Black. }
9... Bd7
{ One of the most logical moves. Black is reluctant to break his queenside pawn structure. }
10. O-O
{ Our argument is that the bishop on d7 is misplaced. Black needs b6-Bb7 setups to activate the bishop, which we managed to prevent. }
10... Be7
{ Chasing our bishop by playing a6 makes no sense, as we want to remove the bishop from b5 ourselves😊. The job is done.   Bb5 was played to lure Black into playing Bd7 where it will be misplaced, and soon we will bring our bishop to its ideal place on d3. }
11. a3
{ Nice prophylaxis before bringing the bishop back to d3.  Engines also give a slight edge after getting rid of the IQP by playing  11.d5  when White's pieces remain more active, but we prefer this more. }
11... O-O 12. Bd3
{ Black bishop is on the wrong diagonal. It should be ideally placed on b7, but it is not easy to get it there. He doesn't have that much time to go Bc8-b6-Bb7, as White will be much faster to create an attack in the center.  Getting the bishop on c6 could be an option, but there are no good squares for the knight, thanks to our little a3 move😊. }
12... Rc8
{ Black admits his bishop will be stuck for a while and continues to finish his development. }
13. Re1
{ We also calmly finish our development and ask Black to show his plans for his light-squared bishop. }
13... Qc7 14. Rc1 Rfd8 15. Bb1
{ Although Black finished his development, it is far from ideal.   White will soon play Qd3 targetting the kingside when playing g6 weakens the dark squares, and playing h6 doesn't solve the problem of the h7-square. The knight on c6 still struggles to find a good square.   Engines evaluation also confirms that White is much better here, and it is not easy to play as Black. }
