1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 g6
{ The ...g6-setup can come from various move orders, and we will cover all of them in this chapter. Anish suggested this direction in his Dragon course for Chessable.   It is interesting to observe that in his Dragon course, Anish suggests opting for 2... d5 and ...g6 systems against the Alapin, but for his Najdorf course, he suggests 2...Nf6 against the Alapin 😊. Probably he wanted to keep similar setups for the Dragon players; bishop on g7.   In the mainline, we will see how we shall play against Anish's system and why it is not fun for Black to play in that direction. }
5. Nf3 cxd4
{ Black wants to give an IQP to White, but this comes with a price. White will now get Nc3 with a tempo. }
6. cxd4
{ Next, we just go for Nc3/Bb5 and play against Black's lack of development. }
6... Bg7
{ 6...Nc6  allows  7.Nc3  and d5.   Black can also start with  6...Nf6  , but it has no independent value since both Nf6 and Bg7 moves are necessary for Black to castle, and sooner or later, we will come to the same position. }
7. Nc3 Qa5
{ The queen is better placed on a5 than d8, but it is not close to Black's king, where White is launching his attack. }
8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+
{ We don't mind trading this piece since it is more important to stop Black from castling quickly. }
9... Nxd7 10. O-O { Black is still two moves away from castling. } 10... Ngf6
11. Re1
{ Right on time, White stops Black from castling.   11...e6  12.d5  would be a total disaster when the center opens up, and Black will likely lose the e6-pawn.   After  11...Qd8  Black plans to castle next, but that will be far away once White goes  12.Qb3  attacking b7 and planning to play Qb4/Qa3 next to keep Black's king in the center. }
