{ This move is rare and only works against @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  but not against @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  .  With the bishop on g7, Black could exchange the queen and take twice on d4, giving us a bad pawn structure without queens, and White will not be fast enough to fight for the initiative.  With the knight on f6, Black cannot do the same, as we will always have Nxd4 ideas.   By playing  6.Qb3  we pose a threat of Bc4. This is the reason why Anish chose @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  instead of  5...Nf6  , as mentioned in our notes earlier. }
6... Qxb3
{ It could be tempting to trade queens and hope for equality, but that is far from reality. }
7. axb3
{ Opens up the a-file for the rook and White now threatens to take on c5. }
7... cxd4
{ 7...Nbd7  8.dxc5  Nxc5  9.Be3  is an excellent move to attack the knight with tempo and set a cute trap of  9...Nxb3  10.Ra3  when the knight is lost.  Black stays behind in development after  9.Be3  and White gets a dominating position. }
8. Nxd4
{ Here is the difference between the 5...Nf6 and the 5...Bg7 variation. Black does not have any ...Bxd4 ideas, and he has to deal with Nb5 threats now. }
8... Bd7
{ Playing a6 does not stop Nb5 due to the pin. Black now wants to give the pair of bishops after Nb5 and try to save the loss of material. }
9. Na3
{ There was nothing wrong with  9.Nb5  taking the pair of bishops and enjoying a better position.  The text move  9.Na3  is even stronger when Black cannot stop Nb5 ideas anymore and will be forced to play Kd8 soon to stop Nc7 ideas. }
