{ The ...g6-setup can come from various move orders, and we will cover all of them in this chapter. Anish suggested this direction in his Dragon course for Chessable.   It is interesting to observe that in his Dragon course, Anish suggests opting for 2... d5 and ...g6 systems against the Alapin, but for his Najdorf course, he suggests 2...Nf6 against the Alapin 😊. Probably he wanted to keep similar setups for the Dragon players; bishop on g7.   In the mainline, we will see how we shall play against Anish's system and why it is not fun for Black to play in that direction. }
5. Nf3 Nf6
{ Black focuses on the kingside like  5...Bg7  . Here we have two pleasant choices. }
6. Qb3
{ This move is rare and only works against @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  but not against @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  .  With the bishop on g7, Black could exchange the queen and take twice on d4, giving us a bad pawn structure without queens, and White will not be fast enough to fight for the initiative.  With the knight on f6, Black cannot do the same, as we will always have Nxd4 ideas.   By playing  6.Qb3  we pose a threat of Bc4. This is the reason why Anish chose @@StartFEN@@rnb1kbnr/pp2pp1p/6p1/2pq4/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Bg7  instead of  5...Nf6  , as mentioned in our notes earlier. }
6... cxd4
{ Black wants to clarify the center before trading queens.  6...e6  blocks the bishop on c8 and allows  7.Bc4   6...Be6  allows White to play  7.c4  Qe4  8.Be3  with the idea of Nbd2 attacking the queen on e4. }
7. Bc4
{ White is ahead in development so it is time to say no to queen trades😊. }
7... Qe4+ 8. Kf1
{ White king has no trouble staying on f1, as Black doesn't have enough pieces to create any attack. The queen from e4 will soon be chased out. }
8... e6
{ Blocks the bishop on c8, but there was no better choice.   8...Be6  9.Ng5  Bxc4  10.Qxc4  loses on the spot as Black cannot control Qc8/Qxf7/Nxe4 threats together. }
9. cxd4
{ White's knight is heading for b5 via c3, gaining a tempo by attacking the queen on e4. }
9... a6
{ Both  9...Nc6  and  9...Bg7  runs into  10.Nc3  Qf5  11.Nb5  and Black cannot avoid material loss due to Nd6/Nc7 threats. }
10. Bg5 { White keeps developing with tempo. } 10... Bg7 11. Nc3 Qf5 12. Re1
{ Black was one move away from castling, but that mission ends since he needs to stop the threat of Re5, which would lead to queen trap. }
12... Nbd7 { 12...Nc6  allows  13.d5 } 13. Nd5
{ 13.d5  was also possible, getting a winning advantage. Our move wins the queen. }
13... Nxd5 14. Bd3
{ Surprise! Now the queen gets trapped after  14...Qg4  15.h3  Qh5  16.g4  and the smart looking @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/1p1n1pbp/p3p1p1/3n1qB1/3P4/1Q1B1N2/PP3PPP/4RK1R b kq - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Ne3+  loses to  15.Rxe3  Qa5  16.Rxe6  when it is a matter of time before Black gets mated. }
