6. Nbd2
{ Almost 3000 games have been played, and only about 80 games this rare move was tried.   With our signature attempt, we deviate from the most popular path and take the game to lesser-explored areas. White plans to play Bc4 next. }
6... cxd4
{ The main move. This has to be the logical reaction against Nbd2 to disturb White's main idea of Bc4. }
7. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate developing move before dealing with the pawn on d4. }
7... Qh5
{ Black ensures the knight on f3 is restricted since White would not like to trade queens with the Black king in the center. }
8. O-O
{ Development is the primary thing in this position. White threatens Qb3 next. }
8... dxc3
{ This move pushes the limit, but one cannot be intimidated by  8...Nf6  9.Qb3  O-O  10.Nxd4  when Black will find it annoying to finish development and find good diagonals for his bishops. }
9. Ne4
{ We are giving another pawn and allowing a fork. Ruthlessly target the king on e8 now. }
9... cxb2 10. Bxf7+ { Now it is time to sacrifice and go all out for mate😊. }
10... Kxf7
{ 10...Kf8  11.Qd8  followed by Ng5, would expedite the mating process. } 11.
Qb3+ e6
{ 11...Kf8  12.Neg5  Nh6  13.Bxb2  would soon lead to resignation due to the mating attack and the engine evaluation of +8 seals it.   The same is applicable for  11...Ke8  12.Bxb2  when the h8 rook comes into danger. }
12. Nfg5+ Kf8 13. Bxb2
{ There is no one to save the king on f8, and it is time to resign. } *

