{ Almost 3000 games have been played, and only about 80 games this rare move was tried.   With our signature attempt, we deviate from the most popular path and take the game to lesser-explored areas. White plans to play Bc4 next. }
6... cxd4
{ The main move. This has to be the logical reaction against Nbd2 to disturb White's main idea of Bc4. }
7. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate developing move before dealing with the pawn on d4. }
7... Qd8
{ The most played move and gives White a great position. There has to be some obvious reason why Anish tried to make the rare  7...Qc5  move work. }
8. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Becoming greedy and senseless with  8...Bxd4  9.cxd4  Qxd4  10.O-O  Nf6  loses to  11.Qa4  Nc6  12.Nf3  , when White attacks the queen on d4 and intends to play Bh6 next.  The Black king will no longer castle in this game. }
9. O-O O-O 10. N2f3 { Aiming for Ne5 next. } 10... Qc7
{ Playing for a6-b5 ideas don't solve Black's problems of developing queenside.  10...a6  11.Re1  b5  12.Bb3  Bb7  13.Ne5  and the knights dominate the center, while Black is miles away from getting any hint of a comfortable position. }
11. Qe2 { Supporting the bishop and continuing to develop. } 11... a6
{ 11...Bg4  12.h3  forces Black to give up pair of bishops.   11...Nc6  12.Nxc6  gives Black a tough choice of either breaking his pawn structure or allowing a future Ne5 tempo by taking with the queen.  In either case, White enjoys a better position strategically as Black bishops are not getting any good diagonals. }
