[White "16) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 g6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 g6 5.Nf3 Bg7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 g6
{ The ...g6-setup can come from various move orders, and we will cover all of them in this chapter. Anish suggested this direction in his Dragon course for Chessable.   It is interesting to observe that in his Dragon course, Anish suggests opting for 2... d5 and ...g6 systems against the Alapin, but for his Najdorf course, he suggests 2...Nf6 against the Alapin 😊. Probably he wanted to keep similar setups for the Dragon players; bishop on g7.   In the mainline, we will see how we shall play against Anish's system and why it is not fun for Black to play in that direction. }
5. Nf3 Bg7
{ There are different move orders here, but Black needs to develop his pieces one way or the other.   5...Bg7  is the most natural follow-up after playing g6. Mixing up two ideas by playing g6 first and then going for  5...Bg4  makes no sense, and White can continue with  6.Be2  and followed by h3, which will immediately make the life of the g4 bishop complicated.  According to Anish, this is the best move order for Black. This is what he says in his Dragon course 'the best move order, keeping the flexibility.   If Black plays  5...Nf6  the problem is  6.Qb3!   5...cxd4  deserves attention and avoids  6.Nbd2  , but allows the extra option of  6.cxd4  followed by Nc3. }
6. Nbd2
{ Almost 3000 games have been played, and only about 80 games this rare move was tried.   With our signature attempt, we deviate from the most popular path and take the game to lesser-explored areas. White plans to play Bc4 next. }
6... cxd4
{ The main move. This has to be the logical reaction against Nbd2 to disturb White's main idea of Bc4. }
7. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate developing move before dealing with the pawn on d4. }
7... Qc5
{ Anish suggests this very rare move in his Lifetime Repertoire about the Dragon, so we can expect this to happen frequently in tournament games, which is why this is our mainline.  The queen on c5 stops the d2 knight from moving, which would have been the case for  7...Qd6  8.Ne4 }
8. Qb3
{ Now we force Black to make some unwanted moves. We attack f7 and also prepare Ne4 next. }
8... Nh6 { Given a choice who wants to put the knight on h6! } 9. Ne4 Qb6
{ Only move to stop Bxh6-Bxf7 ideas. Now Black wants to have the intermediate Qxb3 if White takes on h6. }
10. Nxd4
{ Look at White's pieces in the center! There is no way we are going to accept this will be equal for Black😊. Let us see how the game can unfold. }
10... O-O
{ Anish rightly decides not to suggest Qxb3, which only helps White to activate his a1 rook with axb3. }
11. O-O
{ We don't take on b6 either and welcome Black to take on b3 anytime that will help our rook get the half-open file. }
11... Nf5
{ The most logical move. Black solves the problem of the h6 knight and trades it with White's lovely knight on d4. }
12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. Ng3
{ Our knights moved from the center, but Black must now lose a tempo to remove the bishop from f5. }
13... Bd7 14. Re1
{ Let us quote Anish here from his Dragon course.  'Here we have three fine options,  14...Qxb3  15.axb3  b5  16.Bf1  b4!  Leads to mass simplifications,  14...Nc6  15.Qxb6  axb6  16.Be3  Na5  17.Bf1  b5!  Intending Nc4 next also should be fine, but if you feel ambitious and want to keep the tension, the simple  14...e6  is very playable as well.'  Now let us refute all of them one by one😊. }
14... Qxb3 { The other suggestion goes in this direction of trading queens. }
15. axb3 b5 16. Bf1 b4
{ And according to Anish, this will lead to mass simplifications. We failed to find any such mass simplifications in this direction. }
17. cxb4
{ We have two extra pawns, and the pawn on e7 is hanging. White also gives a positional threat of b5, which will kill the knight on b8. }
17... Nc6
{ Any other move would be losing according engines and hard to argue with. }
18. b5 Nd4 19. Rxe7 { Now we have two extra pawns. } 19... Bxb5 20. Rexa7
{ Black is far from proving equality here - 2 pawns down and no clear solution. Let us dig a bit deeper. }
20... Rxa7
{ 20...Rae8  21.Bf4  doesn't give Black material equality with no obvious liquidation in the site. }
21. Rxa7 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 { We will lose one pawn, but not both. } 22... Nxb3 23.
Be3 { Black cannot take on b2 due to Rb7, which will win a piece. } 23... Rb8
24. Ra2
{ It is okay to make such a backward passive move for such a healthy pawn in the endgame 😊. }
24... Nd4 25. Bf4
{ Forcing Black to leave the b-file as Black must keep Ra8 ideas in control. }
25... Rd8 26. Ne4
{ A pawn is a pawn.   26....Ne6  27.Be3  Rb8  28.Nc3  and still a pawn is a pawn. Black will suffer a long time with no immediate draw in sight.  We are more than happy to get such a position out of the opening 😊. }
