{ Look at White's pieces in the center! There is no way we are going to accept this will be equal for Black😊. Let us see how the game can unfold. }
10... O-O
{ Anish rightly decides not to suggest Qxb3, which only helps White to activate his a1 rook with axb3. }
11. O-O
{ We don't take on b6 either and welcome Black to take on b3 anytime that will help our rook get the half-open file. }
11... Nf5
{ The most logical move. Black solves the problem of the h6 knight and trades it with White's lovely knight on d4. }
12. Nxf5 Bxf5 13. Ng3
{ Our knights moved from the center, but Black must now lose a tempo to remove the bishop from f5. }
13... Bd7 14. Re1
{ Let us quote Anish here from his Dragon course.  'Here we have three fine options,  14...Qxb3  15.axb3  b5  16.Bf1  b4!  leads to mass simplifications,  14...Nc6  15.Qxb6  axb6  16.Be3  Na5  17.Bf1  b5!  intending  Nc4  next also should be fine, but if you feel ambitious and want to keep the tension, the simple  14...e6  is very playable as well.'  Now let us refute all of them one by one😊. }
14... Nc6
{ This is another suggestion by Anish where we have two pleasant choices. } 15.
Bf4
{ Going for the positional advantage. White develops and keeps a threat of Qxb6-axb6-Bc7. }
15... Na5 { Forcing White to take on b6. } 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. Bf1
{ With the bishop on f4, Black now gets an additional task to protect the pawn on e7.   Besides taking on e7, White also has positional threats like Bc7 attacking b6 and Rad1 taking control over the d-file. White's advantage here is indisputable. }
