[White "17) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 cxd4 - ...a6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 a6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 a6
{ This is another way Black can play the a6 setup.   In general, these are just wasting tempo without developing, and by normal moves, White gets a good position. }
6. Be3 { Giving a threat of taking on c5. } 6... Nd7
{ The only independent move.   6...cxd4  7.cxd4  Nf6  would be the normal reply and will be examinedhere after the 4...Nf6 move order.   6...Nf6  loses a pawn after  7.dxc5  and having wasted a crucial tempo with a6 ensures Black doesn't have any compensation. }
7. c4
{ We are attacking the queen and creating a lovely square for our knight on b1.   The engine suggests playing Be2-O-O first, which is also strong, but this move felt more natural and human. }
7... Qd6 8. Nc3 Ngf6 9. Be2
{ The logical way to castle and ask Black what did they get by giving us control over the center and better development. White enjoys a great and easy-to-play position. }
