[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is a pretty extensive line, and very easy to get lost in the oceans of transpositions.   However, for us, this is not an issue since our chapters are based on exact move orders but based on setups. All Bg4 setups in one chapter, all g6 setups in one chapter, and so on.   This particular chapter will not have great significance and will be shorter as, one way or the other, it will divert into some other setups, and it has very few independent systems. }
6. dxc5
{ Johan-Sebastian Christiansen recommends this move in his Alapin course for Chessable. We want to point out why we aren't following his suggestion. }
6... Qxd1+
{ This is the best way for Black to play against this line.  6...Qxc5  7.Na3  gives White a lovely position, as shown by Sebastian in his course. }
7. Kxd1 Bf5
{ This was the only area where we could not prove any advantage, and the worst part is there are almost 100 games in this direction. }
8. Be3
{ In this position, Sebastian analyzed the naive looking  8...e6  and gave an advantage for White which is incredibly surprising as the two most played moves here are  8...O-O-O  and  8...Nd5  and after both moves, Black gets a fine position. Let's take one of them, for example... }
8... Nd5
{ Black keeps the option of playing e6/e5 open and targets the e3 bishop first. }
9. Bb5
{ With the inclusion of @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pp2pppp/2n2n2/2P2b2/8/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/RN1K1B1R b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...e6  9.Nbd2  Sebastian analyzed  9...Nd5  and suggested  10.Bb5  . Let's see what the difference is here. }
9... e5
{ A fantastic sacrificing move that solves all the problems.   Once again, we could argue that it is not super obvious and can be considered a practical try. Sure, but not when three games have already been played, and it is well-known 😊 }
10. Bxc6+
{ Taking on e5 directly would be a blunder.  10.Nxe5  Nxe3  11.fxe3  O-O-O+  and Black wins the knight on e5. }
10... bxc6 11. Nxe5 Nxe3+ 12. fxe3 O-O-O+
{ We dug further, but you get the point. It is too dangerous and not even new!   This position was reached in a game between two GMs back in 2013. There is no point in going to a tournament game without bringing anything new to the table and when an existing game refutes the line.   Hence we don't want the 6.dxc5 direction. }
