[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Nf6/Nc6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6.Be3 Ng4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is a pretty extensive line, and very easy to get lost in the oceans of transpositions.   However, for us, this is not an issue since our chapters are based on exact move orders but based on setups. All Bg4 setups in one chapter, all g6 setups in one chapter, and so on.   This particular chapter will not have great significance and will be shorter as, one way or the other, it will divert into some other setups, and it has very few independent systems. }
6. Be3 { Giving a threat of dxc5 next. } 6... Ng4
{ The only sensible independent move/ direction that needs to be covered in this chapter.   6...Bf5  is examinedhere,   6...e5  is coveredhere,  and  6...e6  7.Na3  is the mainline, which is coveredhere.   Black can include  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  but depending on his next move, it will be covered in that respective setup. By playing Ng4, Black gives the threat to take on e3. As we will see, this is an empty threat. }
7. Nbd2
{ Nxe3-fxe3 favors us greatly as our center gets stabilized, we get rid of the bishop that wasn't doing much currently, the f-file gets opened up, and with the help of Bc4-O-O, the pawn on f7 will be in danger.  Black's main idea of playing Ng4 turns out to be utterly useless. }
7... cxd4
{ 7...Nxe3  was played a few times, but White gets an overwhelming position after  8.fxe3  with Bc4-O-O coming, and Black stays behind the development.  After including Nxe3-fxe3 each time Black takes on d4, we will take with the e-pawn and get two half-open files to put pressure on.  Engines are already claiming winning advantage, but let us be content with a human evaluation of clearly better😊. }
8. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate move before taking on d4, gaining tempo by attacking the queen. }
8... Qd8
{ It is hard to find a better square for the queen where it will be safe.   8...Nxe3  9.fxe3  helps White as he will then take on d4 with the e-pawn and have a great center with two half-open files to attack.  Black could keep the queen on d6, but it will invite a future Ne4, and Black would have to waste another tempo on it. }
9. Nxd4 { We are happy to take fxe3 and open up the f-file for our rook. } 9...
Nxe3 { Black would have to make this move to validate his Ng4 move. } 10. fxe3
Bd7
{ Making sure to keep the queenside structure intact.   10...e6  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Qg4  , with the idea of O-O-O, keeps Black completely restricted when all his pieces are on their initial squares. }
11. Rf1 { We are keeping the provision of castling long. } 11... e6 12. Nxc6
Bxc6 13. Qh5
{ White will castle long and finishes his development.  13...Qe7  14.Bb5  leaves Black in a highly unpleasant situation when his king remains stuck in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 - ...Nf6/Nc6 Setups"]
[Black "4.d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6.Be3 Ng4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is a pretty extensive line, and very easy to get lost in the oceans of transpositions.   However, for us, this is not an issue since our chapters are based on exact move orders but based on setups. All Bg4 setups in one chapter, all g6 setups in one chapter, and so on.   This particular chapter will not have great significance and will be shorter as, one way or the other, it will divert into some other setups, and it has very few independent systems. }
6. Be3 { Giving a threat of dxc5 next. } 6... Ng4
{ The only sensible independent move/ direction that needs to be covered in this chapter.   6...Bf5  is examinedhere,   6...e5  is coveredhere,  and  6...e6  7.Na3  is the mainline, which is coveredhere.   Black can include  6...cxd4  7.cxd4  but depending on his next move, it will be covered in that respective setup. By playing Ng4, Black gives the threat to take on e3. As we will see, this is an empty threat. }
7. Nbd2
{ Nxe3-fxe3 favors us greatly as our center gets stabilized, we get rid of the bishop that wasn't doing much currently, the f-file gets opened up, and with the help of Bc4-O-O, the pawn on f7 will be in danger.  Black's main idea of playing Ng4 turns out to be utterly useless. }
7... cxd4
{ 7...Nxe3  was played a few times, but White gets an overwhelming position after  8.fxe3  with Bc4-O-O coming, and Black stays behind the development.  After including Nxe3-fxe3 each time Black takes on d4, we will take with the e-pawn and get two half-open files to put pressure on.  Engines are already claiming winning advantage, but let us be content with a human evaluation of clearly better😊. }
8. Bc4
{ An excellent intermediate move before taking on d4, gaining tempo by attacking the queen. }
8... Qf5 { Keeping an eye on f2 to create some attack. } 9. Nxd4
{ White wants to trade on d4 and put his bishop there. } 9... Nxd4
{ 9...Nxe3  10.fxe3  weakens the f7-pawn drastically, with Rf1 coming next, and Black gets a terrible position. }
10. Bxd4 e5
{ This is the main idea that Black was counting on. How will White keep f2 protected while saving the bishop on d4? }
11. h3
{ Counter attack is the best defense. White removes the knight from g4. } 11...
exd4 12. hxg4 Qxg4
{ After  12...Qe5  13.Kf1  it is a matter of time before the White rook comes to e1 once White moves the queen to b3/a4. Black is losing almost instantly there. }
13. Qb3
{ We will castle one way or another and get the rooks to the e-file. The black king is not going to castle in this game, and his position is busted. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Na3 a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Na3
{ Our move remains the same irrespective of Black playing Nc6 or Nf6. We want to give threats of Nb5/Bc4, and Black will have to deal with that. }
6... a6
{ After this natural move played by many GMs, Black is already significantly worse. Black prevents Nb5 ideas but creates another weakness on b6. }
7. Nc4 { Instantly exploiting the weakness on b6 by threatening Nb6. } 7... Qd8
{ Stopping Nb6 and planning b5, but Black is behind development now. } 8. Be3
{ We are not giving time to finish Black his kingside development by constantly posing threats on the queenside.   Look at our last three moves Na3-Nc4-Be3 all giving threats on the other side of the board that stopped Black from making a single move on the kingside. This time we threaten dxc5. }
8... b5
{ 8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  would further weakens the b6-square, and Black will eventually be unable to stop the deadly Nb6. }
9. Nce5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5
{ Once again, giving Qf3 threat that must be addressed before Black addresses his kingside development. }
10... Bb7 11. a4 { Once again, striking on the queenside by attacking b5. }
11... c4
{ 11...b4  12.a5  allows White to play Qa4 next when the Black king gets stuck in the center. }
12. b3
{ White blows up the queenside.   Black cannot keep it closed, and soon a check will come from the a4-e8 diagonal before Black can run with O-O. Otherwise, he will have to give up a pawn; in either case, White is better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Na3 cxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Na3
{ Our move remains the same irrespective of Black playing Nc6 or Nf6. We want to give threats of Nb5/Bc4, and Black will have to deal with that. }
6... cxd4
{ Another logical move to target the knight on a3, and a mistake. White takes over now with inspiring play. }
7. Nb5 { A nice intermediate move threatening Nc7. } 7... Bd6
{ The only sensible way to stop Bd6 that does not to lose instantly.   7...Qd8  occurred more than 70 times and after  8.Bf4  Black cannot stop Nc7 ideas, and engines give +5 for White already. }
8. Bc4 { A cute move. Black cannot take on c4 due to the Nxd6 fork. } 8... Qe4+
9. Be3
{ A great move! Using the vulnerability of the d6 bishop, White develops his bishop and blocks the check. Black cannot take this bishop either due to the Nxd6 fork. }
9... Bb8 { Only way to keep control of the c7/d6-square. } 10. Bd3
{ There is no rush to take on d4. Let us get as many tempos as possible. The bishop gets to a better diagonal now. }
10... Qd5 11. Nbxd4
{ Black remains underdeveloped, and his pieces are passively placed, which promises White a great position. }
