[White "19) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Na3 Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Na3
{ Our move remains the same irrespective of Black playing Nc6 or Nf6. We want to give threats of Nb5/Bc4, and Black will have to deal with that. }
6... Bd7 { With the idea to play Rc8 after Nb5. } 7. Nb5 Rc8
{ 7...O-O-O  8.Be2  would be suicidal as Black's queenside would open up much faster than White's kingside.  Engines give a massive advantage to White already. }
8. c4
{ We go for the queen, and once again, don't give Black time to develop his kingside. }
8... Qe4+ 9. Be2 Nxd4
{ Black had to take on d4.  9...Nf6  does not stop d5 due to  10.Ng5  Qg6  and now White crushes in the center with  11.d5 }
10. Nfxd4 cxd4 11. O-O
{ Development is the priority, as usual. Black is not close to matching it with his entire kingside army sleeping. }
11... Bxb5 { It gets rid of Nxd4/Nxa7 ideas but gives away pair of bishops. }
12. Bf3 { A nice little intermediate move to gain tempo. } 12... Qe5 13. cxb5
{ White keeps an eye on the b7-pawn. Black is unable to play b6 due to Bc6+.  It is possible to threaten a mate with  13...Bd6  when White will play  14.g3  and apart from Bxb7 moves like Bf4 will also be annoying.  White keeps the pressure, and Black is far away from finishing development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Na3 Qd8 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Na3
{ Our move remains the same irrespective of Black playing Nc6 or Nf6. We want to give threats of Nb5/Bc4, and Black will have to deal with that. }
6... Qd8
{ Prophylaxis against Nb5/Bc4 ideas. It is one of the popular moves and has been played many times.  However, White is now not obliged to play Nb5/Bc4 anymore. We've examined  6...Nf6  here. }
7. Be3
{ About 220 games were played in this position, and this logical move was tried only once in a tournament game by any titled player.   White's strategy is simple; keep giving threats on the queenside to prevent Black from finishing development on the kingside. Currently, we are threatening to take on c5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black had no other choice but to deal with dxc5 plans. Moreover, this was Black's main idea; to trade everything on d4 and damage the pawn structure by taking on a3.   If Black succeeds in doing both, he would be excellent, but in any move order, he cannot achieve that. }
8. Nxd4
{ Now Black gets to choose whether to take on d4 or a3. If he manages both, he would have zero issues in the position. }
8... Nxd4 { Now Black reverses the move order and plans to take on a3 later. }
9. Qxd4
{ We are keeping an eye on the g7-pawn and stopping Black from taking on a3. }
9... Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Bxa3
{ Black would be fine if White takes on a3 now, but obviously, we are not going to do that😊. }
11. Bxg7 { The rook now dies on h8. } 11... Bxb2 12. Rd1
{ The rook is better placed on d1. There is no need to attack the bishop from b1. }
12... f6
{ 12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  f6  does not help Black; after  14.Bb5+  White will get his rook to d8, paralyzing Black's pieces. }
13. Rd3
{ The final touch of precision. We stop Bxc3, and on the next move, we will take on h8.   Black cannot trap our bishop on h8 as he also needs to keep control of Rd7 ideas, so both the King and the c8-bishop cannot move together. White is winning at this point. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6"]
[Black "4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Na3 Qd8 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Na3
{ Our move remains the same irrespective of Black playing Nc6 or Nf6. We want to give threats of Nb5/Bc4, and Black will have to deal with that. }
6... Qd8
{ Prophylaxis against Nb5/Bc4 ideas. It is one of the popular moves and has been played many times. However, White is now not obliged to play Nb5/Bc4 anymore. 6...Nf6 is covered from 5...Nf6 move order in a different chapter. }
7. Be3
{ About 220 games were played in this position, and this logical move was tried only once in a tournament game by any titled player.   White's strategy is simple; keep giving threats on the queenside to prevent Black from finishing development on the kingside. Currently, we are threatening to take on c5. }
7... cxd4
{ Black had no other choice but to deal with dxc5 plans. Moreover, this was Black's main idea; to trade everything on d4 and damage the pawn structure by taking on a3.   If Black succeeds in doing both, he would be excellent, but in any move order, he cannot achieve that. }
8. Nxd4
{ Now Black gets to choose whether to take on d4 or a3. If he manages both, he would have zero issues in the position. }
8... Bxa3 { Black is hoping for bxa3-Nxd4. } 9. Nxc6
{ This move is essential to include. We make sure Black's pawn structure will be broken if he trades queen. }
9... Qc7
{ The only titled-player game that reached this position continued this way. Two of my good friends, GM Deep Sengupta and GM Arjun Erigaisi, had this position in their game from the Abu Dhabi Masters in August 2022.  Arjun realized the position after  9...Qxd1  10.Rxd1  bxc6  11.bxa3  is terrible for Black when White keeps pair of bishops, and Black doesn't have sufficient counterplay against it. White also controls the open files, giving White a durable advantage.  Arjun opted for the more dynamic  9...Qc7  to take on c6 with the queen. In hindsight, we can safely say, choosing the worse endgame would have been a better decision for Black. }
10. Ne5
{ An incredibly strong and counter-intuitive move that was missed in the game. Deep continued with  10.bxa3  , and after  10...Qxc6  Arjun had no problem. White opens up the provision of Qa4+ now. }
10... Bxb2
{ Not the best move, but undoubtedly the most critical one.  The best would be to accept a worse position after  10...Qxe5  11.Qa4+  Bd7  12.Qxa3  when White gets the advantage of the bishop-pair, and Black's king remains in the center.   10...Bxb2  is far worse than that, but it forces White to precision. }
11. Bb5+ Ke7 { With the king on f8, Qxe5 won't be a threat due to mate on d8. }
12. O-O
{ We are looking at the exposed king and do not care about the material at this stage. }
12... Qxe5
{ White is one piece down, and he is about to lose some more material. Despite that, it is winning for White😊. }
13. Qa4
{ A multipurpose move. Supporting the bishop on b5 and threatening Qb4 with a double attack on e7 and b4. White has also threats like Bd4 in the air.   Black's pieces are not only underdeveloped, but the developed pieces also lack harmony. }
13... Bxc3
{ Stopping Qb4 and Bd4 threats.  13...Bxa1  14.Qb4  Kf6  15.Bd4  loses the queen. }
14. Rac1
{ The threats of Qa3 and Rxc3-Bd4 are unstoppable, and Black will lose heavy material with his king being exposed.   The engine's evaluation of +7 is not an exaggeration of the position. }
*

