11. Bb5+ Ke7 { With the king on f8, Qxe5 won't be a threat due to mate on d8. }
12. O-O
{ We are looking at the exposed king and do not care about the material at this stage. }
12... Bxa1 { Being too greedy and materialistic. } 13. Qh5
{ The queen comes from a different side this time, targeting the pawn on f7. }
13... g6
{ 13...Kf8  14.Bc5  leads to mate on the very next move with the unstoppable Qxf7. }
14. Bc5+ { Another fabulous move, offering the bishop for free. } 14... Kf6
{ 14...Qxc5  15.Nxg6  Kd6  16.Rd1  loses the queen. } 15. Nxg6
{ Among various other wins, this one looks the simplest. } 15... Bxc3
{ 15...fxg6  16.Qf3  Kg7  gives White a choice to mate with  17.Bf8  or  Qf8  .   15...hxg6  16.Qxh8  picks up the rook, and soon the Black king will get mated too.   15...e5  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  17.Bd4  wins the queen. }
16. Bf8
{ A fantastic imagination. White takes away the hiding square on g7 for the Black king.   The threat of Qh4-Kxg6-Qg4 and Qg7 is deadly. Black has to give up big material to procrastinate the mate, but he cannot avoid it forever. White is winning outright. }
