[White "20) 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Alternatives"]
[Black " 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... cxd4 { Black is planning to take on a3 next. } 7. Nb5
{ A typical intermediate move to get away from Bxa3 ideas. } 7... Qd8 8. Nbxd4
{ Although the engine's top choice is  8.Qxd4  , we liked this much better from a practical point of view.  After  8.Qxd4  a6  9.Qxd8  Kxd8  the engine's fine point is to play  10.Ne5  axb5  11.Nxf7  Ke8  12.Nxh8  , but it will require extreme precision to ensure the knight on h8 doesn't get trapped or does a good kamikaze job to get many pawns before it dies.  Why bother to go into such complications when more straightforward moves are easy to understand and give an advantage anyways😊. }
8... Be7 9. Bd3
{ Picking the correct diagonal, anticipating a short castle by Black. } 9...
O-O 10. Qe2
{ White keeps both side castling options open. He is better developed, and his pieces are more active. The advantage here is obvious. }
