[White "20) 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Alternatives"]
[Black " 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 cxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... cxd4 { Black is planning to take on a3 next. } 7. Nb5
{ A typical intermediate move to get away from Bxa3 ideas. } 7... Na6
{ Stopping Nc7, but now the knight is misplaced on a6. } 8. Nbxd4
{ Basically, this knight on a6 is awful no matter where it goes. } 8... Be7
{ 8...Nc7  9.Bd3  keeps the knight passive on c7.   8...Nc5  9.Nb5  Qxd1  10.Kxd1  would force Black's knight to return to a6 and stay passive while White's king gets a nice spot on c2. }
9. Be2
{ Our bishop's best place is on d3, but here  9.Bd3  e5  causes some trouble with e4-fork ideas. }
9... O-O
{ Now  9...e5  is met by  10.Nb5  Qxd1  11.Kxd1  e4  12.Ne5  when our king will be safe on c2, Black's knight is misplaced on a6, and White intends to play Be3-Bd4, completely dominating Black. }
10. Bf4 { No more e5 business for Black. } 10... Rd8
{ 10...b6  allows  11.Ne5  when Black cannot take on g2 due to Bf3. } 11. O-O
{ Ready to play Ne5 next. } 11... Nh5
{ 11...Bd6  12.Bg5  gets Black's knight on f6 into an uncomfortable pin. } 12.
Be3
{ Both Black knights are on the edge of the board. White's plan is to play Qc2-Rad1-Rfe1 developing all pieces in a centralized manner.  According to engines, Black's best move would be to return with  12...Nf6  and after  13.Qc2  does not like Black's position at all.   Note that  12...e5  fails due to the simple, but effective,  13.Nxe5 }
