[White "20) 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Alternatives"]
[Black " 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Be7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... Be7 { Black prepares to castle and ignores Nb5. } 7. Nb5
{ If we get to play Nb5 with Nc7 threat, we usually opt for that to gain the tempo. }
7... Na6
{ The knight is usually misplaced on a6, but Black didn't have a good choice at this point.  7...Qd8  8.dxc5  poses issues on the c7-square after the queen trade. }
8. Be2
{ Now we develop most simply and play against the knight on a6.   8.Bd3  cxd4  9.Nbxd4  allows  9...e5  hence we keep the bishop on e2. }
8... O-O
{ We already covered  8...cxd4  9.Nbxd4  in the previous variationhere. } 9.
O-O Qd8
{ This move admits the failure of strategy as Black had to compromise twice  @@StartBracket@@Qd5-Qd8 and Na6@@EndBracket@@ to prevent one idea of Nc7.   Either he could play Na6 and try to justify that without playing Qd8 or play Qd8 and get the knight to c6. Doing both strategically worse Qd8 and Na6 makes no sense.   Nevertheless, this position has been reached several times, even at GM levels. }
10. Bf4 { Meanwhile, White finishes his development naturally. } 10... Nd5 11.
Bg3
{ The bishop is nicely placed on g3, keeping an eye on c7 and restricting the knight on a6. }
11... cxd4
{ The knight on b5 remains solid.  11...Nac7  loses a pawn after  12.Nxc7  Nxc7  13.dxc5  , as the knight on c7, remains hanging after the queen trade.   11...Bd7  12.a4  stabilizes the knight on b5 further. }
12. Nbxd4 Nc5 13. Qc2
{ Black's knights might optically look nice, but they are prone to attack with b4/c4 ideas, while the knight on d4 is much more stable as playing e5 is not easy for Black.   White plans to play Rad1-Rfe1 giving trouble to the queen on d8. Black's bishops remain passive, and the good-looking knights will soon be kicked out. }
