{ Now we develop most simply and play against the knight on a6.   8.Bd3  cxd4  9.Nbxd4  allows  9...e5  hence we keep the bishop on e2. }
8... O-O { 8...cxd4  9.Nbxd4  is coveredhere after the 6...cxd4 move order. }
9. O-O cxd4
{ Black liquidates the center and makes a square on c5 for the knight on a6.  After  9...Rd8  10.Ne5  , the threat of trapping the queen on d5 with Bf3 forces Black to go back to Rf8. }
10. Nfxd4 { Planning to get in Bf3 next to harass the queen. } 10... e5
{ Black is ready to meet Bf3 with e4. } 11. Nf3
{ White goes for the e5-pawn which hangs after the queen exchange. } 11... e4
12. Qxd5
{ The queen trade is fine for us, as Black's knight on d5 won't be stable. }
12... Nxd5 13. Nfd4
{ White plans to play Rd1 and keep threats against the knight on d5, which cannot get enough protection, unlike the knight on d4.   13...Nc5  14.c4  kicks the knight even faster since  14...Nb4  runs into  15.Nc7  Rb8  16.Bf4  when the rook on b8 starts to feel uncomfortable. }
