[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... Qd8 { Black takes measures against Nb5 even before it has been executed. }
7. Nc4
{ We go for Plan B, keep the knight on c4, where it is centralized, and claim that Black has wasted tempi with Qd5-Qd8. }
7... Nc6
{ The knight comes to its ideal square on c6, but Black's bishops will develop miserably while White has a better center and free play.  We will cover  7...a6  here,  and  7...cxd4  would be a mistake, and after  8.Qxd4  Qxd4  9.Nxd4  White's pieces dominate the center, and we can't say the same for Black.  White's bishop would also come into the game faster, and no wonder engines give an excellent advantage for White. }
8. Be3
{ A typical motif against Nc6 setups. White targets the pawn on c5 now. } 8...
Nd5
{ Black aims for the e3 bishop to reduce the pressure on c5.   8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.Bxd4  only helps White to centralize his pieces further. }
9. Bd3 { Completely ignoring Black's threat and developing normally. } 9... Be7
{ 9...Nxe3  10.fxe3  has the following disadvantages: Black changes his most active piece against White's least active minor piece.  Gives White a better center by bringing another pawn towards it. It opens up the f-file, and after White castles short, the pressure on f7 will mount. Thus Black should refrain from taking on e3.  The point of 8... Nd5 was not to take on e3 but to prevent White from taking the pawn with dxc5. }
10. dxc5 { Taking the pawn and practically forcing Black to take on e3. } 10...
Nxe3 { Otherwise, Black remains a pawn down. } 11. fxe3
{ We really want to open up the f-file and get Nd4. Even when we have the option of taking Nxe3, we reject that and take on e3 with the pawn. }
11... Bxc5 12. Nd4
{ To start with, Black cannot castle due to Bxh7-Qh5 ideas picking up the bishop on c5.   Black still remains underdeveloped. White's pieces are more active, and his moves are easy to play. }
