1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... a6 { Black stops Nb5 ideas, but creates a weakness on b6. } 7. Nc4
{ The standard response when the Nb5 idea gets stopped. White threatens Nb6. }
7... Nbd7 { Black develops the knight and prepares b5. } 8. Be2
{ We prepare to castle next and ignore Black's main idea of playing b5. } 8...
cxd4
{ Once again, mixing up the plans.   If Black plays a6-Nbd7, he should follow up only on the queenside. If he wanted to play in the center, then his last two moves made no sense. }
9. Nxd4 e5
{ Black removes the knight from d4.  The danger in Black's position is illustrated nicely after  9...Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.b3  when White supports the c4 knight and prepares Bf3. Black's most active piece is the queen, which will be attacked to no end and Black's minor pieces remain very poorly placed.   Engines already give White a winning advantage. Being greedy with  9...Qxg2  will be playing with fire, and after  10.Bf3  Qg6  11.Qe2  White will develop his c1 bishop and castle long.  Make sure to bring one point home with this fantastic position which will probably also give you a chance to get some brilliancy prizes 😋. }
10. Nf5 Nc5 { Black keeps going for our knights. } 11. Nfe3
{ There was nothing wrong with giving a check on d6 and picking up the bishop on c8, which would give us a double bishop advantage.   The text move is surprisingly stronger and unique, so we didn't want to miss the chance to share it. }
11... Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1
{ The knight came back to d1 from a lovely square f5. By all means, this is not natural and doesn't feel right. However, engines have concrete reasoning for this.   How is Black going to stop Nxe5/Nb6/Be3 ideas? }
12... Nfd7
{ Defends the pawn on e5 but blocks the bishop on c8.  Playing  12...e4  wasn't as an option as it loses a piece after  13.Nb6  Rb8  14.Bf4 }
13. O-O
{ The bishop on c8 is not going to come out soon. Playing ...b5 doesn't help, as White will have Na5 blocking the bishop on c8 once again.   White now plans to play Ne3-d5 and enjoys a clearly better position. }
