1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3
{ A very interesting and standard way of developing the knight in this system.   White threatens to play Nb5 but keeps the Nc4 option open, and we decide where to go depending on Black's response. }
6... a6 { Black stops Nb5 ideas, but creates a weakness on b6. } 7. Nc4
{ The standard response when the Nb5 idea gets stopped. White threatens Nb6. }
7... Nbd7 { Black develops the knight and prepares b5. } 8. Be2
{ We prepare to castle next and ignore Black's main idea of playing b5. } 8...
b5
{ Without a doubt, the most critical continuation. Black gets rid of the strong knight on c4.   In this line, with precise play against engines, it is impossible to prove a clear edge. We have different practical tries where we can test Black, and if he finds all the right moves, we get a position that is practically easier to play from the White side. }
9. Ne3
{ The move Sebastian recommends in his Chessable course. White attacks the queen on d5. }
9... Qc6
{ The queen is better placed on c6 than on d6 as it protects the pawn on b5 when White plays a4. }
10. a4 { Threatening to take on b5 twice as the rook on a8 hangs. } 10... Bb7
{ Thanks to the queen on c6, the pawn on b5 remains protected. } 11. dxc5
{ White clears the d4-square for his knight to attack the queen. } 11... Qxc5
{ Getting away from the Nd4 attack. } 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+
{ White plays against the b5-pawn. } 13... Bxa8 14. Nc2
{ Sebastian stops here, claiming this is an advantage for White and easier to play from the White side. }
14... Be7 { The most logical follow-up for Black. } 15. O-O
{ This position has been reached from a different move order @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/3n1ppp/p1q1pn2/1pp5/3P4/2P1NN2/PP2BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 2 10@@EndFEN@@  10.O-O  Bb7  11.a4  Be7  12.axb5  axb5  13.Rxa8  Bxa8  14.dxc5  Qxc5  15.Nc2  and there are a few games already played here. }
15... O-O 16. Be3
{ Following the plan mentioned by Sebastian, to attack the b5-pawn by going for the queen.  We tried  16.Nfd4  , but Black is fine after  16...Rb8  17.Re1  Nf8  with the idea of Ng6. The bishop on a8 remains active to compensate for the weakness on b5. }
16... Qc7
{ We would happily recommend this line despite engines claiming equality since we did give Black some practical tests to pass, and the position is not dead, and it is not trivial to sacrifice a pawn.   However, we are not keeping this as our first option because two GM-level games and one correspondence game reached this position and showed the right way for Black.   Suggesting some line where existing games are holding seems too naive, where we don't bring anything new to the table and hope our opponent would not know a particular game. }
17. Bxb5
{ This would be the first new move, technically.  17.Nfd4  was played in all the games and reached this position, and Black is fine after  17...Qb7  18.Bf3  Nd5  as shown in Kulkarni - Swiercz, 2018 and Mammadov - Abasov, 2015. }
17... Rb8 18. Bxd7 Nxd7 19. Bc1
{ We keep the extra pawn, but Black gets enough compensation due to double bishops, and our pawns are not moving forward immediately.   The game remains complicated with all three results possible. }
