{ Without a doubt, the most critical continuation. Black gets rid of the strong knight on c4.   In this line, with precise play against engines, it is impossible to prove a clear edge. We have different practical tries where we can test Black, and if he finds all the right moves, we get a position that is practically easier to play from the White side. }
9. Nfd2
{ An exceptionally rare move that will surely surprise our opponents. It has never been played at masters level and only two games reached this position in 1994 and 1999.   By threatening Bf3, we give Black a few choices, and only one of them is in the right direction. }
9... Qf5
{ Black gets away from the pin and keeps Ra7/Rb8 ideas flexible for now. This is also very human and already a slight inaccuracy that gives White an excellent position. }
10. Na5 { We stay away from playing Bf3 now 😊. } 10... cxd4 11. cxd4
{ We got an IQP but managed to restrict Black's pieces on the queenside. }
11... Bd6 { 11...Be7  would allow  12.Bf3  followed by Nc6. } 12. g4
{ A surprising assault on the queen. Black cannot play  12...Qd5  due to  13.Bf3  and the rook on a8 will fall. }
12... Qg6 13. h4
{ Making the life of the g6 queen miserable, and h5 is a dangerous threat now. }
13... h6
{ Giving up a pawn with  13...h5  doesn't improve the queen's life and after  14.gxh5  Qf5  15.Rg1  , the queen again gets into threats like Rg5, and the pawn on g7 hangs. }
14. h5
{ Let us not forget apart from the queen, the bishop on c8 also struggles to get into the game. }
14... Qh7 15. Ndb3
{ With Bd3 coming, the queen will reach the place where his king wanted to go 😊.  White's advantage is obvious. }
