{ The standard response when the Nb5 idea gets stopped. White threatens Nb6. }
7... Nbd7 { Black develops the knight and prepares b5. } 8. Be2
{ We prepare to castle next and ignore Black's main idea of playing b5. } 8...
b5
{ Without a doubt, the most critical continuation. Black gets rid of the strong knight on c4.   In this line, with precise play against engines, it is impossible to prove a clear edge. We have different practical tries where we can test Black, and if he finds all the right moves, we get a position that is practically easier to play from the White side. }
9. Nfd2
{ An exceptionally rare move that will surely surprise our opponents. It has never been played at masters level and only two games reached this position in 1994 and 1999.   By threatening Bf3, we give Black a few choices, and only one of them is in the right direction. }
9... Ra7
{ The best square for the rook, and it is not that obvious at first sight. It is a good sign when the best moves are not obvious.   It turns out the Black rook needs to get to the c-file, and there is no hope for the c8 bishop to come out once White opts for Na5. So, Black prepares a different route to get there by Ra7-Rc7. }
10. Bf3 { We go for the queen first. } 10... Qf5 11. Ne3
{ It is better not to go for Na5 once Black plays Ra7. Black will eventually play Rc7 and compared to the 9... Rb8 variation, we won't get any domination on the queenside.   Engines also give very complex lines with  11.g4  but with precise play, Black is fine, and the positions are messy. }
11... Qf4
{ Another test for Black. Playing  11...Qg6  might look natural, and after  12.O-O  the queen is miles away, where the combat will take place once White plays a4. }
12. a4
{ Engines do not understand what an uncomfortable position is, and it is impossible to prove a clear advantage, but from a human point of view, we would be scared as Black here when the queenside is getting opened up, and Black wants to play moves like Qb8. }
12... cxd4 { Black first takes on d4 to avoid Nb3-cxd4-Nxd4 ideas for White. }
13. cxd4 Qb8 14. axb5 { Time to open up the position. } 14... axb5 15. Rxa7
Qxa7 16. Qc2
{ Once again cannot beat engines here who give very few numbers for White.   However, 9.Nfd2 is a fresh idea, and Black had to pass many tests before reaching this position which doesn't look clear at first sight and poses practical problems. }
