[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Nc6"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Nc6 7.Be3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3 Nc6
{ One of the significant alternatives in this position.   Black keeps the queen on d5 unless White forces him to go back with Nb5. He holds the bishop on f8 to avoid a loss of tempo after Nb5-Qd8/Qd7-dxc5. }
7. Be3
{ We stay noncommittal with Nb5/Bc4/Nc4 plans and give the threat to take on c5 instead and force Black to decide on the center. }
7... Ng4
{ A rare move, Vidit tried it in a rapid online event in July 2022. Black plans to eliminate the bishop on e3. }
8. Bc4
{ White develops the last minor piece with tempo and gets ready to follow up with d5. }
8... Qe4
{ Playing with fire. The queen is exposed to all sorts of dangers here. } 9.
Qe2 { Defending e3 is the simplest. } 9... cxd4 { Meets a sudden refutation. }
10. Bd3 { A nice intermediate move, going for the queen. } 10... Qd5 11. Nb5
{ And Black will regret his opening plan. There is no defense against Nc7 at once or prepared by Bf4. }
*

