[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21) 4.d4 e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Nc6"]
[Black "5.Nf3 Nf6 6.Na3 Nc6 7.Be3 cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3 Nc6
{ One of the significant alternatives in this position.   Black keeps the queen on d5 unless White forces him to go back with Nb5. He holds the bishop on f8 to avoid a loss of tempo after Nb5-Qd8/Qd7-dxc5. }
7. Be3
{ We stay noncommittal with Nb5/Bc4/Nc4 plans and give the threat to take on c5 instead and force Black to decide on the center. }
7... cxd4
{ The main idea of Black. He now wants to eliminate the knight on a3. } 8. Nb5
{ The point of White's setup. The knight leaves an exposed position on a3, gaining time in the process. The threat of Nc7 forces Black to move his queen, losing precious time. }
8... Qd7
{ There are two sensible moves at this point. Black can retreat with his queen on d7 or d8.   8...Bd6  loses to a nice trick  9.Bc4  Qxc4  10.Nxd6+  with a fork.   By the number of games,  8...Qd8  is more popular, but  8...Qd7  is more trendy. }
9. Nbxd4
{ Our response remains the same irrespective of Black's queen retreat on d7 or d8.   Although Black now might avoid breaking of pawn structure, his queen is not ideally placed on d7 stalemating the bishop on c8 😊. }
9... a6
{ This move is prevention against any Nb5/Bb5 ideas, but it comes with the cost of wasting tempo and not developing pieces. }
10. Bd3
{ We finish development most harmoniously.  It was also possible to get a slight edge after  10.Nxc6  Qxc6  11.Ne5  Qc7  12.Qa4  when Black would have to go passive with Nd7. }
10... Bd6 11. Qe2
{ There was nothing wrong with  11.O-O  which also gives a slight edge. It is a matter of personal taste which move we choose.  Castling long makes sense as Black's pieces are not actively placed, and in the direct attacking combat, we will be faster. }
