9. Nbxd4
{ Our response remains the same irrespective of Black's queen retreat on d7 or d8.   Although Black now might avoid breaking of pawn structure, his queen is not ideally placed on d7 stalemating the bishop on c8 😊. }
9... Nd5
{ Once again, this is the main move, like in the Qd8 variation here. Black goes for the bishop on e3.  We will examine  9...Qc7  here after the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/1N1q4/3p4/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qd8  9.Nbxd4  Qc7  move order. }
10. Bd2
{ We ask Black to show us how he intends to develop his light-squared bishop. }
10... Nxd4
{ Black hopes to trade the knight and reduce White's development advantage. }
11. Ne5
{ An unexpected intermezzo! We force the queen to leave the a4-e8 diagonal and thus expose Black's king on e8. }
11... Qd8 12. cxd4 a6
{ Black must take care of the threats on the a4-e8 diagonal. } 13. Bc4 Be7 14.
O-O
{ Black manages to solve his issue with the king, but not with the bishop on c8. }
14... O-O 15. Re1
{ The bishop on c8 will be stuck for a long time.  Black cannot play  15...b6  as it loses material after  16.Nc6  followed by Bxd5.   Playing  15...Bd7  does not improve the bishop's future, and White goes  16.Bxd5  exd5  17.Qb3  Bc6  18.Bb4  and Black remain with a bishop on c6 that looks like a pawn 😊. }
