{ The point of White's setup. The knight leaves an exposed position on a3, gaining time in the process. The threat of Nc7 forces Black to move his queen, losing precious time. }
8... Qd7
{ There are two sensible moves at this point. Black can retreat with his queen on d7 or d8.   8...Bd6  loses to a nice trick  9.Bc4  Qxc4  10.Nxd6+  with a fork.   By the number of games,  8...Qd8  is more popular, but  8...Qd7  is more trendy. }
9. Nbxd4
{ Our response remains the same irrespective of Black's queen retreat on d7 or d8.   Although Black now might avoid breaking of pawn structure, his queen is not ideally placed on d7 stalemating the bishop on c8 😊. }
9... Nd5
{ Once again, this is the main move, like in the Qd8 variation here. Black goes for the bishop on e3.  We will examine  9...Qc7  here after the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/1N1q4/3p4/2P1BN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qd8  9.Nbxd4  Qc7  move order. }
10. Bd2
{ We ask Black to show us how he intends to develop his light-squared bishop. }
10... Be7
{ Castling is a bigger priority than deciding on where to develop the c8-bishop. }
11. Nxc6 { The usual trick of not bothering for Qxc6 due to Ne5/Nd4 ideas. }
11... bxc6
{ Undoubtedly the most challenging move.  Sebastian considered  11...Qxc6  in his Chessable course, and rightly concluded White is better after  12.Ne5  Qb6  13.Qa4  Kf8  14.Nd3  when Black lost the ability to castle, and White will soon castle long and enjoy a superior position. }
12. c4 { Removing Black's best piece. } 12... Nb4 13. Bc3
{ The bishop is nicely placed on c3, looking at g7. } 13... Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1
{ The king is needed on the queenside, where we have the majority, so we don't mind moving our king to d1. }
14... Bb7
{ 14...c5  creates a better place for the knight on c6 but after  15.a3  Nc6  16.Bxg7  White remains one pawn up.  Black keeps some compensation but will play for two results. After all, a pawn is a pawn 😊. }
15. a3 { We need the c2-square for our king. } 15... Rd8+
{ After  15...O-O-O  16.Kc1  Black cannot play  16...Nd3  since after the trade  17.Bxd3  Rxd3  , White will have the  18.Ne5  fork attacking d3 and f7.  Hence Black keeps the king on e8. }
16. Nd2 Nd3 17. Bxd3 { Time to eliminate Black's most active piece. } 17...
Rxd3 18. Kc2 Rd7 19. Rhe1
{ Black does have the bishop pair, but his pawn structure remains awful, and whether he keeps the pawn on c6 or c5, one of his bishops will always remain bad.  Our king on c2 is ideally placed where we have a pawn majority, giving White a lovely endgame to look forward to. }
