[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3 Nc6
{ One of the significant alternatives in this position.   Black keeps the queen on d5 unless White forces him to go back with Nb5. He holds the bishop on f8 to avoid a loss of tempo after Nb5-Qd8/Qd7-dxc5. }
7. Be3
{ We stay noncommittal with Nb5/Bc4/Nc4 plans and give the threat to take on c5 instead and force Black to decide on the center. }
7... cxd4
{ The main idea of Black. He now wants to eliminate the knight on a3. } 8. Nb5
{ The point of White's setup. The knight leaves an exposed position on a3, gaining time in the process. The threat of Nc7 forces Black to move his queen, losing precious time. }
8... Qd8 { The more natural retreat for the queen. } 9. Nbxd4
{ The first position to give Black an illusion of choice. There are lots of lines, but some of them are plain bad. White's lead in development forces Black to be very precise.  For instance,  9...Bd7  looks pretty tempting and solid, not damaging our pawn structure, but after  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Qxd8  Black cannot recapture with rook as the pawn on a7 falls, and recapturing with the king exposes the king after White castles long and plays Ne5.   9...Be7  10.Nxc6  breaks Black's pawn structure, and after the queen trade, White puts immediate pressure on the pawn with moves like Ne5 and enjoys a pleasant position. }
9... Nd5 { Going for the e3 bishop is pretty typical in this line. } 10. Nxc6
{ Damaging Black's pawn structure. } 10... bxc6 11. Bd2
{ The simplest way to fight for a durable advantage.  It is also possible to play the very interesting and computerized  11.Qd4  , that as well gives a slight edge.  However,  11.Bd2  is easy to understand and gives a pleasant position. We save our bishop and play against Black's weak pawn structure. }
11... Rb8
{ Black goes for a quick counter to compensate his broken pawn structure. } 12.
c4 { We are aiming for our ideal setup with Qc2-Bc3. } 12... Nf6 13. Qc2
{ White is one move away from getting his ideal setup. } 13... Qb6
{ The queen is nicely placed on b6, aiming at f2 and b2. } 14. O-O-O
{ Sacrificing the pawn on f2.   14.Bc3  Bb4  15.O-O-O  allows  15...Bxc3  16.Qxc3  Ne4  17.Qxg7  Rf8  with massive complications. }
14... Qxf2
{ Black accepts the challenge.   14...Ne4  was safer but after  15.Be3  Bc5  16.Re1  Bxe3  17.Rxe3  White consolidates his position, and Black still got his lousy pawn structure and a bad bishop on c8. }
15. Bd3
{ A very strong idea. White is not in a rush and finishes his development. }
15... Qxg2
{ This is greedy, but already Black was in an extremely difficult position.   15...Be7  16.Rhe1  O-O  17.Ne5  wasn't holding either. }
16. Rhf1
{ Once again not showing any rush and just playing for development and initiative. }
16... Be7 17. Qc3
{ A great move aimed against  17...O-O  when White can play  18.Rg1  and Black cannot take on f3 due to Bxh7 ideas.  Black now comes under massive attack and White's position is fabulous. }
