[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Na3 Nc6
{ One of the significant alternatives in this position.   Black keeps the queen on d5 unless White forces him to go back with Nb5. He holds the bishop on f8 to avoid a loss of tempo after Nb5-Qd8/Qd7-dxc5. }
7. Be3
{ We stay noncommittal with Nb5/Bc4/Nc4 plans and give the threat to take on c5 instead and force Black to decide on the center. }
7... cxd4
{ The main idea of Black. He now wants to eliminate the knight on a3. } 8. Nb5
{ The point of White's setup. The knight leaves an exposed position on a3, gaining time in the process. The threat of Nc7 forces Black to move his queen, losing precious time. }
8... Qd8 { The more natural retreat for the queen. } 9. Nbxd4
{ The first position to give Black an illusion of choice. There are lots of lines, but some of them are plain bad. White's lead in development forces Black to be very precise.  For instance,  9...Bd7  looks pretty tempting and solid, not damaging our pawn structure, but after  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Qxd8  Black cannot recapture with rook as the pawn on a7 falls, and recapturing with the king exposes the king after White castles long and plays Ne5.   9...Be7  10.Nxc6  breaks Black's pawn structure, and after the queen trade, White puts immediate pressure on the pawn with moves like Ne5 and enjoys a pleasant position. }
9... Nd5 { Going for the e3 bishop is pretty typical in this line. } 10. Nxc6
{ Damaging Black's pawn structure. } 10... bxc6 11. Bd2
{ The simplest way to fight for a durable advantage.  It is also possible to play the very interesting and computerized  11.Qd4  , that as well gives a slight edge.  However,  11.Bd2  is easy to understand and gives a pleasant position. We save our bishop and play against Black's weak pawn structure. }
11... Bb7
{ The most challenging move. Black is playing against White's main idea of getting a c4-Qc2-Bc3 setup.  Sebastian covers  11...Be7  in his Chessable course where he rightly points out after  12.c4  Nf6  13.Qc2  White gets the ideal setup, and with O-O-O-Bc3 coming, Black cannot create a counter on time.   The move  11...Be7  is naive and doesn't take measures against White's plan. There are other critical tries that Black can opt for, and we should know how to deal with those. }
12. Qc2
{ It is important to start in this order.  After the careless  12.c4  Nf6  13.Qc2  Black saves on Be7 and goes  13...c5  opens up the bishop on b7, and he is on time to create enough counterplay.  By keeping the f1-bishop open we are ready to meet ...c5 with Bb5. }
12... Qc7
{ If Black plays Nf6, then we don't have to play c4, obviously, and we can continue with castling long. }
13. c4 Nf6 { 13...Nb4  14.Qa4  attacks the knight while preventing c5. } 14. c5
{ This is the fine point. We do not allow Black to free his bishop on b7. }
14... Nd7 { Black goes for the c5-pawn and plans to meet b4 with a5 break. }
15. Bc3
{ A cool sacrifice to gain time.   White gets to his ideal setup, even at the cost of a pawn but makes sure it will take a long time for Black to activate his pieces. }
15... Nxc5 16. Rd1
{ We are avoiding Qf4-Qe4 ideas, which Black would have played against O-O-O. Now we are ready to play Rd4 after Qf4. Black bishops remain passive. We will develop our light-squared bishop and castle short.   Engines are giving a slight advantage to White, though, with very precise play, Black might hold the position, but this is not our concern. The position is easier from the White side, and practically it is difficult for Black to coordinate his pieces. }
