{ White is not worried about giving up the c3-pawn, but it is essential to play Bd2 after Black takes the pawn on c3. Hence we cannot put our bishop on d3, and thus we put it on b5.   It is also interesting to note that both Anish and Jorden opted for this rare move. Jorden playing this in April 2022 also underlines that this is what they felt is the way to go and not opting for 7.Bd2. }
9... Bb7
{ In both games mentioned above, Black did not dare to take on c3.   9...Qxc3  10.Bd2  Qb2  11.a4  or @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/p2p1ppp/1p2p3/1B2P3/3P4/2q2N2/P2B1PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 1 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Qc7  11.Rc1  Bb7  12.O-O  does look very scary when we compare the development. Looking at the engine evaluation would make Black's life even more miserable 😊.   9...a6  10.Ba4  b5  11.Bc2  gets us to the diagonal where we want to reach, but this time, we can play Bd2 once Black takes on c3. }
10. O-O Be7 11. Bg5
{ This will be the new move.  Anish tried  11.Qd3  and Jorden played  11.Bf4  both gives White a pleasant position, but the text move is stronger.  Once the dark squared-bishop is gone, the king on g8 would have no help. All Black's pieces are crowded on the queenside, and it takes one move for White to get the bishop on d3. }
