[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) 2...Nf6 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nf3 e6"]
[Black "5.d4 cxd4 6.cxd4 b6 7.Bd2 alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... e6
{ Black stabilizes the knight on d5 and keeps Nc6/d6/b6 ideas in hand. } 5. d4
{ Grabbing the center and threatening c4-d5. } 5... cxd4
{ Any other move allows White to play c4 when engines give an understandable winning advantage, as Black has no argument against White's fantastic center. }
6. cxd4 b6
{ An entirely different approach by Black. He solves one of the major issues of developing the light-squared bishop. }
7. Bd2
{ White plans to play Nc3 and intends to recapture with the bishop if Black takes on c3. A relatively rare move that has been played at the GM level twice so far by Pragg and Harika.   Sebastian also suggested it in his Chessable course. We liked his direction and, in this particular case, have no objection to following the same. We can keep this as our second alternative. }
7... Bb7
{ Undoubtedly the main move. After  7...Ba6  Sebastian gives the strong  8.h4  Bxf1  9.Kxf1  , and we suggest stopping the analyses there.  We have more space. Our king is much safer than Black's, which will come under attack after we go Rh3-h5-Nc3-Ne4 etc. Our center is strong, and the Black pieces are underdeveloped. As an assurance, engines also give +0.75 😊. }
8. Nc3 Nxc3
{ Black would eventually have to castle, and to allow Bd3-Ne4 would take away any peace from the king on g8. }
9. Bxc3
{ The point of Bd2. Is our bishop bad on c3? At first glance, yes.   Once we go deeper, we realize Black's only way to counter White is to break the center with d6. We want to counter that plan by preparing d5. For this, we need enough protection for the e5-pawn. The bishop on c3 is just doing its role 😊. }
9... Be7
{ Black can get his other knight to d5 with  9...Na6  10.a3  @@StartBracket@@stopping Nb4@@EndBracket@@  10...Nc7  11.Bd3  Nd5  but after  12.Bd2  both bishops are looking at the kingside, and our dark-squared bishop nicely tames the black knight on d5, and the b7 bishop remains blocked. Soon we will play h4, and Black's king on g8 will start to feel uncomfortable.   After the immediate  9...d6  10.Bc4!  there is no way to stop White from playing d5 which takes more space and breaks the center. Black himself would hate to play d5 and block his bishop. }
10. Bd3
{ We are getting ready to attack with h4-Bxg7-Ng5 plan once Black castles. }
10... d6
{ The king is currently safe on e8, and it would be naive to castle and run into h4-Bxh7 threats. }
11. Qe2 { For now, we keep both side castling options open. } 11... Nd7
{ Black keeps delaying castling to avoid h4-Bxh7 ideas. } 12. h4
{ We are showing our intentions clearly. } 12... Qc7 13. Rd1
{ Still waiting for Black to show his hand. } 13... Rd8
{ Black keeps waiting too. } 14. O-O dxe5 15. dxe5 O-O
{ Finally Black managed to castle without getting his by Bxh7 ideas. } 16. Nd4
{ This move is tactically justified.  16...Qxe5  17.Nc6  , @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/pbqnbppp/1p2p3/4P3/3N3P/2BB4/PP2QPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Nxe5  17.Nxe6  and @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/pbqnbppp/1p2p3/4P3/3N3P/2BB4/PP2QPP1/3R1RK1 b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Bxh4  17.Qh5  all of them favor us and give White a pleasant position. }
