[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) 2...Nf6 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nf3 e6"]
[Black "5.d4 cxd4 6.cxd4 d6 7.Bc4 Nb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... e6
{ Black stabilizes the knight on d5 and keeps Nc6/d6/b6 ideas in hand. } 5. d4
{ Grabbing the center and threatening c4-d5. } 5... cxd4
{ Any other move allows White to play c4 when engines give an understandable winning advantage, as Black has no argument against White's fantastic center. }
6. cxd4 d6
{ 6...Nc6  or  6...Be7  does not have any independent value. We can be lazy and play  7.Bc4  and transpose into 6... d6 lines as and when Black plays d6.  We can also try to exploit the move order inaccuracies and opt for a direct  7.Nc3  and get our bishop to d3 later in one tempo.   6...Bb4  allows White to play for initiative with  7.Nbd2  , we will kick the bishop out with a3 and get our knight to e4, or play strategically by trading Black's good bishop with  7.Bd2   In either case, White's advantage is obvious. }
7. Bc4
{ We are now playing for rapid development while having a great center. } 7...
Nb6
{ This is a very concrete way to solve the problem for Black. Usually, such a move makes no sense after taking cxd4.   Black's logic is based on a definite sequence of moves which we will now see. }
8. Bd3
{ What did Black achieve by forcing the White bishop into an excellent diagonal and putting his own knight away from the center? }
8... Nc6
{ The argument is Black is quick enough to create threats on the center with dxe5 and Nb4 to go for the excellent bishop on d3. }
9. O-O dxe5 { This encourages a queen trade that we don't mind. } 10. dxe5 Nb4
11. Be4
{ Look at the difference between the light-squared bishops of White and Black. }
11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bd7
{ A radical way to solve the problem of the light-squared bishop.  The slow approach of  12...N4d5  does not give Black an acceptable position after  13.a4  a5  14.Nc3  , when developing the bishop c8, remains an issue. }
13. Bxb7 Nc2
{ The point of Black's previous move.  13...Rb8  14.Be4  rules out this option, and Black remains one pawn down. }
14. Bxa8 Nxa8 15. Ne1
{ Forces Black to take on a1 and controls the c2-square to ensure the knight is trapped on a1. }
15... Nxa1 16. Be3
{ Now we go for the a1-knight, but it is essential to start with Be3 and not to play Nc3. }
16... Nb6 17. Nd2
{ The point of delaying Nc3 is revealed. White takes care of any Nc4 ideas, and Black lacks any counter.   The a1-knight will be lost, and Black will remain one pawn down. }
