1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... e6
{ Black stabilizes the knight on d5 and keeps Nc6/d6/b6 ideas in hand. } 5. d4
{ Grabbing the center and threatening c4-d5. } 5... cxd4
{ Any other move allows White to play c4 when engines give an understandable winning advantage, as Black has no argument against White's fantastic center. }
6. cxd4 d6
{ 6...Nc6  or  6...Be7  does not have any independent value. We can be lazy and play  7.Bc4  and transpose into 6... d6 lines as and when Black plays d6.  We can also try to exploit the move order inaccuracies and opt for a direct  7.Nc3  and get our bishop to d3 later in one tempo.   6...Bb4  allows White to play for initiative with  7.Nbd2  , we will kick the bishop out with a3 and get our knight to e4, or play strategically by trading Black's good bishop with  7.Bd2   In either case, White's advantage is obvious. }
7. Bc4
{ We are now playing for rapid development while having a great center. } 7...
Nb6
{ This is a very concrete way to solve the problem for Black. Usually, such a move makes no sense after taking cxd4.   Black's logic is based on a definite sequence of moves which we will now see. }
8. Bd3
{ What did Black achieve by forcing the White bishop into an excellent diagonal and putting his own knight away from the center? }
8... Nc6
{ The argument is Black is quick enough to create threats on the center with dxe5 and Nb4 to go for the excellent bishop on d3. }
9. O-O Nb4 { Black continues to chase the light-squared bishop. } 10. Be4
{ An extremely rare move.  The most popular move is to retain the bishop with  10.Be2  and after  10...dxe5  11.Nxe5  White keeps a small edge we can keep as our second alternative.  The text move will have more surprise value, and also objectively and practically not easy to handle over the board for our opponents. }
10... d5
{ Otherwise, Black's play makes no sense. He must eliminate this bishop. } 11.
Bd3
{ We give up our pride on d3. As the saying goes... It is not important what pieces are getting exchanged but what pieces are left on the board 😊. }
11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3
{ Not just the bishop on c8, but the knight on b6 is also misplaced.   Black got into a French where he has also taken cxd4, and there is no way to put pressure on White's central pawns. }
12... Be7 13. Nc3
{ Black's other big problem is his king.   It is interesting to see engines hate to castle here anticipating the reroute of White's c3-knight to h5 via e2-g3/f4-h5. }
13... Bd7
{ Not touching the kingside and keeping the rook on h8 to meet Ne2-g3 ideas with ...h5 if needed. }
14. b3
{ We are not in a rush. How long can Black stay in the center after all 😊 }
14... Rc8 15. Bd2 { Again showing total coolness. } 15... O-O
{ Black cannot wait in the center forever.   White has space on every side of the board, and he would start progressing anyways. }
16. Ne2
{ We could stop much earlier, but we would like to show one interesting plan for increasing general understanding. }
16... Na8
{ The knight on b6 had no future, so Black tries to get it to a better square. This plan is seen in some French lines, so it is not uncommon. }
17. h4
{ We wanted to highlight this strong attacking theme.   White gives direct threats like Ng5 and builds up a slow attack with g3-Kg2-Rh1-h5 etc. If Black takes on h4, he will soon get mated once White gets his rook to h1. }
