10. Nc3
{ In the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/3pp3/3nP3/2BP4/5N2/PP2QPPP/RNB2RK1 b - - 5 9@@EndFEN@@  9...b6  line, we refrain from playing  10.Nc3  as after the exchange on c3 the bishop gets a nice diagonal on b7.  Why that is not the case here? We shall see it soon 😊. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bc6
{ So, our argument is the bishop is good on b7 but misplaced on c6! } 12. exd6
Bxd6 13. Ne5
{ With one move, White made both bishops look miserable. This is the reason the bishop on c6 is misplaced.   We don't even want to take the bishop immediately. We will keep our knight on e5, which in a way, prevents Nd7 ideas as then we take on c6. }
13... Bxe5
{ Makes sense. Otherwise, White would stabilize the knight with f4. } 14. Qxe5
{ Now, we have the advantage of having a pair of bishops. } 14... Nd7 15. Qg3
Nf6 { Black stops Bg5 ideas with the tactical shot of Ne4. } 16. Bh6
{ In Tari-Shankland, Chessable Masters rapid 2022, White opted for  16.Re1  and kept a microscopic edge due to the double bishop. The text move is more direct. }
16... Nh5 17. Qg4 Qf6
{ These moves were forced. Now White has two pleasant options. } 18. Be3
{ This move keeps the double bishop advantage.  It was also possible to transform our advantage to an endgame with better structure by playing  18.Qxh5  Qxh6  19.Qxh6  gxh6  20.Be2  and get a comfortable edge. }
18... Qg6 19. Qxg6 hxg6 20. a4
{ White retains his double bishop advantage with a play on both wings. He also enjoys more space which gives him a great endgame to look forward to. }
