4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... e6
{ Black stabilizes the knight on d5 and keeps Nc6/d6/b6 ideas in hand. } 5. d4
{ Grabbing the center and threatening c4-d5. } 5... cxd4
{ Any other move allows White to play c4 when engines give an understandable winning advantage, as Black has no argument against White's fantastic center. }
6. cxd4 d6
{ 6...Nc6  or  6...Be7  does not have any independent value. We can be lazy and play  7.Bc4  and transpose into 6... d6 lines as and when Black plays d6.  We can also try to exploit the move order inaccuracies and opt for a direct  7.Nc3  and get our bishop to d3 later in one tempo.   6...Bb4  allows White to play for initiative with  7.Nbd2  , we will kick the bishop out with a3 and get our knight to e4, or play strategically by trading Black's good bishop with  7.Bd2   In either case, White's advantage is obvious. }
7. Bc4
{ We are now playing for rapid development while having a great center. } 7...
Be7
{ Black first takes care of his kingside, and keeps his queenside development plans flexible and noncommittal. }
8. O-O O-O { Black can include dxe5-dxe5 anytime he wants. } 9. Qe2
{ We also keep our decision flexible on the queenside.   First, we wait for Black to show his intentions on the queenside. }
9... b6
{ Black skips Nc6 and plans to solve his issue with the c8 bishop first.   9...Nc6  transposes to the line we will examinehere after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp3ppp/3pp3/3nP3/2BP4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6 }
10. Rd1
{ We still delay the development of our queenside pieces. There is a hidden intention behind this which will be revealed in our next move. }
10... Bb7
{ The logical follow-up. The Black knight is stabilized on d5, he solved the problem of his passive bishop, and everything looks under control. }
11. Bxd5
{ Surprise! White gives up his bishop and reveals the point of 10. Rd1. If Black recaptures with the bishop, we get a quick Nc3-d5 @@StartBracket@@thanks to Rd1@@EndBracket@@.   If Black recaptures with the pawn, then the issue of a bad light-squared bishop continues to haunt him. }
11... Bxd5
{ The bishop might look good on d5, but it is soon going to be chased out by our knight. }
12. Nc3 { We want to take on d5 and play e6 next. } 12... Qd7
{ Black prevents White's idea of Nxd5-e6 } 13. Ng5
{ A fantastic move that renews our idea of playing e6 after taking on d5. }
13... Qb7 { Black tries his best to keep preventing White's plan. } 14. Nge4
{ Change of target! Now we go for the d6-pawn. } 14... dxe5 15. dxe5 Bxe4
{ 15...Bc6  16.Bg5  would create a massive attack on the kingside by trading the dark-squared bishop.  Black will not be in time to reach to help his king as the queenside pieces have not woken up yet. }
16. Nxe4 Nd7 17. Bf4
{ We have a strong center, better development, more space, and good attacking chances, so our advantage is indisputable here. }
