14. Qg4
{ With the threat of Bh6, the c1-bishop looks like a monster, while its counterpart doesn't have a good place to go. }
14... f5
{ In a blitz game, Gukesh opted for  14...Re8  , which loses either to  15.Bh6  Bf8  16.Nb5  with an unstoppable Nd6, or @@StartFEN@@rn1qr1k1/p3bppp/1p2p3/3pP3/3P2Q1/2N5/PP3PPP/R1BR2K1 w - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Rd3  with a rook swing to the kingside with an unstoppable attack on the kingside. }
15. Qg3
{ In every game that reached this position, White took  15.exf6  , and after  15...Rxf6  16.Ne2  had a stable edge due to the clear weakness on e6.  However, the text move is even stronger and poses more practical problems for Black. }
15... Nc6 16. Ne2
{ Black lacks space and concrete plans to create a counter. White aims to improve his position slowly. }
16... Rc8 17. Bd2
{ Black has zero targets to play for.   His bishop on e7 is worse practically than his counterpart. Black will be happy to trade the bishop because the White bishop has more space and free squares available.   White has various slow plans, while Black must wait and watch. The weakness on e6 is permanent. White will put his queen on d3, and Black must constantly watch for ideas like Qa6/Nb5/doubling on the c-file.   On the kingside, White will slowly expand with g3-Kg2-h4-h5, gaining more space. Black struggles due to a lack of targets and plans. }
