{ Our advantage is dynamic and based on development and extra space. It is not surprising that we don't want to change pieces now.   More than 1000 games reached this position and the debate is, can Black finish his development smoothly and claim that White will have issues due to his weak pawns in the queenside? }
12... b6
{ Addressing the Elephant in the room. It is the biggest issue for Black to develop the bishop and the rook on the queenside. }
13. Bd3
{ We shift our attention to the kingside while Black is busy finishing development on the queenside. }
13... Bb7
{ Natural, but not the best.  13...Qc7  will transpose to the line which we will examinehere. }
14. Qe4 g6 15. Bh6
{ This is the reason why moves like 12... Qc7 or 12... Qa5 are more popular. Black needs to get his rook on the open d-file when White opts for the Qe4-Bh6 plan. }
15... Na5
{ A smart intermediate move to ensure White queen does not get its ideal square f4 as the bishop on d3 hangs. }
16. Qe3
{ It keeps the protection of the d3-bishop, and the attack on the f8-rook continues. }
16... Re8 17. Bb5
{ A simple but strong way to either block the b7-bishop or trade it. } 17...
Bc6 18. Bxc6 Nxc6 19. h4
{ White's attack on the kingside is coming slowly but surely, while Black has absolutely no counterplay or a proper way to defend it.   We will go h5-Qf4-Rfe1-Nh2-Ng4, and it is a matter of time before Black's defense collapses completely. }
