[Black "5.d4 cxd4 6.cxd4 d6 7.Bc4 Nc6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 { We don't miss the chance of getting a nice tempo. }
3... Nd5
{ 3...Ne4  traps the knight after  4.d3  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp1ppppp/5n2/2p1P3/8/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Ng8  4.d4  we refuse to analyze 😊. }
4. Nf3 { We develop our knight and keep Bc4-d4 ideas flexible. } 4... e6
{ Black stabilizes the knight on d5 and keeps Nc6/d6/b6 ideas in hand. } 5. d4
{ Grabbing the center and threatening c4-d5. } 5... cxd4
{ Any other move allows White to play c4 when engines give an understandable winning advantage, as Black has no argument against White's fantastic center. }
6. cxd4 d6
{ 6...Nc6  or  6...Be7  does not have any independent value. We can be lazy and play  7.Bc4  and transpose into 6... d6 lines as and when Black plays d6.  We can also try to exploit the move order inaccuracies and opt for a direct  7.Nc3  and get our bishop to d3 later in one tempo.   6...Bb4  allows White to play for initiative with  7.Nbd2  , we will kick the bishop out with a3 and get our knight to e4, or play strategically by trading Black's good bishop with  7.Bd2   In either case, White's advantage is obvious. }
7. Bc4
{ We are now playing for rapid development while having a great center. } 7...
Nc6
{ This is by far the most popular setup.  Black could also start with Be7-O-O and then play Nc6. There are positions with Nc6 and without Nc6. We will see all positions with Nc6 setups from this move order to avoid any transposition confusion.   9...dxe5  10.dxe5  Be7  is covered from 9...Be7 move order. }
8. O-O { Our standard and easy-to-understand moves that are self explanatory. }
8... Be7 9. Qe2
{ We want to play Nc3 next, so we are getting away from any queen trade that might arise after the trades on c3 and e5. }
9... O-O
{ The most popular move. We can reach this position with different permutations and combination of Nc6/d6/Be7/O-O }
10. Nc3
{ We are going as per plan. Now the queen trade is not possible after the exchanges on c3 and e5, so it is time to remove the knight on d5.  Sebastian, in his course, recommends the interesting and lesser-played  10.Qe4  Bd7  11.Bb3  , but we ran into another lesser-played move by Black after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  10.Qe4  Qb6  stopping White's idea of  11.Bb3  with  11...dxe5  12.dxe5  Qb4  , and we could not find any advantage there.   Instead, the mainline  10.Nc3  felt more logical, which is objectively and practically annoying for Black to handle. }
10... Nxc3
{ This is Black's best bet. He will break White's pawn structure and try to neutralize White's development advantage.   10...Nb6  11.Bd3  helps White to get his bishop where is want to go and puts Black knight in a square which blocks the development of the c8 bishop with b6-Bb7. }
11. bxc3 dxe5
{ Black sticks to his plan of giving White a bad pawn structure.   It is tough to imagine Black playing without including this move one way or the other. He can start with Qa5/Qc7/b6, but eventually, he will have to capture the pawn, and then we will transpose to the mainline with 11...dxe5.   It shows zero understanding to play d5 for Black when White goes Bd3 and gets a strong center, free attack on the kingside, while Black pieces are cramped and underdeveloped. }
12. dxe5
{ Our advantage is dynamic and based on development and extra space. It is not surprising that we don't want to change pieces now.   More than 1000 games reached this position and the debate is, can Black finish his development smoothly and claim that White will have issues due to his weak pawns in the queenside? }
12... Qa5
{ The queen looks nicely placed on a5, attacking both c3 and e5. However, as we will see, the queen is not ideal on a5, and it is far away from Black's king. }
13. Rb1
{ A powerful move. We have no intention of wasting a move by protecting the weak c3-pawn. Instead, we develop our piece and restrict Black from developing his c8-bishop.   Moves like Rb5 in the future are also an idea, but for now, we want to hit on the kingside with Bd3-Qe4. }
13... Qxc3
{ Biting the bullet. Black wants us to show how strong an attack we have. Is it worth a pawn? }
14. Bd2
{ First, we get a tempo by attacking the queen and developing our bishop.  It is also equally strong to go for  14.Rb3  Qa5  15.h4  as we will see in the 13...Rd8 variation. }
14... Qa3 15. Rfc1
{ White is in no rush,and is fully developed now.   The Black queen is in danger, and a surprise attack is waiting for his majesty on g8 😊. }
15... Rd8 { Preparing some piece exchanges with Nd4. } 16. h4
{ While Black struggles to cope with his development issues, we march forward on the kingside to provoke some weakness with h5-h6. }
16... Nd4 17. Nxd4 Rxd4 18. h5
{ Black managed to change the knights, his queenside army is not awake yet and dealing with Rc3-Rg3 and the upcoming assault on the kingside is getting unstoppable.   For machines, these positions are already winning for White. }
