1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 d6
{ Black attacks the e5-pawn at the first chance.   Anish recommends this move in his Najdorf course from the Black side. He also refutes the ideas given in Sebastian's Chessable course from the White side. Our signature strategy is coming into place right now. The current position is super common with many different tries.   A huge surprise is waiting for Black on the next move, which is exceptionally rare. }
5. Bb5+
{ We provoke Bd7 before playing Bc4.  To understand the main reasoning behind it, we need to understand the mainline of  5.Bc4  Nb6  6.Bb3  c4  7.Bc2  . In this position, Black's main move is  7...dxe5  8.Nxe5  Qd5!  attacking d5 and g2.  With the bishop on d7, Black will miss Qd5 move at the end.  More than 1500 games played in this position, and only in two GM level games 5.Bb5 was played. }
5... Nc6
{ 5...Nd7  6.d4  gives White free control over the center and keeps the bishop on c8 blocked. }
6. O-O { We castle quickly and next d4 is coming. } 6... e6 7. c4
{ It was also possible to claim an advantage with  7.d4  , but the text move poses more problems for Black. }
7... Ne7
{ The only move that does not give close to +1 evaluation for White.  Both  7...Nb6  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.d3  and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2npp3/1BpnP3/2P5/5N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc7  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Nc3  gives White a fantastic position when the c8-bishop will be practically dead, and Black ends up with a bad pawn structure when all his minor pieces are restricted in a cramped position. }
8. exd6 { Now Black is forced to take with the queen. } 8... Qxd6 9. Nc3
{ Black's pieces are not ideally placed, and White is better developed.   It is a matter of time before White opens up the center with d4 or goes for the dynamic pawn sacrifice of b4. }
