5... Nc6
{ 5...Nd7  6.d4  gives White free control over the center and keeps the bishop on c8 blocked. }
6. O-O { We castle quickly and next d4 is coming. } 6... Bg4
{ Black gets his bishop out before playing e6. } 7. h3
{ Engines give various ways to fight for advantage, this one is the most direct. }
7... Bh5
{ Black could take on f3, but we don't object to getting double bishop advantage right out of the opening. }
8. d4 { Logical play. We have a secured king, so let us open up the center. }
8... cxd4 9. g4
{ A tricky intermediate move to ensure we can take on d4 with the knight. }
9... Bg6 10. Nxd4 { Giving Nxc6 and e6 threats simultaneously. } 10... Qd7
{ The black queen stops both threats, but staying in such a pin is not a pleasant thing. }
11. exd6 h5
{ An almost impossible move to make without preparation or having external help during a game. Black ignores the center and strikes on the kingside.  The human  11...Qxd6  12.Na3  followed by Nc4 gives White a big advantage due to the lead in development. }
12. Re1 { Our moves are pretty much straightforward. } 12... hxg4 13. Qxg4 Rxh3
{ Black regains the pawn and creates a mess. This move can be made either as a result of a blunder, or pure cheating 😋. }
14. Ne6
{ We refuse to believe any normal human being cooking this soup over the board😊. }
14... Rh8
{ Please, ensure to call the arbiter and demand a thorough search if your opponent gets this far without preparation. }
15. Qg2
{ The good news is, despite all bizarre engine's top choice we are still having a good position 😊. }
15... fxe6 16. Qxg6+
{ We will take Qxe6 next and have a double bishop advantage.   There is no way we are going to beat a machine, but if Black makes it this far, and holds the position easily, certainly he fully deserves half a point 😊. }
