7... c4
{ Now both  7...e6  8.d4  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp1bpppp/1n1p4/2p1P3/8/1BP2N2/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  8.d4  cxd4  9.exd6  e6  transposes to the line which we will examinehere. }
8. Bc2
{ Compared to the usual mainline where Black bishop stays on c8, Black is missing the critical idea of dxe5-Nxe5-Qd5. }
8... Nc6 { Trying to get rid of the e5-pawn. } 9. exd6
{ Now taking on d6 with the pawn will ruin Black's pawn structure. } 9... e5
{ If Black can take Bxd6 with impunity, he will be fine. } 10. d3
{ White indirectly protects the pawn on d6. } 10... cxd3
{ 10...Bxd6  11.dxc4  Nxc4  12.b3  loses a piece. } 11. Qxd3
{ Now the pawn gets its protection. } 11... Be6 12. Ng5
{ An important detail. While Black is busy getting back the pawn, we try to get a double bishop advantage. }
12... Bd5
{ 12...Bc4  13.Qg3  Bxd6  14.Ne4  practically forces Black to go back with Bf8, and White gets a clear advantage. }
13. O-O
{ Engines give different moves to get an advantage, but this is the easiest to understand and most logical. }
13... Bxd6 14. Rd1
