{ Going for the e5-pawn. Both  8...dxe5  9.Nxe5  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2bpp3/2pnP3/2BP4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nxd4  gives the c6 bishop a tough time, who took two moves to get there to get attacked by our knight. }
9. Bb3 { Threatening the devastating c4-d5, opening up the center. } 9... cxd4
{ The most logical move.  9...dxe5  would be playing into White's trap of  10.c4  N5b6  11.d5  exd5  12.cxd5  Bb5  13.Re1  when the initiative in the center costs Black heavily due to his uncastled king. }
10. exd6
{ We want to take on d4 with our knight, so it is essential first to capture the d6-pawn. }
10... d3
{ Black does not accept the sacrifice but restricts b1-knight from coming into the game quickly.   This is a very practical approach that we can expect to happen, especially when your opponent gets hit by this rare Bb5-Bc4 idea. }
11. Qxd3 Nc5
{ Another human and tempting move is likely to happen.  Engines are also OK with  11...Bxd6  12.Nd4  giving up the c6-bishop, but we get the double bishop, and although against machines, everything ends in 0.00, the position remains practically easier to play from the White side.  Black can take Nc5-Nxb3 and get our bishop too, but it helps us to open up the a-file and even engines like White's position with this half-open file and extra space on the queenside with b4. }
12. Qd4
{ We give up our bishop but ensure Black must take on d6 with his queen to keep the g7-pawn protected. }
12... Qxd6
{ Including  12...Nxb3  13.axb3  does not work for Black, as the pawn on a7 hangs. }
13. Bc2
{ Now we save our bishop.   Black will take some time to castle, and the bishop on f8 still does not move. We intend to play Re1/d1, and anytime we can move the black knight from c5 with b4.   White retains some pressure here. }
