[Black "4.Nf3 d6 5.Bb5+ Bd7 6.Bc4 e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 d6
{ Black attacks the e5-pawn at the first chance.   Anish recommends this move in his Najdorf course from the Black side. He also refutes the ideas given in Sebastian's Chessable course from the White side. Our signature strategy is coming into place right now. The current position is super common with many different tries.   A huge surprise is waiting for Black on the next move, which is exceptionally rare. }
5. Bb5+
{ We provoke Bd7 before playing Bc4.  To understand the main reasoning behind it, we need to understand the mainline of  5.Bc4  Nb6  6.Bb3  c4  7.Bc2  . In this position, Black's main move is  7...dxe5  8.Nxe5  Qd5!  attacking d5 and g2.  With the bishop on d7, Black will miss Qd5 move at the end.  More than 1500 games played in this position, and only in two GM level games 5.Bb5 was played. }
5... Bd7 { The most logical move for Black. } 6. Bc4
{ So our claim is compared to the 5.Bc4 line, the bishop on d7 is misplaced. It can be seen in the  6...Nb6  line.  There are only six games that have reached this position so far. Once our course is out, the numbers will increase rapidly😊. }
6... e6
{ You are most likely to face this move more often than  6...Nb6  . Black would like to take advantage of this extra Bd7 move and get Bc6 faster. }
7. d4
{ This is the first position where we give Black various choices that look similar, with or without computers. Funnily enough with the bishop on c8, also we get a position that is part of our repertoire.   Irrespective of the placement of the bishop @@StartBracket@@c8/d7@@EndBracket@@, we are happy with our position😊. }
7... Bc6 { A very logical move to prove the usefulness of the extra Bd7 move. }
8. O-O { Our natural follow-up, playing for faster development. } 8... Nd7
{ Going for the e5-pawn. Both  8...dxe5  9.Nxe5  and @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2bpp3/2pnP3/2BP4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...cxd4  9.exd6  Bxd6  10.Nxd4  gives the c6 bishop a tough time, who took two moves to get there to get attacked by our knight. }
9. Bb3 { Threatening the devastating c4-d5, opening up the center. } 9... cxd4
{ The most logical move.  9...dxe5  would be playing into White's trap of  10.c4  N5b6  11.d5  exd5  12.cxd5  Bb5  13.Re1  when the initiative in the center costs Black heavily due to his uncastled king. }
10. exd6
{ We want to take on d4 with our knight, so it is essential first to capture the d6-pawn. }
10... dxc3
{ This move accepts the challenge of sacrifice. Since the position is very fresh, it is hard to predict what moves we might encounter more.  There is this move challenging the sacrifice or the safer approach of playing  10...d3  that stops White from developing faster.   10...Bxd6  is an acceptance of giving up the pair of bishops after  11.Nxd4  and a possible continuation could be  11...Qc7  12.g3  O-O  13.Nd2  when White eventually takes the c6-bishop at his convenient time and enjoys double bishop advantage. }
11. Bxd5
{ A surprise! White gives up the bishop to ensure rapid development. Now, Nxc3 will come with a tempo. }
11... c2
{ Not a trivial move to make, but not too difficult to understand the logic behind it. Black forces White's queen to c2 to pin the knight on c3 with Rc8. }
12. Qxc2 Bxd5 13. Nc3
{ The only difference with the 11... Bxd5 line is our queen is on c2 instead of d1. }
13... Rc8
{ Nothing else justifies provoking Qc2.  The only other move that explains this idea is to take  13...Bxf3  , but it loses on the spot due to the excellent intermediate  14.Nb5  with an unstoppable Nc7 while keeping the gxf3 ideas in hand. }
14. Bg5
{ We focus on fast development, again giving Black different options and provoking to go wrong. }
14... f6
{ This move is a bit computerized unless it is based on a blunder of not seeing  15.Rfe1  fxg5  16.Qf5  that wins on the spot. }
15. Rfe1 Bxd6 { After  15...fxg5  16.Qf5  the Black king dies in the center. }
16. Qd1 O-O { The only move to stay alive. } 17. Nxd5 fxg5
{ Once again obligatory.  After  17...exd5  18.Qxd5  White will take on d6, and the threats of Re7/Rad1 will put huge pressure on the d7-knight. }
18. Rxe6
{ Seeing this far while playing f6 and still going for it is a bit inhuman as the position looks very scary from the Black side. Computers can get away by giving a microscopic edge to White.   Still, it is not an enjoyable position to aim for practically when one must walk on a thin rope to get a position like this without any upside. }
