{ This move accepts the challenge of sacrifice. Since the position is very fresh, it is hard to predict what moves we might encounter more.  There is this move challenging the sacrifice or the safer approach of playing  10...d3  that stops White from developing faster.   10...Bxd6  is an acceptance of giving up the pair of bishops after  11.Nxd4  and a possible continuation could be  11...Qc7  12.g3  O-O  13.Nd2  when White eventually takes the c6-bishop at his convenient time and enjoys double bishop advantage. }
11. Bxd5
{ A surprise! White gives up the bishop to ensure rapid development. Now, Nxc3 will come with a tempo. }
11... Bxd5 { An automatic recapture that seems the most human respond. } 12.
Nxc3 { We attack the bishop immediately. } 12... Nb6
{ 12...Nf6  13.Bg5  puts Black in an uncomfortable pin. } 13. a4
{ Going for the d5 bishop again by planning to chase away its defender on b6. }
13... Bxd6
{ After  13...a5  , White can play the move that would not work without a4-a5 inclusion.  14.Bg5  Bxf3  15.Bxd8  Bxd1  16.Bxb6  and we see the advantage of including a4-a5. }
14. a5 Nc8
{ Only retreat that does not lose. Black needs to keep his minor pieces protected so he can prioritize castling. }
15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Ng5
{ Engines also suggest  16.a6  ,  16.Bg5  etc with a complex game, but the text move poses a maximum practical challenge for Black. }
16... h6 { This move allows a pretty combination after } 17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18.
Qxd5+ Kg6 19. Qd3+ Kf7 20. Qb3+ Kg6 21. a6
{ And White will win as Black cannot touch the b7-pawn since the rook on a8 falls with a check. }
