cxd4 6. Bc4 { White prioritizes quick development and active play. } 6... Bb7
7. O-O { Look at the difference between both kings! } 7... e6
{ Black is counting on the good-looking knight on d5 and finally focuses on castling. }
8. cxd4 { We are coming with Nc3 to dislodge Black's pride on d5. } 8... d6
{ Many strong GMs have played this move, and it is already a losing mistake! }
9. Bxd5
{ A typical motif in this line. We give up the bishop to get a quick Nc3-d5 break. }
9... Bxd5 10. Nc3
{ We threaten to take on d5, and if Black moves the bishop, we go d5 when the Black king can settle in the center for the rest of the game or give up the material.   In either case, White wins. }
10... Bxf3
{ Black hopes to close the center with d5 and ensure safety for his king. } 11.
Qxf3 d5 12. Bd2
{ A calm move to highlight Black's inability to develop his kingside pieces.   Be7 will always run into Qg3 when there is no way to castle peacefully due to Bh6 ideas. }
12... Nc6 13. Ne2
{ It will be challenging for Black to complete the development in the kingside.   White enjoys more space, and engines are screaming +1.5, confirming White's tremendous activity and Black's lack of counterplay. }
