{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ It is the most-played move in this position. Black develops his knight and, depending on White's move, decides what pawn to move. }
5. Bc4
{ Attacking the knight on d5 and developing the bishop.  We will see all sidelines here except  5...Nb6  6.Bb3  d6  and  6...d5  , which we will examine in the mainlines. }
5... Nc7
{ This move has never occurred in a GM-level game, and the reasoning is obvious.   The knight is poorly placed on c7 and gives White another tempo. Why would anyone play Nf6-d5-c7 within the first five moves of the game?   Honestly speaking, we never had any analyzes here😊, and it is not needed either. One can go and play such positions with zero homework.   Nevertheless, for the sake of completion, let us see a few logical follow-ups. }
6. d4 { We take complete control over the center. } 6... cxd4
{ After  6...d5  7.exd6  Qxd6  8.Ng5  the double threat of taking on f7 and playing Ne4 gives White an overwhelming advantage. }
7. O-O
{ Black will not survive the middlegame with such a difference in development. }
7... d5
{ Trying to catch up with the development.   7...dxc3  8.Nxc3  makes it too late to finish the development, and after  8...g6  9.Ng5  Nxe5  10.Qd4  it is time for Black to resign despite being too many pawns up. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. cxd4
{ White will soon play Nc3-e4, taking another tempo away from Black, who remains underdeveloped with a centralized king. }
