[White "25) 2...Nf6 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nf3 Nc6 Sidelines"]
[Black "4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bc4 Nb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ It is the most-played move in this position. Black develops his knight and, depending on White's move, decides what pawn to move. }
5. Bc4
{ Attacking the knight on d5 and developing the bishop.  We will see all sidelines here except  5...Nb6  6.Bb3  d6  and  6...d5  , which we will examine in the mainlines. }
5... Nb6
{ The most popular move by a large margin. Black attacks the bishop on c4.   5...Nf4  attacking the pawn on g2 backfires when White ignores it with  6.d4  and Black cannot take  6...Nxg2  as the knight gets trapped after  7.Kf1 }
6. Bb3
{ It is Black who must justify his unnatural moves like Nf6-d5-b6.   Unless he does something concrete, such as waste of tempos to the knight to b6 will not suffice to get an acceptable position. }
6... g6
{ This move does not justify Black's maneuver of Nf6-d5-b6. Now we will get a solid center with a few extra tempos.   Astonishingly, many strong GMs have opted for this while modern machines are giving +1 already for White! }
7. d4 { Given a chance, we will play d5 as well 😊. } 7... cxd4 8. Ng5
{ There are many ways to get a better position, this being the most direct.   We play this intermediate move to attack f7 first. }
8... d5
{ The best bet for Black.  After  8...Nxe5  both  9.Qxd4  or  9.Bf4  wins the game due to the attack on e5 and a potential mate threat on f7.   After the direct  8...e6  9.Ne4  the weakness of the dark squares speaks for themselves.  The greedy  9...Nxe5  fails to  10.Bg5  Be7  11.Nd6  ruining Black's castle, and after the trade on e7, White takes on d4 with the queen, and Black's position is close to being stalemated😊. }
9. exd6 e6 10. Qf3 { We attack the f7-pawn again. } 10... Ne5
{ Playing f6 would give up the pawn on e6, so Black instead finds this move which protects the f7-pawn and attacks the queen simultaneously. }
11. Qg3 { We go for the knight now. } 11... Bxd6
{ Black is two pawns up and just one move away from consolidating his position... }
12. Ne4 { We now go for the d6 bishop. } 12... O-O
{ 12...Nec4  13.Qd3  forces  13...Ne5  and White can take  14.Qxd4  with a tremendous attacking position. }
13. Nxd6
{ Taking the dark-squared bishop to get complete domination over the dark squares. }
13... Qxd6 14. Bh6 { Attacking the rook on f8. } 14... Re8 15. cxd4 Qxd4 16.
O-O
{ Black's pieces in the center are unstable and prone to attack with Nc3-Rad1-Rfe1 coming.   The weakness on the dark squares will constantly worry Black from getting mated. White is clearly better, although engines disagree with us and say White is winning😊. }
