{ 9...Qc7  10.Nxc4  Nxc4  11.Qxc4  forces Black to take on e5 with the bishop as the knight is pinned.  We can take the bishop and play with a double bishop advantage or just go O-O-d4 and play for development advantage. }
10. O-O
{ Our pawn will be nicely protected with Re1, but the same cannot be said for the c4-pawn. }
10... Na5
{ Black keeps his pawn alive at the cost of keeping both knights away from the center. }
11. d4 { Thus, it is time to play at the center😊. } 11... cxd3 12. Qxd3
{ A miserable position when Black cannot be proud of any one factor in his position. All his pieces are passively and poorly placed.   White keeps more space, and his pieces are more active, which gives him a clear advantage. }
