[White "25) 2...Nf6 3.e5 Nd5 4.Nf3 Nc6 Sidelines"]
[Black "4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bc4 Nb6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ It is the most-played move in this position. Black develops his knight and, depending on White's move, decides what pawn to move. }
5. Bc4
{ Attacking the knight on d5 and developing the bishop.  We will see all sidelines here except  5...Nb6  6.Bb3  d6  and  6...d5  , which we will examine in the mainlines. }
5... Nb6
{ The most popular move by a large margin. Black attacks the bishop on c4.   5...Nf4  attacking the pawn on g2 backfires when White ignores it with  6.d4  and Black cannot take  6...Nxg2  as the knight gets trapped after  7.Kf1 }
6. Bb3
{ It is Black who must justify his unnatural moves like Nf6-d5-b6.   Unless he does something concrete, such as waste of tempos to the knight to b6 will not suffice to get an acceptable position. }
6... c4
{ This idea, either before or after d5, is the crux of this system with Nb6.   Black ensures White will not get the b2-c3-d4-e5 pawn chain, as Black intends to take on d3 as soon as White opts for d4. }
7. Bc2
{ Our argument here is we are ahead in development and still have a better center.   How is Black going to finish his development? }
7... Qc7
{ Black attacks the pawn on e5. It is the most-played move in the position.   7...d6  8.exd6  , and @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/1nn5/4P3/2p5/2P2N2/PPBP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...d5  8.exd6  are coveredhere in a separate chapter. }
8. O-O
{ We sacrifice the pawn and play for development. It has been established in modern times that due to this strong sacrifice, White takes over entirely in this variation.  The @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/1nn5/4P3/2p5/2P2N2/PPBP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  line had its time back in the 1996 Olympiad when Ivanchuk won a nice game against Torre, who opted for  8.Qe2  and got the surprise  8...g5  .  A lot of theories later developed in that direction, but none of them are relevant to us as the pawn sacrifice is much stronger. }
8... Nxe5 { There is no other possible way to justify Black's previous moves. }
9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 { We gain another tempo attacking the queen. } 10... Qf6
{ This risky retreat has been tried a few times with an excellent score for White.   The queen remains exposed on f6, and it is just a matter of time before it will be chased again. }
11. a4
{ White cunningly stops Black from playing d5 which is now answered with a5 when the knight must go back to an awkward d7 square, and Black remains hugely underdeveloped.  A sample variation can be  11...d5  12.a5  Nd7  13.d3  cxd3  14.Qxd3  when Black's lack of development is so huge that even the materialistic machines scream +2 for White! }
11... e6 12. d3
{ Now we open up the center and threaten to take the c4-pawn with a5. } 12...
cxd3 13. Qxd3
{ Stopping Nd5 due to the pin on the e-file and threatening a5 to trap the knight.  White's knight has two attractive directions. One aims for the b5 square via a3, and the other is to head for the e4 square via d2. }
13... d5
{ 14...Bc5  15.Qg3  d5  will lead to similar positions like the text move. }
14. Nd2 { Planning Nf3-Bg5. } 14... Bc5 15. Qg3
{ In this move order, we could also start with direct Nf3 with the idea to trap the queen on g5, but Black could always first play Bc5 before we got Nd2 in. It makes sense to have similar setups as and when possible.   Nf3-Bg5/Bf4 is coming next, and computers are giving a winning advantage for White which is not surprising and gets further clarity once we try to find some move for Black😊. }
