8. O-O
{ We sacrifice the pawn and play for development. It has been established in modern times that due to this strong sacrifice, White takes over entirely in this variation.  The @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1ppppp/1nn5/4P3/2p5/2P2N2/PPBP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Qc7  line had its time back in the 1996 Olympiad when Ivanchuk won a nice game against Torre, who opted for  8.Qe2  and got the surprise  8...g5  .  A lot of theories later developed in that direction, but none of them are relevant to us as the pawn sacrifice is much stronger. }
8... Nxe5 { There is no other possible way to justify Black's previous moves. }
9. Nxe5 Qxe5 10. Re1 { We gain another tempo attacking the queen. } 10... Qc7
{ The queen gets back to its safest spot. } 11. a4
{ By now, a well-known refutation of this system does not require any change.  We want to attack the knight with a5, which is practically unstoppable as  11...a5  12.Na3  makes it even worse for Black, with White knight coming to b5 permanently. }
11... e6
{ Black almost exclusively played this move which is understandable as this is the most logical way to ensure Black's king safety.   11...g6  12.a5  Nd5  13.Qf3  almost kills the knight in the center as it cannot go to f6 due to the pin on the e-file.   In the game, Jones - Rowson Black tried  11...d5  12.Na3  a6  and after  13.a5  Nd7  13.d3  the position opened up with the Black king in the center, with no development and White getting an overwhelming advantage. }
12. d3
{ We open up the center.  Sebastian recommends  12.Na3  Bxa3  13.Rxa3  in his course, which also gives White a great position.  However, it is even more precise to wait for Black to commit Be7 before playing Na3 to ensure another loss of tempo😊. }
12... cxd3 13. Qxd3
{ It would be impossible to imagine where the black king can find any safety in this game. }
13... Be7 { How else to develop? } 14. Na3 { Threatening to play Nb5. } 14...
a6 15. a5
{ After taking control of the c4-square, we go for the knight, which now has only one square available. }
15... Nd5 16. Bb3
{ We now want to take the knight on d5 and again force Black to waste another move defending it. }
16... Nf6
{ 16...Qxa5  17.Bxd5  Qxd5  18.Qxd5  exd5  19.Nb5!  gives us a winning position, as Black cannot take on b5 due to the pin on the a8 rook, and  19...Kd8  20.Be3  , with an unstoppable Bb6-Nc7, wins heavy material. }
17. Nc4
{ Black remains paralyzed on the queenside. We intend to play Nb6 next, and trying to stop it with Bc5 would backfire after we go Be3 and change Black's last hope to save him on dark squares.   Black can castle right now, but soon after Nb6, White will also play Bg5-Bc2 attacking h7, and the rooks will join in the battle too.   Engines are giving close to +1 and practically speaking we feel the evaluation should be more as it would take computer precision for Black to maintain +1 position😊. }
