{ Black was practically forced to play this to justify his two previous moves @@StartBracket@@Be7-Bf6@@EndBracket@@.   13...Nxd4  14.Nxf6+  loses a piece. }
14. Nxd4
{ According to engines playing  14.a4  is also powerful, but let us keep it as simple as possible😊.  We take the advantage of having the bishop pair. }
14... Qxd4 15. Qh5
{ For obvious reasons, we do not want to trade queens. Black is underdeveloped, and his king will face a fierce attack soon.   White intends to move the bishop on c1 and gain a tempo with Rad1. }
15... Nd5
{ Trying to bring back the knight to f6, where it can be more helpful in defending the king.  Hoping for a queen trade with  15...Qe5  doesn't work due to  16.Qh4  with the idea of Bf4/Bg5-Nf6 giving a headache to the queen on e5. }
16. Bg5 { Taking away Nf6 ideas and planning Rad1 next. } 16... f6
{ After the greedy  16...Qxb2  17.Rad1  the queen will be further pushed back with Rd2.  The threat of Rd3-h3 also kills Black on the kingside when his pieces are not ready to withstand such a full-fledged attack by White. }
17. Rad1 Qb4 { 17...Qxb2  18.Bc1  Qe5  19.Ng5  loses the queen. } 18. Bc1
{ A fantastic retreat to its original square, but the open diagonal keeps the bishop active.  White intends to play Bc2 next to target the pawn on h7, and  18...Ne5  is answered with  19.Ng5   Once again, Black is just not ready to meet such an attack on the kingside when White is fully prepared and developed, and Black is far away from his majesty. }
