[White "26) 4.Nf3 Nc6 Main Line without ...c4"]
[Black "5.Bc4 Nb6 6.Bb3 d5 7.exd6 e6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5
{ Whether Black plays d6 or d5, it does not make any difference since we respond with exd6 in both cases.  In this chapter, we will be considering all lines for Black after  6...d6  /  6...d5  7.exd6  when Black refrains from playing a quick c4. }
7. exd6 e6 8. O-O Bxd6
{ The most natural recapture, but Black has also taken  8...Qxd6  a couple of times, which is coveredhere. }
9. d4 { Gaining control over the center and opening up the c1 bishop. } 9...
cxd4 { Black wants to play against the IQP and consolidate his position. } 10.
cxd4
{ We give the same argument. The bishop on c8 is bad typically, and with the knight on b6, it gets further worse as it blocks the path of b6-Bb7. }
10... O-O
{ The most obvious and logical move.   Black can play other moves also, but eventually, he will have to castle and we will get a similar position. }
11. Nc3
{ Black's Knight on b6 is stopping c8 Bishop from developing. Let us not forget this detail 😊.  At this point, Black can try a few things, but none give him equality. Let us see his various logical plans. It is very interesting to observe that Sebastian's course on the Alapin ended right here, giving White an edge.   We felt it would be essential to understand the upcoming middlegame and plans as this position is highly likely to come, and Black has tried several moves. }
11... Be7
{ Black wants to come for the d4-pawn by rerouting his bishop to f6. } 12. Re1
{ As usual, we play our natural developing move. } 12... Bf6
{ This position was reached a few times at the GM level.  Most notably in the game Vishnu - Kasimdzhanov from Isle of Man 2017, where White played  13.Re4  to protect the pawn on d4. }
13. Ne4
{ This move is on Black's face when White invites him to take on d4.  The most popular move by a large margin is to protect the pawn with  13.Be3  and the move  13.Re4  has also been tried a few times.   13.Ne4  has not been played on OTB events yet, but there are just a few correspondence games where White had a 100% score. The idea is to make sure we get a double bishop advantage. }
13... Bxd4
{ Black was practically forced to play this to justify his two previous moves @@StartBracket@@Be7-Bf6@@EndBracket@@.   13...Nxd4  14.Nxf6+  loses a piece. }
14. Nxd4
{ According to engines playing  14.a4  is also powerful, but let us keep it as simple as possible😊.  We take the advantage of having the bishop pair. }
14... Nxd4
{ The only two correspondence games that reached this position, and Black took on d4 with the queen.   This move is objectively stronger, eliminating the bishop on b3. }
15. Bg5
{ At this stage, we have three lucrative options. We recommend the one that is most forcing and gives Black more opportunities to go wrong.   However, let's also mention the other two, which also give White a good position to look forward to.   15.Be3  leads us to a nice endgame after  15...Nxb3  16.Qxb3  @@StartBracket@@threatens Rad1-Bc5-Nd6, etc@@EndBracket@@  16...Qh4  17.Bxb6  axb6  18.Qxb6  and White gets a comfortable endgame.   15.Bf4  @@StartBracket@@idea Bd6@@EndBracket@@  15...Nxb3  16.Qxb3  gives White a lovely compensation in the middlegame when his dark-squared bishop remains super active, and the threats on the d-file @@StartBracket@@Rad1/Nd6/Bd6@@EndBracket@@ and on the kingside @@StartBracket@@Qg3/Be5/Bh6@@EndBracket@@ poses Black enough practical troubles.  Engines are giving a very slight edge, and it is impossible to beat them, obviously, but in a practical game, this won't be fun to handle for Black over the board. }
15... f6
{ The only move that does not lose on the spot.   15...Qd7  16.Nf6  gxf6  17.Bxf6  would be an immediate resignation, with a mate coming soon. }
16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Bh6
{ The threat of Qg4 is unstoppable now.  Playing  17...f5  worsens things when the rook joins the attack with  18.Re3  . }
17... Rf7
{ The only move that does not to lose immediately.   17...Nf5  18.Qg4  Kh8  19.Bxf8  Qxf8  20.Bxe6  gets into a position where Black's kingside gets opened up, and White is almost winning, as the attack with major pieces are much more helpful in such an open position compared to having two uncoordinated knights. }
18. Qg4+ Kh8 19. Rad1
{ White goes for the e5 knight that forces Black to play e5 next. } 19... e5
{ 19...Rd7  20.Rxd4  Rxd4  21.Qg7#  won't make Black happy. } 20. Rxd4
{ An easy-to-miss move from a distance. White attacks the Black queen instead of moving his queen. }
20... Bxg4
{ After  20...exd4  21.Qf4  there is no way to protect the rook and stop Qe8 ideas since  21...Rf8  loses to the pretty  22.Bxf8  Qxf8  23.Re8  Qxe8  24.Qxf6# }
21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Bxf7
{ The smoke has cleared, and it ended up having a double bishop advantage, a better pawn structure, and a safer king for us.   In the silicon world, this is enough for winning the game, and in a practical game, it should not be too difficult to convert this advantage to a whole point. }
