[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5
{ Whether Black plays d6 or d5, it does not make any difference since we respond with exd6 in both cases.  In this chapter, we will be considering all lines for Black after  6...d6  /  6...d5  7.exd6  when Black refrains from playing a quick c4. }
7. exd6 e5
{ This is an over-ambitious move.   Black gains more space in the center and wants to take on d6 with his bishop. However, his pieces are not yet ready for direct combat in the center. }
8. d4
{ We are one move away from castling and got better development. We must not shy away from such a direct fight. }
8... c4
{ Black does not want to open up the center entirely and blocks our light-squared bishop.   8...Qxd6  9.dxe5  wins a pawn, and Black does not have enough compensation for the same. }
9. Bc2
{ Our bishops are looking at the open diagonal in the kingside that will make Black's king uncomfortable even after castling. }
9... exd4 10. Nxd4
{ We want a piece on d4 to maximize our development advantage. } 10... Bxd6
{ After  10...Nxd4  11.Qxd4  it will be challenging to develop the f8 bishop due to the attack on g7.  White's domination continues even without queens after  11...Qxd6  12.Be3!  Qxd4  13.Bxd4  and Black's passive pieces are unmatchable with our super active pieces. }
11. Qe2+
{ We are now transforming our development/dynamic advantage to a structural/static advantage.  Machines also give a slight edge after  11.O-O  , keeping the lead in the development and maintaining the initiative. }
11... Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7
{ After  12...Nxe7  13.Nb5  Bb8  14.Be3  or the direct  14.a4  makes Black's life miserable since it will be hard to get proper development on the queenside. }
13. Nxc6 { We break the pawn structure. } 13... bxc6 14. Be4
{ Black will have to keep defending his pathetic pawns on the queenside, and he has zero compensation against it. }
