[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5
{ Whether Black plays d6 or d5, it does not make any difference since we respond with exd6 in both cases.  In this chapter, we will be considering all lines for Black after  6...d6  /  6...d5  7.exd6  when Black refrains from playing a quick c4. }
7. exd6 exd6
{ This anti-positional move became popular when Kasparov used it for one game against Ivanchuk in 1992, Dortmund.   Kasparov himself never used it again, but as it often happens, there were many followers. }
8. d4
{ We have a better center and a better development advantage.   It is OK to stop our analyses here when engines also give the edge to White. Nevertheless, let us see a few more moves to enhance our understanding of the upcoming middlegame. }
8... Bg4
{ The point of Black's play. He pins the knight and puts pressure on the d4-pawn. }
9. h3 { Let Black keep any one useful diagonal, but not both. } 9... Bh5
{ Maintaining the pin. } 10. O-O
{ This move is more direct than  10.Be3  , which was played in the game mentioned before. }
10... Be7 11. dxc5
{ We give up the center and play for better piece placement. } 11... dxc5 12.
Bf4
{ Pay attention to Black's minor pieces. Apart from the bishop on h5, none can be proud of their position. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Qxd1  13.Rxd1  Bxf3  14.gxf3  takes away Black's only active piece and leaves him with all passive minor pieces with no place to go. }
13. Na3
{ Our play is straightforward.   We know Black's minor pieces are restricted, so we want to continue development most effectively. The knight keeps an eye on the b5 and c4 squares for its future jump.   As always, taking on d1 and f3 enhances our advantage, as the last active piece for Black will also be gone. }
