[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5
{ Whether Black plays d6 or d5, it does not make any difference since we respond with exd6 in both cases.  In this chapter, we will be considering all lines for Black after  6...d6  /  6...d5  7.exd6  when Black refrains from playing a quick c4. }
7. exd6 Qxd6
{ Black keeps his structure intact, but the queen on d6 will have to waste another move later to find a safer square. }
8. O-O { We play for rapid development as usual. } 8... Be6
{ Solving the light-squared bishop issue quickly, but delaying the kingside development project.   8...c4  9.Bc2  is coveredhere in the Mainlines with c4 chapter.   8...Bg4  will attract the beautiful  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Ng5  winning back the bishop along with a healthy pawn. }
9. Bxe6
{ We don't mind Black's queen on e6 which will block the natural development of e6-Be7. }
9... Qxe6 10. a4
{ White plays on the queenside to keep Black busy responding there, delaying the castling process. }
10... Qd7
{ Black moves the queen to get the normal development with e6-Be7.   10...Rd8  transposes to the Qd7 line after  11.a5  Nd5  12.a6  b6  13.d4  cxd4  14.Nxd4  .   Black can also play  10...Nd5  but it does not have any independent value after we go  11.a5  and it will eventually transpose to the mainline.   The downside of  10...g6  is visible after  11.a5  Nd5  12.d4  cxd4  13.Nxd4  when recapturing one more time, allows the White queen to get to d4 and attack the h8 rook and poses problems for Black.   Finally, playing  10...a6  or  10...a5  will weaken the b6 and b5 square, respectively, and White knight will eventually find its route to get there via a3. }
11. a5 Nd5 12. a6
{ Getting a solid annoying pawn on a6 that will always be a nuisance for Black in the middlegame and endgame. }
12... b6 13. d4
{ It is time to break the center and not give Black time to complete his development peacefully. }
13... cxd4
{ Black must respond in the center first.  After  13...e6  14.Ne5  Nxe5  14.dxe5  White gets a great space advantage, and it is a matter of time before the d5 knight is kicked away, and White rook will come to d1 with his queen on f3. }
14. Nxd4 Rd8
{ Black once again ignores the kingside and brings the rook into the game. }
15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. Qe2
{ We keep giving threats before Black can touch his kingside, and c4 is coming now. }
16... e6 17. c4
{ Removing the most active piece from its best available square. } 17... Nb4
{ Not the top choice by engines who wants to put the knight on c7 and accept a slightly worse position due to worst placed knight.  We can answer  17...Nc7  with  18.Nc3  and enjoy more space. Ideas like a timely Nb5 in the future to ensure our c4 pawn gets to b5 after the exchange, and play against Black's a7-pawn when in any endgame our pawn on a6 will be potentially dangerous. }
18. Nc3
{ Our knight is more potent than its counterpart as it is untouchable on b5 @@StartBracket@@unlike the knight on b4, which will soon come under our bishop's observation from d2@@EndBracket@@, and it also keeps a constant attack on a7. }
