[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) 4.Nf3 Nc6 Main Line with ...c4"]
[Black "7.exd6 c4 8.Bc2 e5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5 7. exd6 c4
{ We have already covered previous deviations in different chapters. In this chapter, this will be our starting position. }
8. Bc2
{ Can Black claim his pawn on c4 is strong enough to block us from opening the center without making any concessions?   Or is the c4-pawn just a burden for Black that needs more protection? This debate will get more clarity as we move forward. }
8... e5
{ Black wants to take the pawn with his bishop.  The confusing move  8...Bg4  doesn't give Black an acceptable position after  9.h3  Bh5  10.Qe2  Qxd6  11.Na3  when protecting the c4-pawn becomes a nuisance, and supporting it with Na5 puts the knight on the edge when White can focus on casting and playing b3 at the right time to gain total control of the center and the game. }
9. a4
{ A very smart move which is quite typical with the knight on b6.   Black cannot stop White from playing a5 by normal means, and if Black goes for ...a5 it weakens the b5-square, which will be immediately exploited with Na3-b5.   Playing ...Na5 is also not a healthy option when the pawn on e5 hangs. }
9... Bxd6 10. a5 { We are going as per plan. } 10... Nd7
{ Although this move is rarely played compared to the normal-looking Nd5, it requires some precision for White to prove his advantage.  After  10...Nd5  11.d3  cxd3  12.Qxd3  the knight on d5 hangs, and Black cannot castle soon due to the mate on h7.  Anticipating this d3 break, Black puts his knight on d7 to jump to a better square at c5. }
11. d3 { We must not allow Black to get Nc5 before we get this d3 break. }
11... cxd3 12. Qxd3 Nc5
{ That was the point of keeping the knight on d7. Now it disturbs the queen. }
13. Qe3
{ There is no way to attack this queen quickly.   We will soon castle and play b4 to remove the knight. Black must also watch out for ideas like b5-Nxe5 etc, and the White rook will come to d1, and the knight on b1 will head for c4.   Engines give significant advantages already, and the reasoning is straightforward. }
