[Round "?"]
[White "27) 4.Nf3 Nc6 Main Line with ...c4"]
[Black "8.Bc2 Qxd6 9.O-O g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5 7. exd6 c4
{ We have already covered previous deviations in different chapters. In this chapter, this will be our starting position. }
8. Bc2
{ Can Black claim his pawn on c4 is strong enough to block us from opening the center without making any concessions?   Or is the c4-pawn just a burden for Black that needs more protection? This debate will get more clarity as we move forward. }
8... Qxd6
{ 8...e6  9.O-O  transposes to a line we've already examinedhere in the ...Nc6 sidelines chapter.   8...exd6  makes absolutely no sense when White can play O-O and d3, and Black will end up with a pathetic pawn structure.  A sample variation could be  8...exd6  9.O-O  Be7  10.d4  d5  11.a4!  and now Black must either allow White to play a5 and move the knight from b6, thus losing protection from c4, or play a5 and allow Na3-b5 ideas.  In either case, there are too many weaknesses in Black's position. }
9. O-O
{ One of the leading trendy positions of this system.   White keeps his option on the queenside flexible. We can go a4-a5 or break with b3/d3. First, Black must show his intentions with his king.   On which side is it going to hide? }
9... g6
{ The only other sensible move. In this case, Black wants to hide his king on the safer side. }
10. Na3 { Our knight is nicely placed there targeting the c4-pawn. } 10... Bg7
11. b3
{ A typical break that gives us a fantastic center. Once the c4-pawn is removed, our central pawns will roll. }
11... Be6 { Black tries to hold on to the pawn. } 12. Re1 Bd5
{ Getting away from the tactical shot that comes after  12...O-O  when White can play  13.bxc4  Nxc4  14.Rxe6!  Qxe6  15.Bb3  N6a5  16.Nxc4  Nxc4  17.d3  .  Black keeps some compensation and can fight for a draw, but without a doubt, White will be pressing. }
13. Nxc4 { Now we trade everything on c4 to clear our d-pawn's march. } 13...
Nxc4 14. bxc4 Bxc4 15. d4
{ White is better, but it is good to know the next thematic move. } 15... O-O
16. h4
{ A lovely kingside march that becomes tough to handle.   Playing h5 for Black is not attractive as the g5 square gets weakened. Our pawns on c3-d4 nicely restrict the bishop on g7 and the knight on c6. Meanwhile, our bishops are looking at the kingside, and after playing h4, they become ecstatic.   Engines are happy with White, and so are we from the human point of view. It is easier to play this position from the White side. }
