1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5 7. exd6 c4
{ We have already covered previous deviations in different chapters. In this chapter, this will be our starting position. }
8. Bc2
{ Can Black claim his pawn on c4 is strong enough to block us from opening the center without making any concessions?   Or is the c4-pawn just a burden for Black that needs more protection? This debate will get more clarity as we move forward. }
8... Qxd6
{ 8...e6  9.O-O  transposes to a line we've already examinedhere in the ...Nc6 sidelines chapter.   8...exd6  makes absolutely no sense when White can play O-O and d3, and Black will end up with a pathetic pawn structure.  A sample variation could be  8...exd6  9.O-O  Be7  10.d4  d5  11.a4!  and now Black must either allow White to play a5 and move the knight from b6, thus losing protection from c4, or play a5 and allow Na3-b5 ideas.  In either case, there are too many weaknesses in Black's position. }
9. O-O
{ One of the leading trendy positions of this system.   White keeps his option on the queenside flexible. We can go a4-a5 or break with b3/d3. First, Black must show his intentions with his king.   On which side is it going to hide? }
9... g6
{ The only other sensible move. In this case, Black wants to hide his king on the safer side. }
10. Na3 { Our knight is nicely placed there targeting the c4-pawn. } 10... Bg7
11. b3
{ A typical break that gives us a fantastic center. Once the c4-pawn is removed, our central pawns will roll. }
11... cxb3 12. axb3 O-O { The most natural follow-up for Black. } 13. Nc4
{ A rare and more straightforward solution than Sebastian's suggestion of  13.d4  Bg4  14.h3  Bxf3  15.Qxf3  e5  with extensive notes, but we could not find an advantage there, and it is also going for the mainline, where everyone will be more prepared. }
13... Nxc4
{ Sooner or later, Black must take as there is no benefit from keeping White's knight on c4. }
14. bxc4
{ Now Black must respond fast. Otherwise, we will roll over in the center, and Ba3-Re1 will also create problems. }
14... Be6 15. Qe2
{ Black tried two sensible moves here. Both are aiming for the c4-pawn. } 15...
Ne5 16. Nxe5
{ We want to push our pawns at the right time. First, we had to eliminate the knight. }
16... Qxe5
{ It makes sense for Black to trade the queens.  After  16...Bxe5  17.g3  the threat of Ba3 will give away some tempos to White, and as usual, the pawn marching with d4-d5-c5 is always a headache for Black. }
17. Qxe5 Bxe5 18. Re1
{ Gaining a tempo and bringing the rook out in the game. } 18... Bd6
{ The only time this position was reached in a tournament game between Zvjaginsev - Nepomniachtchi, Black kept the bishop in the right place to ensure White won't be able to push c5 quickly while Black kept attacking the c4-pawn. }
19. Be4
{ Attacking the b7-pawn, we are also ready to defend our pawn with d3 as the light-squared bishop is out. }
19... Bxc4 20. Bxb7 Rab8 { The a7-pawn cannot be taken due to Bc5. } 21. Ba6
{ We make sure the a7-pawn won't move from its square quickly. } 21... Bxa6 22.
Rxa6 Rb7 { Black keeps his pawns protected, but they cannot move. } 23. Kf1
{ Until now, we have been following the game mentioned above. This is a simple improvement that gives White a stable advantage.   White exchanged the bishop in the game with Ba3, which was unnecessary. This bishop on d6 will become trouble for Black once we get d4-c4-c5. We are getting ready by bringing our king with Ke2-d4-Kd3 or Ke2-Kd1-Kc2-d4, depending on how Black responds. In either case, our pawns will move forward faster.   Imagine Black playing Ra8-Rb6 when we go Ra5, and then again, Black must go a6-Rb5, and we go Ra4 to frustrate him ultimately.   Meanwhile, our pawns will slowly but surely march forward. We may not win this position in correspondence chess, but it would be super tricky for Black to keep calm and hold it in an OTB game. }
