{ One of the leading trendy positions of this system.   White keeps his option on the queenside flexible. We can go a4-a5 or break with b3/d3. First, Black must show his intentions with his king.   On which side is it going to hide? }
9... Bg4
{ The most tempting/challenging, and dynamic move. Black pins the knight on f3 and intends to castle long to gain more control on the d3-square.   At first glance, this looks awesome, but let's go deeper before concluding anything. }
10. Re1
{ It is essential to refrain from including h3-Bh5, as suggested by Sebastian in his course. The reasoning will get clear later. }
10... e6
{ This move is also, in a way, consistent with the previous move. Black plays e6 only once he got the c8 bishop out. }
11. Na3 { A multipurpose move. We keep threats of Nb5/Qe2/b3 open. } 11... Be7
12. h3 { We go for one of our plans, but first, we kick the bishop out. } 12...
Bh5 13. Qe2 { Going for the c4-pawn. } 13... Qf4
{ 13...Qd5  attracts  14.Be4  and after @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pp2bppp/1nnqp3/7b/2p5/N1P2N1P/PPBPQPP1/R1B1R1K1 b kq - 2 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Qc5  14.b3  , the c4-pawn gets eliminated, and it is a matter of time before the queens get kicked out with d4. }
14. d4 Bxf3
{ After  14...cxd3  15.Qxd3  Black's queen does not have a good place to return. }
15. gxf3
{ Going to the endgame with the bishop-pair advantage seems tempting, but Black will take on a3 after trading queens, and our pawns on the queenside become vulnerable. }
15... Qh4 16. Nxc4
{ Black only has the queen for an attack, while our pieces are fully coordinated. There is no worry on the kingside. }
16... Nxc4 17. Qxc4 { Given a chance, we will protect the h3-pawn with Kg2. }
17... Qxh3 18. d5
{ Engines give many different moves to get an advantage, but this is the simplest. }
18... exd5 19. Qxd5
{ Black must castle, then we have the simple Qf5, which forces queen trade and pawns on both wings our bishops will roar. }
