{ There are no other decent plans available for Black. This is the way Black usually plays in this line. Attacking on f3 and stopping White from playing d3.  After  11...e5  12.h3  Bh5  13.b3  the queenside explodes rapidly, and Black is not on time to generate counterplay on the other side. }
12. Qe2
{ This is a strong and unusual idea for this line. White almost exclusively plays for the b3 break, but here we ruthlessly go for the c4-pawn. }
12... Bxf3
{ The alternatives do not have any independent value as after taking twice on c4, Black will be obliged to take on f3, and we will transpose eventually.   Black cannot get away without making this move sooner or later. }
13. gxf3
{ We are not worried about our king as there are not enough pieces for Black to conduct an attack. Meanwhile, we intend to take on c4 next.   This position is very fresh, and there are too many tempting ideas for Black which backfires completely. It is highly likely that over the board Black will choose the most active moves and get a lost position soon. Especially if we don't blitz out all our moves until here and pretend slightly that we are freestyling on the board 😉.  Let us analyze this position thoroughly to ensure we understand why our king is safe 😉. }
13... Kb8
{ Quite a normal reaction, Black wants to play Ne5 if we take on c4. } 14. Nxc4
{ We bite the bullet. This is our only way to fight for an advantage. } 14...
Nxc4 15. Qxc4
{ How we deal with Ne5 business will get clear in our next move. } 15... Ne5
{ The most challenging way.  After  15...Qxf3  16.Qh4  , we will get our queen to g3, and the unstoppable d4 will ensure Black suffers from a lack of space. }
16. Rxe5
{ Only move, but once again, nothing complicated to spot. We go for the f7-pawn. }
16... Qxe5 17. Qxf7
{ Black's pieces are stuck, and our pieces will come rapidly with d4-Bf4 next. Engines think the only way not to get a losing position for Black is to trade queens!   We could stop our analyses here, but lets us improve our endgame understanding too 😊. }
17... Qf6 { Otherwise, it would be impossible to deal with d4-Bf4 ideas. } 18.
Qxf6 gxf6
{ The best way to recapture. Black cannot allow White to play d4 and have total control of the center. }
19. d4 e5
{ Another only move to not to get a clearly worse position. Black finds the best moves to stay in the game. }
20. Be3
{ We keep total stability in the center. Black must find the only way not to get a horrible position once again. }
20... h5 { Black wants to trade his bad bishop. } 21. Kg2
{ With an amazing idea in mind... } 21... Bh6
{ The inclusion of  21...Rg8  22.Kh3  beats the purpose of Black's idea of h5-Bh6. }
22. f4 { We give up a pawn to get a lovely square on f3. } 22... exf4 23. Bc1
{ What an instructive moment! To activate his king White gave a pawn and lost a couple of tempos too.   It was crucial to return to c1 to avoid any f3-Bxd2 ideas. We won't take the f4-pawn easily. Instead, we want to play Kf3-Bd2 and laugh at the bishop on h6 for the rest of the game.   For engines, the next move is an absolute necessity. }
23... f3+
{ Black must get rid of this bishop. We would not have taken on f4 and set it free otherwise. }
24. Kxf3 Bxc1 25. Rxc1
{ An active king, two pawns for the exchange, and a broken pawn structure at the enemy camp are good enough to get a stable advantage.   This is too far from opening preparation, and unlikely one will get this far @@StartBracket@@especially Black, who had to make many only moves@@EndBracket@@.   However, we could not stop ourselves from showing this brilliant endgame idea which highlights how important it is to have king activity in the endgame 😊. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27) 4.Nf3 Nc6 Main Line with ...c4"]
[Black "8.Bc2 Qxd6 9.O-O Bg4 - 11.b3 Alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 d5 7. exd6 c4
{ We have already covered previous deviations in different chapters. In this chapter, this will be our starting position. }
8. Bc2
{ Can Black claim his pawn on c4 is strong enough to block us from opening the center without making any concessions?   Or is the c4-pawn just a burden for Black that needs more protection? This debate will get more clarity as we move forward. }
8... Qxd6
{ 8...e6  9.O-O  transposes to a line we've already examinedhere in the ...Nc6 sidelines chapter.   8...exd6  makes absolutely no sense when White can play O-O and d3, and Black will end up with a pathetic pawn structure.  A sample variation could be  8...exd6  9.O-O  Be7  10.d4  d5  11.a4!  and now Black must either allow White to play a5 and move the knight from b6, thus losing protection from c4, or play a5 and allow Na3-b5 ideas.  In either case, there are too many weaknesses in Black's position. }
9. O-O
{ One of the leading trendy positions of this system.   White keeps his option on the queenside flexible. We can go a4-a5 or break with b3/d3. First, Black must show his intentions with his king.   On which side is it going to hide? }
9... Bg4
{ The most tempting/challenging, and dynamic move. Black pins the knight on f3 and intends to castle long to gain more control on the d3-square.   At first glance, this looks awesome, but let's go deeper before concluding anything. }
10. Re1
{ It is essential to refrain from including h3-Bh5, as suggested by Sebastian in his course. The reasoning will get clear later. }
10... O-O-O
{ Consistent with Black's previous move. Black ensures White cannot push the d-pawn.   10...Qf6  11.Be4  O-O-O  12.a4  gets Black to a position where he cannot simultaneously take care of a5/b3/d4 threats, and the position opens up on the queenside, exposing his king. }
11. b3
{ This move is more dynamic and risky but poses many complex/practical problems to Black. }
11... Qf6
{ Once again, this is Black's only way to counter. It is good to note that  11...Ne5  loses instantly to  12.Bf5  when Black's attack disappears, and our attack becomes unstoppable with queenside getting opened up. }
12. bxc4
{ Almost unheard of! We take the pawn and intend to play d4/Be4 next.  Sebastian recommends Na3 here from a different move order, including h3-Bh5 on the move ten. Let us see why that does not work.  12.h3  Bh5  @@StartBracket@@just to reconstruct the position, we use this move order@@EndBracket@@  13.Na3  and we are back to Sebastian's course.  Here he gave a long line with  13...Nd5  14.Nxc4  b5  15.Be4  bxc4  16.Qe2  Ne5  17.g4  Nf4  18.Qe3  Nxf3  19.Bxf3  Nxh3  20.Kg2  and in the game Kraus - Horvath, Vienna 2022, Black refuted this line with  20...Rd3  , which wasn't mentioned in the course.  White must be precise not to lose in this position, which Kraus did not manage in the game, and Black won easily. }
12... Bxf3
{ Black's best response again is to break White's pawn structure. Black cannot get away without playing this move sooner or later. }
13. gxf3
{ A new concept!  We challenge Black to show his attacking skills on the kingside and claim that he does not have enough pieces to generate a good attack.  Trading the queens with  13.Qxf3  ensures safety but also gives Black a comfortable position. }
13... e6
{ Black opens up his bishop but keeps the e5-square available for his knight and the bishop on d6 remains open to attack on h2. }
14. Be4
{ We don't rush with  14.d4  when engines find some bizarre draw after  14...Nxd4  .  First, we bring the bishop to the center. }
14... Nxc4
{ 14...Bd6  15.d4  Nxc4  transposes to this line and  15...Qh4  16.f4  allows White to get his queen to f3, stopping all attacks and keeping the double bishop advantage with a great center.   14...Qg5  15.Kh1  Qh5  16.d4  Bd6  17.f4  ensures the queen trade, and White enjoys a double bishop advantage with a better center. }
15. d4 { Keeping complete control in the center. } 15... Bd6
{ Black's only bet is to go for the h2-pawn. } 16. Nd2
{ Our king is very safe on f1, so we don't have to bother about any Qg5 ideas. }
16... Nb6
{ Black keeps the b7-pawn secured.   16...N4a5  17.Rb1  Qh4  18.Nf1  gives White stability on the kingside while maintaining a good center and attacking prospect on the queenside. }
17. Bxc6 { It is time to break Black's pawn structure. } 17... Qg6+
{ This is what Black was counting on. To get Qd3 in case White goes for Kf1. }
18. Kh1 bxc6
{ After  18...Qh5  19.Bxb7  Kxb7  20.Nf1  White remains a healthy pawn up with no attack for Black. }
19. Ne4
{ Black's king got more exposed and White will play f4-Qf3 next when our attack starts and Black's attack is over. }
*

