13... e5 { Taking control in the center and stopping us from playing d4. } 14.
d3
{ The bishop is bad on c2, but that is temporary.   We are a pawn up and Nd2-e4 is on the way, Black must prove his compensation here. }
14... Qh4
{ Black must be cunning enough to avoid the trap set by us.   14...Nxc4  looks like a typical move, but after the brilliant  15.f4  the knight on c4 comes into danger due to the Qg4-dxc4 threat.  15...Qg6  16.Kh1  doesn't help as now d4 becomes a serious threat attacking the queen on g6 and striking in the center. }
15. Nd2
{ For engines, there are many ways for White to fight for the advantage, and  15.Re4  and  15.f4  are two more interesting options.  We felt the text move is the simplest to understand and deal with over the board. We bring the knight into the game. }
15... f5 { Black stops Ne4 and intends to play Bd6-e4 next. } 16. Kh1
{ We want total stability on the kingside with Rg1-Nf1.   Let's not forget we are a pawn up and have a double bishop advantage. }
16... Bd6
{ Engine top choice is to play  16...g6  😊. Good luck finding and understanding that.  It still gives a slight edge to white with  17.Rg1  with the idea of Nf1 that is very clear to understand. }
17. Rg1 { We are just in time to get Nf1 to protect the h2-pawn. } 17... e4 18.
Nf1
{ This Karpov-like play, with all the pieces barely on their second rank yet, super effective, is quite instructive. }
18... exd3 19. Qxd3
{ We still keep the extra pawn with the double bishop advantage and give threats of Qxf5/Bg5.   White is clearly better at this point. }
